{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_812065", "question": "two digits in father ' s age are the same as the digit in the son ' s age , but in reverse order . in 5 years father will be twice as old as son will be then . what is the difference in their current age ?", "answer": "Let's denote the father's age as \\( F \\) and the son's age as \\( S \\). Since the digits in the father's age are the same as the digits in the son's age but in reverse order, we can express their ages as follows:\n\nIf the father's age is \\( F \\), then it can be expressed as \\( 10a + b \\) where \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) are the tens and units digits, respectively.\nIf the son's age is \\( S \\), then it can be expressed as \\( 10b + a \\) since the digits are reversed.\n\nIn 5 years, the father will be \\( F + 5 \\) years old and the son will be \\( S + 5 \\) years old. At that time, the father will be twice as old as the son, so we can write the equation:\n\n\\[ F + 5 = 2(S + 5) \\]\n\nSubstituting \\( F \\) and \\( S \\) with \\( 10a + b \\) and \\( 10b + a \\) respectively, we get:\n\n\\[ 10a + b + 5 = 2(10b + a + 5) \\]\n\\[ 10a + b + 5 = 20b + 2a + 10 \\]\n\\[ 8a - 19b = 5 \\]\n\nSince \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) are digits, they must be between 0 and 9. We need to find a combination of \\( a \\) and \\( b \\) that satisfies the equation and makes sense for the ages of a father and son.\n\nLet's try to find a solution by testing possible values for \\( a \\) and \\( b \\):\n\nFor \\( a = 1 \\), the equation becomes \\( 8 - 19b = 5 \\), which has no positive integer solution for \\( b \\).\nFor \\( a = 2 \\), the equation becomes \\( 16 - 19b = 5 \\), which also has no positive integer solution for \\( b \\).\nFor \\( a = 3 \\), the equation becomes \\( 24 - 19b = 5 \\), which gives \\( b = 1 \\).\n\nSo, the father's age \\( F \\) is \\( 10 \\times 3 + 1 = 31 \\) and the son's age \\( S \\) is \\( 10 \\times 1 + 3 = 13 \\).\n\nThe difference in their current ages is \\( F - S = 31 - 13 = 18 \\) years."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_177134", "question": "A man intends to complete a journey of 24 km in x hours. If he travels at a speed of 4km/hr for the first four hours, at what speed does he need to travel for the remainder of the journey to be right on time?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 2, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "The man intends to complete a journey of 24 km in x hours.\nHe travels at a speed of 4 km/hr for the first four hours, so he covers a distance of 4 km/hr * 4 hr = 16 km.\nThe remaining distance he needs to cover is 24 km - 16 km = 8 km.\nHe needs to cover this remaining distance in x - 4 hours.\nTo find the speed he needs to travel for the remainder of the journey, we can use the formula:\nspeed = distance / time\nSubstituting 8 km for \"distance\" and x - 4 hours for \"time\", we get:\nspeed = 8 km / (x - 4) hr\nWe are given that the speed he needs to travel for the remainder of the journey is 2 km/hr, so we can write:\n2 km/hr = 8 km / (x - 4) hr\nCross multiplying, we get:\n2 km/hr * (x - 4) hr = 8 km\n2(x - 4) = 8\nSimplifying, we get:\n2x - 8 = 8\n2x = 16\nDividing both sides by 2, we get:\nx = 8\nThe value of x is 8.\n#### 8\nThe answer is: 8"}
