{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_977784", "question": "Write a C++ program that implements a simple calculator supporting addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operations. The program should use a command-line interface where users can input expressions like \"5 + 3\" or \"9 / 2\", and it should output the result.\nPLAINFORMAT", "answer": "#include <iostream>\n#include <sstream>\n\nint main() {\n    double num1, num2;\n    char operation;\n\n    std::cout << \"Enter an expression (e.g., 5 + 3): \";\n    std::string input;\n    getline(std::cin, input);\n\n    std::stringstream ss(input);\n    ss >> num1 >> operation >> num2;\n\n    // Perform the specified operation and output the result\n    switch (operation) {\n        case '+':\n            std::cout << \"Result: \" << num1 + num2 << std::endl;\n            break;\n        case '-':\n            std::cout << \"Result: \" << num1 - num2 << std::endl;\n            break;\n        case '*':\n            std::cout << \"Result: \" << num1 * num2 << std::endl;\n            break;\n        case '/':\n            if (num2 == 0) {\n                std::cout << \"Error: Division by zero\" << std::endl;\n            } else {\n                std::cout << \"Result: \" << num1 / num2 << std::endl;\n            }\n            break;\n        default:\n            std::cout << \"Error: Invalid operation\" << std::endl;\n            break;\n    }\n\n    return 0;\n}"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_73384", "question": "A distributor sells a product through an online store, which takes a commission of 20% of the price set by the distributor. The distributor obtains the product from a producer at the price of $17 per item. If the distributor wants to maintain a 20% profit on the cost of the item, what is the price that the buyer observes online?", "answer": "First, let's calculate the price the distributor needs to set to maintain a 20% profit on the cost of the item.\n\nThe cost of the item is $17. To calculate the 20% profit, we multiply the cost by 20% (or 0.20):\n\nProfit = Cost * Profit Percentage\nProfit = $17 * 0.20\nProfit = $3.40\n\nNow, we add this profit to the cost to find the price the distributor needs to set:\n\nPrice Set by Distributor = Cost + Profit\nPrice Set by Distributor = $17 + $3.40\nPrice Set by Distributor = $20.40\n\nHowever, the online store takes a 20% commission on the price set by the distributor. So, we need to find a price that, after the 20% commission is taken out, leaves the distributor with $20.40.\n\nLet's denote the final price that the buyer observes online as P. The online store takes 20% of P as commission, so the distributor receives 80% of P (which is 100% - 20% commission).\n\nWe can set up the equation as follows:\n\n0.80 * P = $20.40\n\nNow, we solve for P:\n\nP = $20.40 / 0.80\nP = $25.50\n\nTherefore, the price that the buyer observes online should be $25.50 to ensure the distributor maintains a 20% profit on the cost of the item after the online store's commission."}
