{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1287512", "question": "two years ago , john put $ 5000 into a savings account . at the end of the first year , his account had accrued $ 500 in interest bringing his total balance to $ 5500 . the next year , his account balance increased by 10 % . at the end of the two years , by what percent has john ' s account balance increased from his initial deposit of $ 5000 ?", "answer": "At the end of the first year, John's account balance was $5500 after accruing $500 in interest.\n\nIn the second year, his account balance increased by 10%. To find the new balance, we calculate 10% of $5500 and add it to the existing balance:\n\n10% of $5500 = 0.10 * $5500 = $550\n\nAdding this to the previous balance:\n\n$5500 + $550 = $6050\n\nNow, to find the percentage increase from his initial deposit of $5000 to the balance at the end of two years ($6050), we use the formula for percentage increase:\n\nPercentage Increase = [(Final Amount - Initial Amount) / Initial Amount] * 100\n\nPlugging in the values:\n\nPercentage Increase = [($6050 - $5000) / $5000] * 100\nPercentage Increase = [$1050 / $5000] * 100\nPercentage Increase = 0.21 * 100\nPercentage Increase = 21%\n\nSo, John's account balance has increased by 21% from his initial deposit of $5000 after two years."}
