{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_497206", "question": "Zach baked cookies for a bake sale. On Monday he baked 32 cookies. On Tuesday he ran out of sugar and could only bake half of the number of cookies he baked the day before. On Wednesday he baked three times the number of cookies he did on Tuesday, but his brother ate x of those cookies. How many cookies did he have at the end of the three days?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 92, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "On Monday Zach baked 32 cookies.\nOn Tuesday he baked half of the number of cookies he baked on Monday, which means he baked 32/2 = 16 cookies.\nOn Wednesday he baked three times the number of cookies he did on Tuesday, which means he baked 3*16 = 48 cookies.\nBut his brother ate x of those cookies, so the number of cookies he had left is 48 - x.\nThe total number of cookies he had at the end of the three days is the sum of the cookies he baked on Monday, Tuesday, and the cookies he had left on Wednesday: 32 + 16 + (48 - x) = 96 - x.\nWe are given that the total number of cookies he had is 92, so we can write: 96 - x = 92.\nSolving for x, we get: x = 4.\nThe value of x is 4.\n#### 4\nThe answer is: 4"}
