{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_884396", "question": "How can I implement a Java method that finds all pairs of numbers in a given array which sum up to a specified number?", "answer": "You can use the following code example to implement the desired functionality. \n\n```java\nimport java.util.HashSet;\n\npublic class ArrayPairs {  \n    public static void main(String[] args) { \n        int[] arr = {1, 3, 4, 6};\n        findAllPairs(arr, 8);\n    }  \n    \n    static void findAllPairs(int[] arr, int sum) { \n        // Store results \n        HashSet<String> pairs = new HashSet<String>(); \n  \n        // Consider each element of the array\n        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) { \n            int target = sum - arr[i]; \n  \n            // If a valid pair is found \n            if (target >= 0) { \n                // Store the result \n                pairs.add(\"(\" + arr[i] + \", \" + target + \")\"); \n            } \n        } \n  \n        // Print the result \n        System.out.println(pairs); \n    } \n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we define a method called `findAllPairs` that takes an array and a target sum as parameters. Inside the method, we use a `HashSet` called `pairs` to store the resulting pairs of numbers. \n\nWe iterate through each element of the array using a `for` loop. For each element, we calculate the difference between the target sum and the current element (`target = sum - arr[i]`). If the `target` is greater than or equal to 0, we add the pair consisting of the current element and the `target` to the `pairs` set.\n\nFinally, we print the contents of the `pairs` set, which gives us all the pairs of numbers in the array that sum up to the given target. In the provided example, the output would be `[(6, 2), (4, 4)]`."}
