{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_712680", "question": "walking at 4 / 5 of her normal speed , a worker is 15 minutes later than usual in reaching her office . the usual time ( in minutes ) taken by her to cover the distance between her home and her office is", "answer": "Let's denote the usual speed of the worker as \\( S \\) and the usual time taken to reach the office as \\( T \\). The distance between her home and her office is the same regardless of her speed, so we can denote it as \\( D \\).\n\nUnder normal circumstances, the worker's time to reach the office is \\( T \\), and the distance covered is \\( D \\). So, we have the equation:\n\\[ D = S \\times T \\]\n\nWhen the worker walks at \\( \\frac{4}{5} \\) of her normal speed, her speed becomes \\( \\frac{4}{5}S \\). Let's denote the new time taken to reach the office as \\( T' \\). The worker is 15 minutes later than usual, so \\( T' = T + 15 \\) minutes.\n\nThe distance is still the same, so we have:\n\\[ D = \\left(\\frac{4}{5}S\\right) \\times (T + 15) \\]\n\nSince the distance \\( D \\) doesn't change, we can set the two equations equal to each other:\n\\[ S \\times T = \\left(\\frac{4}{5}S\\right) \\times (T + 15) \\]\n\nNow we can solve for \\( T \\):\n\\[ S \\times T = \\frac{4}{5}S \\times T + \\frac{4}{5}S \\times 15 \\]\n\nDivide both sides by \\( S \\) to cancel it out:\n\\[ T = \\frac{4}{5}T + 12 \\]\n\nNow, subtract \\( \\frac{4}{5}T \\) from both sides to get \\( T \\) on one side:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5}T = 12 \\]\n\nMultiply both sides by 5 to solve for \\( T \\):\n\\[ T = 12 \\times 5 \\]\n\\[ T = 60 \\]\n\nSo, the usual time taken by the worker to cover the distance between her home and her office is 60 minutes."}
