{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1414397", "question": "How can I determine how many times a specific substring occurs within a string in Python? I have a string '000123000123' and I want to find how many times '123' occurs in it. Currently, I tried to implement a while loop to achieve this but I'm stuck in an infinite loop. Here is my current code:\n\n```python\nnStr = '000123000123'\npattern = '123'\ncount = a = 0\nwhile pattern in nStr[a:]:\n    a = nStr[a:].find(pattern)+1\n    count += 1\nreturn count\n```\n\nI was informed that count is a better way to do it, however, I am curious if there's a way to do it similar to what I have already done.", "answer": "Your current approach is almost correct, but the issue is with the updating of variable 'a'. The find method returns the lowest index of the substring if found in the given string. When you add 1 to it, it starts searching from the next character of the first occurrence and that's why it's going into an infinite loop when the substring is found at the last index. You need to add the length of the pattern to 'a' instead of adding 1. Here's the corrected code:\n\n```python\nnStr = '000123000123'\npattern = '123'\ncount = a = 0\nwhile pattern in nStr[a:]:\n    a = nStr[a:].find(pattern) + len(pattern)\n    count += 1\nprint(count)\n```\n\nHowever, a more pythonic way to achieve this would be to use the count method which returns the number of occurrences of a substring in the given string:\n\n```python\nnStr = '000123000123'\npattern = '123'\nprint(nStr.count(pattern))\n```\n\nBoth of these code snippets will return 2 as '123' occurs twice in '000123000123'."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1427702", "question": "Let $x_1,$ $x_2,$ $x_3$ be positive real numbers such that $x_1 + 2x_2 + 3x_3 = 60.$  Find the smallest possible value of\n\\[x_1^2 + x_2^2 + x_3^2.\\]", "answer": "By Cauchy-Schwarz,\n\\[(1 + 4 + 9)(x_1^2 + x_2^2 + x_3^2) \\ge (x_1 + 2x_2 + 3x_3)^2 = 60^2,\\]so $x_1^2 + x_2^2 + x_3^2 \\ge \\frac{3600}{14} = \\frac{1800}{7}.$\n\nEquality occurs when $x_1 = \\frac{x_2}{2} = \\frac{x_3}{3}$ and $x_1 + 2x_2 + 3x_3 = 60.$  We can solve, to find $x_1 = \\frac{30}{7},$ $x_2 = \\frac{60}{7},$ and $x_3 = \\frac{90}{7}.$  Hence, the smallest possible value is $\\boxed{\\frac{1800}{7}}.$. The answer is \\frac{1800}{7}"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_859542", "question": "I'm having an issue with my Go code for a password authentication library. The main idea is to have two functions, Check() and New(), both taking a password and a 256-bit HMAC key as inputs. The Check() function also takes a 256-bit salt and hash as inputs, and returns a boolean value. The New() function generates a new random salt and its corresponding hash. Both functions depend on a helper function called hash(), which uses scrypt to extend the key length and generate the final hash output.\n\nInitially, this code was working fine, as I have test data generated by an earlier version of the code. However, I recently noticed that the Check() function fails when provided with data generated by the New() function, even though both functions use the same underlying hash() function.\n\nI understand that I should have used version control from the beginning, but unfortunately I didn't. Now I've learned my lesson.\n\nI've included all the functions and a quick demonstration of the problem in one .go file below, along with some debug output:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n    \"code.google.com/p/go.crypto/scrypt\"\n    \"crypto/hmac\"\n    \"crypto/rand\"\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"crypto/subtle\"\n    \"errors\"\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"io\"\n)\n\n// Constants for scrypt. See code.google.com/p/go.crypto/scrypt\nconst (\n    KEYLENGTH = 32\n    N         = 16384\n    R         = 8\n    P         = 1\n)\n\n// hash takes an HMAC key, a password, and a salt (as byte slices)\n// It uses scrypt to transform the password and salt, then applies HMAC to the result.\n// Returns the resulting 256-bit hash.\nfunc hash(hmk, pw, s []byte) (h []byte, err error) {\n    sch, err := scrypt.Key(pw, s, N, R, P, KEYLENGTH)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    hmh := hmac.New(sha256.New, hmk)\n    hmh.Write(sch)\n    h = hmh.Sum(nil)\n    hmh.Reset() // Probably not necessary\n    return h, nil\n}\n\n// Check takes an HMAC key, a hash to check, a password, and a salt (as byte slices)\n// It calls the hash() function.\n// Compares the resulting 256-bit hash against the check hash and returns a boolean.\nfunc Check(hmk, h, pw, s []byte) (chk bool, err error) {\n    // Print the input hash\n    fmt.Printf(\"Hash: %x\\nHMAC: %x\\nSalt: %x\\nPass: %x\\n\", h, hmk, s, []byte(pw))\n    hchk, err := hash(hmk, pw, s)\n    if err != nil {\n        return false, err\n    }\n    // Print the hash to compare against\n    fmt.Printf(\"Hchk: %x\\n\", hchk)\n    if subtle.ConstantTimeCompare(h, hchk) != 1 {\n        return false, errors.New(\"Error: Hash verification failed\")\n    }\n    return true, nil\n}\n\n// New takes an HMAC key and a password (as byte slices)\n// It generates a new salt using \"crypto/rand\"\n// It calls the hash() function.\n// Returns the resulting 256-bit hash and salt.\nfunc New(hmk, pw []byte) (h, s []byte, err error) {\n    s = make([]byte, KEYLENGTH)\n    _, err = io.ReadFull(rand.Reader, s)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, nil, err\n    }\n    h, err = hash(pw, hmk, s)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, nil, err\n    }\n    fmt.Printf(\"Hash: %x\\nSalt: %x\\nPass: %x\\n\", h, s, []byte(pw))\n    return h, s, nil\n}\n\nfunc main() {\n    // Known values that work\n    pass := \"pleaseletmein\"\n\n    hash := []byte{\n        0x6f, 0x38, 0x7b, 0x9c, 0xe3, 0x9d, 0x9, 0xff,\n        0x6b, 0x1c, 0xc, 0xb5, 0x1, 0x67, 0x1d, 0x11,\n        0x8f, 0x72, 0x78, 0x85, 0xca, 0x6, 0x50, 0xd0,\n        0xe6, 0x8b, 0x12, 0x9c, 0x9d, 0xf4, 0xcb, 0x29,\n    }\n\n    salt := []byte{\n        0x77, 0xd6, 0x57, 0x62, 0x38, 0x65, 0x7b, 0x20,\n        0x3b, 0x19, 0xca, 0x42, 0xc1, 0x8a, 0x4, 0x97,\n        0x48, 0x44, 0xe3, 0x7, 0x4a, 0xe8, 0xdf, 0xdf,\n        0xfa, 0x3f, 0xed, 0xe2, 0x14, 0x42, 0xfc, 0xd0,\n    }\n\n    hmac := []byte{\n        0x70, 0x23, 0xbd, 0xcb, 0x3a, 0xfd, 0x73, 0x48,\n        0x46, 0x1c, 0x6, 0xcd, 0x81, 0xfd, 0x38, 0xeb,\n        0xfd, 0xa8, 0xfb, 0xba, 0x90, 0x4f, 0x8e, 0x3e,\n        0xa9, 0xb5, 0x43, 0xf6, 0x54, 0x5d, 0xa1, 0xf2,\n    }\n\n    // Check the known values. This works.\n    fmt.Println(\"Checking known values...\")\n    chk, err := Check(hmac, hash, []byte(pass), salt)\n    if err != nil {\n        fmt.Printf(\"%s\\n\", err)\n    }\n    fmt.Printf(\"%t\\n\", chk)\n\n    fmt.Println()\n\n    // Create new hash and salt from the known HMAC and Salt\n    fmt.Println(\"Creating new hash and salt values...\")\n    h, s, err := New(hmac, []byte(pass))\n    if err != nil {\n        fmt.Printf(\"%s\\n\", err)\n    }\n\n    // Check the new values. This fails!\n    fmt.Println(\"Checking new hash and salt values...\")\n    chk, err = Check(hmac, h, []byte(pass), s)\n    if err != nil {\n        fmt.Printf(\"%s\\n\", err)\n    }\n    fmt.Printf(\"%t\\n\", chk)\n}\n```\n\nI've tested this code on both Linux 64-bit and Windows 8 64-bit, and it fails on both platforms.\n\nAny help would be greatly appreciated! I had this working at some point, but it seems like I broke something along the way. I only discovered the issue while writing unit tests, which is what they're for, I suppose!\n\nThanks,\nMike.", "answer": "It seems like the issue lies in the mismatched arguments to the hash() function in your Check() and New() functions. In Check(), you have:\n\n```go\nhchk, err := hash(hmk, pw, s)\n```\n\nWhile in New(), you have:\n\n```go\nh, err = hash(pw, hmk, s)\n```\n\nThese different argument orders will produce different results, leading to the verification failure.\n\nMistakes like this are common when dealing with multiple arguments of the same type. It might be worth considering restructuring your code to prevent these types of errors, such as using structs instead of multiple arguments.\n\nI hope this helps you resolve the issue. Let me know if you have any further questions!"}
