{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_467223", "question": "A certain sum is invested at simple interest at 18% p.a. for two years instead of investing at 12% p.a. for the same time period. The sum is Rs. 4000. How much more interest is received by investing at 18% p.a. instead of 12% p.a.?", "answer": "To calculate the interest received at 18% p.a. and 12% p.a., we can use the formula for simple interest:\n\nSimple Interest (SI) = Principal (P) × Rate (R) × Time (T) / 100\n\nFirst, let's calculate the interest received at 18% p.a. for two years:\n\nP = Rs. 4000\nR = 18% p.a.\nT = 2 years\n\nSI at 18% p.a. = (4000 × 18 × 2) / 100\nSI at 18% p.a. = (4000 × 36) / 100\nSI at 18% p.a. = 144000 / 100\nSI at 18% p.a. = Rs. 1440\n\nNow, let's calculate the interest received at 12% p.a. for two years:\n\nP = Rs. 4000\nR = 12% p.a.\nT = 2 years\n\nSI at 12% p.a. = (4000 × 12 × 2) / 100\nSI at 12% p.a. = (4000 × 24) / 100\nSI at 12% p.a. = 96000 / 100\nSI at 12% p.a. = Rs. 960\n\nNow, to find out how much more interest is received by investing at 18% p.a. instead of 12% p.a., we subtract the interest at 12% p.a. from the interest at 18% p.a.:\n\nMore Interest = SI at 18% p.a. - SI at 12% p.a.\nMore Interest = Rs. 1440 - Rs. 960\nMore Interest = Rs. 480\n\nTherefore, by investing at 18% p.a. instead of 12% p.a., an additional interest of Rs. 480 is received."}
