{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_637034", "question": "What is the value of the expression $213_{8} - 142_{7}$ when converted to base 10?", "answer": "To convert $213_{8}$ to base 10, we use the formula $a_{n} \\cdot 8^{n} + a_{n-1} \\cdot 8^{n-1} + \\ldots + a_{0} \\cdot 8^{0}$,\nwhere $a_{n}, a_{n-1}, \\ldots, a_{0}$ are the digits of the number. In this case, we have $2 \\cdot 8^{2} + 1 \\cdot 8^{1} + 3 \\cdot 8^{0} = 2 \\cdot 64 + 1 \\cdot 8 + 3 \\cdot 1 = 128 + 8 + 3 = 139$.\nTo convert $142_{7}$ to base 10, we use the formula $a_{n} \\cdot 7^{n} + a_{n-1} \\cdot 7^{n-1} + \\ldots + a_{0} \\cdot 7^{0}$,\nwhere $a_{n}, a_{n-1}, \\ldots, a_{0}$ are the digits of the number. In this case, we have $1 \\cdot 7^{2} + 4 \\cdot 7^{1} + 2 \\cdot 7^{0} = 1 \\cdot 49 + 4 \\cdot 7 + 2 \\cdot 1 = 49 + 28 + 2 = 79$.\nSo the expression $213_{8} - 142_{7}$ is equal to $139 - 79 = \\boxed{60}$ when converted to base 10.\nThe answer is: 60"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_252159", "question": "Examine the following list of integers and eliminate any numerals which are exact multiples of the value four. Additionally, if a number is a prime, multiply it by two before removing. Consider computational efficiency.\nlist_int = [2,4,6,10]", "answer": "Here is a Python solution for you following the provided specifications:\n\n```python\ndef is_prime(n):\n    if n <= 1:\n        return False\n    if n == 2:\n        return True\n    if n % 2 == 0: \n        return False\n    i = 3\n    while i * i <= n:\n        if n % i == 0:\n            return False\n        i += 2\n    return True\n\ndef process_list(lst):\n    processed_list = []\n    for num in lst:\n        # If the number is a multiple of 4, ignore it\n        if num % 4 == 0:\n            continue\n        # If the number is prime, multiply it by 2\n        if is_prime(num):\n            processed_list.append(num * 2)\n        else:\n            processed_list.append(num)\n    return processed_list\n\nlist_int = [2,4,6,10]\nnew_list = process_list(list_int)\nprint(new_list)\n```\n\nIn this code, function `is_prime(n)` checks whether a number n is prime. The `process_list(lst)` function goes through all numbers in the input list. If a number is a multiple of 4, it's not included in the new list. If a number is prime, it's multiplied by 2 before being included in the new list.\n\nWhen run against the provided list `[2,4,6,10]`, the output will be `[4,6]`, since 2 is a prime number and is doubled, 4 is discounted since it is a multiple of four, 6 passes through unaltered since it is not a prime number and not a multiple of 4, and 10 also passes through unaltered under the same conditions."}
