{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1105730", "question": "Looks like CSS selector that checks if my React input has value doesn't work correctly. I want it to assign color to gray when the value is an empty string and to black when its not empty, however even if I will write something in it it applies the style for an empty value even though it already has some value. Is there a fix to that?", "answer": "One possible solution is to use a combination of CSS and JavaScript to achieve the desired functionality. \n\nIn your CSS file, you can define two classes that represent the two different styles you want to apply based on the input value:\n\n```css\n.gray {\n  color: gray;\n}\n\n.black {\n  color: black;\n}\n```\n\nThen, in your React component, you can add a `className` attribute to your input element and conditionally assign the appropriate class based on the input value using JavaScript:\n\n```jsx\nimport React, { useState } from 'react';\nimport './App.css';\n\nfunction App() {\n  const [inputValue, setInputValue] = useState('');\n\n  const handleInputChange = (event) => {\n    setInputValue(event.target.value);\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <div className=\"App\">\n      <input\n        type=\"text\"\n        value={inputValue}\n        onChange={handleInputChange}\n        className={inputValue === '' ? 'gray' : 'black'}\n      />\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\nexport default App;\n```\n\nWith this setup, the input text will be displayed in gray if the input value is an empty string, and in black if it is not empty. This way, the correct styles will be applied based on the input value."}
