{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1348969", "question": "A 300 metre long train crosses a platform in 39 seconds while it crosses a post in 18 seconds. What is the length of the platform?", "answer": "Let's denote the length of the platform as \\( L \\).\n\nWhen the train crosses a post, it only needs to cover its own length because the post has negligible width compared to the length of the train. So, the time it takes to cross the post (18 seconds) is the time it takes for the train to cover a distance equal to its own length (300 metres).\n\nThe speed of the train (\\( V \\)) can be calculated using the formula:\n\\[ V = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Time}} \\]\n\nSo, when crossing the post:\n\\[ V = \\frac{300 \\text{ metres}}{18 \\text{ seconds}} \\]\n\\[ V = \\frac{300}{18} \\text{ metres/second} \\]\n\\[ V = \\frac{50}{3} \\text{ metres/second} \\]\n\nWhen the train crosses the platform, it has to cover the distance equal to the sum of its own length and the length of the platform. The time it takes to cross the platform is 39 seconds.\n\nSo, the total distance covered when crossing the platform is:\n\\[ \\text{Distance} = 300 \\text{ metres} + L \\]\n\nUsing the speed we found earlier, we can set up the equation:\n\\[ V = \\frac{300 \\text{ metres} + L}{39 \\text{ seconds}} \\]\n\nSubstituting the value of \\( V \\) we found:\n\\[ \\frac{50}{3} = \\frac{300 + L}{39} \\]\n\nNow, we solve for \\( L \\):\n\\[ 39 \\times \\frac{50}{3} = 300 + L \\]\n\\[ 650 = 300 + L \\]\n\\[ L = 650 - 300 \\]\n\\[ L = 350 \\text{ metres} \\]\n\nTherefore, the length of the platform is 350 metres."}
