{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1469476", "question": "Write a Python function that not only sorts a given list of numbers in ascending order using the Bubble Sort algorithm, but does an optimized version of bubble sort that keeps track of the last occurrence of an interchange to improve the running time. This function should also track and return the number of swaps made during the sorting process. \n\nIn addition to that, make the function robust by including exception handling for non-numeric inputs and empty lists. The function should be able to handle a list of arbitrary numeric inputs (integers, floats) and preserve their types in the sorted list. \n\nThe function should return a tuple with 2 elements: the sorted list and the total swap count.", "answer": "Here is the implemented function:\n\n```python\ndef optimized_bubble_sort(nums):\n    try:\n        if len(nums) == 0:\n            return \"Error: List is empty\"\n        if not all(isinstance(num, (int, float)) for num in nums):\n            return \"Error: List contains non-numeric elements\"\n        n = len(nums)\n        swap_count = 0\n        while n > 0:\n            new_n = 0\n            for i in range(1, n):\n                if nums[i-1] > nums[i]:\n                    nums[i-1], nums[i] = nums[i], nums[i-1]\n                    swap_count += 1\n                    new_n = i\n            n = new_n\n        return nums, swap_count\n    except TypeError:\n        return \"Error: Input should be a list of numbers\"\n\n# Testing the function\nprint(optimized_bubble_sort([64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90])) # Should return ([11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90], 14)\nprint(optimized_bubble_sort([])) # Should return \"Error: List is empty\"\nprint(optimized_bubble_sort([64, '34', 25, 12, 22, 11, 90])) # Should return \"Error: List contains non-numeric elements\"\nprint(optimized_bubble_sort(123)) # Should return \"Error: Input should be a list of numbers\"\n```\nThis function checks the type of each element in the list to make sure they are numeric. The bubble sort algorithm is slightly optimized by keeping track of the last swap in each pass. The function counts all the swaps performed and returns both the sorted list and the swap count. If the input list is empty, the function returns an appropriate error message."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1256153", "question": "Answer the following question: Given the following passage  \"Ancient tables provided the sun's mean longitude. Christopher Clavius, the architect of the Gregorian calendar, noted that the tables agreed neither on the time when the sun passed through the vernal equinox nor on the length of the mean tropical year. Tycho Brahe also noticed discrepancies. The Gregorian leap year rule (97 leap years in 400 years) was put forward by Petrus Pitatus of Verona in 1560. He noted that it is consistent with the tropical year of the Alfonsine tables and with the mean tropical year of Copernicus (De revolutionibus) and Reinhold (Prutenic tables). The three mean tropical years in Babylonian sexagesimals as the excess over 365 days (the way they would have been extracted from the tables of mean longitude) were 14,33,9,57 (Alphonsine), 14,33,11,12 (Copernicus) and 14,33,9,24 (Reinhold). All values are the same to two places (14:33) and this is also the mean length of the Gregorian year. Thus Pitatus' solution would have commended itself to the astronomers.\",  answer the following question. Note that the answer is present within the text.  Question: What is the last number in the group of Reinhold numbers as it has been extracted from the tables of mean longitude?\nAnswer:", "answer": "24"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_382931", "question": "def find_closest_distance(athlete_positions: List[int], target_position: int) -> int:\n\n    \"\"\"Given a list of athlete positions and a target position, find the smallest absolute difference between each athlete's position and the target position.\n       Return the distance of this closest position to the target.\"\"\"", "answer": "# Initialize a variable to store the closest distance\n    closest_distance = float('inf')\n\n    # Iterate through each athlete position\n    for position in athlete_positions:\n        \n        # Calculate the absolute difference between the current athlete's position and the target position\n        absolute_difference = abs(position - target_position)\n\n        # Update the closest_distance if the current absolute difference is smaller\n        if absolute_difference < closest_distance:\n            closest_distance = absolute_difference\n\n    return closest_distance"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_553835", "question": "A certain number of people are going to a movie. 6 people can ride in each car, and 18 cars are needed to get all the people to the movie. How many people are going to the movie?", "answer": "If 6 people can ride in each car and 18 cars are needed, then the total number of people going to the movie can be calculated by multiplying the number of people per car by the number of cars.\n\nNumber of people = Number of people per car × Number of cars\nNumber of people = 6 × 18\nNumber of people = 108\n\nSo, 108 people are going to the movie."}
