{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_492546", "question": "A 20 litres mixture contains 20% alcohol and the rest water. If a certain amount of water is mixed with it, the percentage of alcohol in the new mixture is 17.391304347826086%. How many litres of water are mixed with the original mixture?", "answer": "Let's denote the amount of water added to the mixture as \\( x \\) litres.\n\nThe original mixture contains 20% alcohol, which means there are \\( 0.20 \\times 20 \\) litres of alcohol in it. That's \\( 4 \\) litres of alcohol.\n\nAfter adding \\( x \\) litres of water, the total volume of the mixture becomes \\( 20 + x \\) litres.\n\nThe percentage of alcohol in the new mixture is given as 17.391304347826086%, which can be approximated as \\( \\frac{17.391304347826086}{100} \\) or \\( \\frac{4}{23} \\) (since 17.391304347826086% is approximately 4/23 when converted to a fraction).\n\nThe amount of alcohol remains the same, only the total volume of the mixture changes. So, we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ \\frac{4}{20 + x} = \\frac{4}{23} \\]\n\nNow, we can solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\[ 4 \\times 23 = 4 \\times (20 + x) \\]\n\\[ 92 = 80 + 4x \\]\n\\[ 92 - 80 = 4x \\]\n\\[ 12 = 4x \\]\n\\[ x = 3 \\]\n\nSo, 3 litres of water were mixed with the original mixture."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_354866", "question": "I have a table called \"numbers\" with a field called \"num\" of type INT. The table has the following entries: 364, 0, 123, 0, 321, 4215, 12138. I want to sort these numbers in ascending order, but I want the zeros to be at the bottom of the sorted list. Currently, I am achieving this by running two separate queries: one to select all non-zero numbers in ascending order and another to select all zeros. Is it possible to accomplish this in a single query?", "answer": "Yes, it is possible to achieve the desired sorting in a single query. You can modify the ORDER BY clause to sort the numbers by whether they are zero or not. Here's the modified query:\n\n```sql\nSELECT num FROM numbers ORDER BY (num = 0) ASC, num ASC\n```\n\nThis query first sorts the numbers based on whether they are zero or not, in ascending order. The expression `(num = 0)` evaluates to 1 if the number is zero and 0 otherwise. By sorting in ascending order, the non-zero numbers will appear before the zeros. Within each group, the numbers are sorted in ascending order.\n\nHere's the output of the modified query:\n\n```\n123\n321\n364\n4215\n12138\n0\n0\n```\n\nYou can also omit the \"ASC\" keyword in the ORDER BY clause, as it is the default sorting order. Here's the modified query without specifying the sorting order explicitly:\n\n```sql\nSELECT num FROM numbers ORDER BY (num = 0), num\n```\n\nThis query achieves the same result as the previous query.\n\nYou can try out these queries in the SQLFiddle demos provided below:\n\n- [SQLFiddle Demo 1](http://www.sqlfiddle.com/#!2/0c523/2)\n- [SQLFiddle Demo 2](http://www.sqlfiddle.com/#!2/0c523/3)"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_783129", "question": "Julieta went to the store to buy a backpack and three ring-binders for her school supplies. She knew the backpack was $50, and each ring-binder cost was $20. However, at the store, she found out that the price of a back had increased by $5, and the price of a ring-binder had reduced by $2. Calculate the total amount of money Julieta spent at the store.", "answer": "Initially, a backpack cost was $50; when it increased by $5, the price became $50+$5 = $55\nThe price of a ring-binder $20, when it reduced by $2, the price became $20-$2 = $18\nIf she wanted to buy 3 ring-binders, she spent $18*3 = $54\nIn total, Julieta spent $55+$54 = $109\nThe answer is 109"}
