{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_447817", "question": "Question: What type of details about peter hook  can be gathered from the following bio?  Bio: peter hook -lrb- born 13 february 1956 -rrb- is an english bass player , co-founder of the seminal post-punk band joy division along with bernard sumner in the mid-1970s . he is also musician , singer , dj , nightclub owner and author . following the death of joy division lead singer ian curtis , the band reformed as the modern rock band , new order , and hook played bass with them until his departure in 2007 . the band has since reformed without hook . he has also recorded an album with revenge -lrb- `` one true passion '' -rrb- , two albums with monaco -lrb- `` music for pleasure '' and `` monaco '' -rrb- and one album with freebass -lrb- `` it 's a beautiful life '' -rrb- as bassist , keyboardist and lead vocalist . he is currently lead vocalist and bassist for peter hook and the light .\nAnswer:", "answer": "From the bio, we can gather the following details about Peter Hook:\n\n1. He was born on 13th February 1956. \n2. Peter Hook is an English bass player. \n3. He co-founded the post-punk band Joy Division with Bernard Sumner in the mid-1970s. \n4. Besides being a bass player, he is also a musician, singer, DJ, nightclub owner, and author. \n5. After the death of Ian Curtis, Joy Division reformed as the modern rock band New Order, and Hook played bass with them until 2007. \n6. He has recorded an album with Revenge, two albums with Monaco, and one album with Freebass as bassist, keyboardist, and lead vocalist. \n7. Peter Hook is currently the lead vocalist and bassist for the band Peter Hook and the Light."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1298851", "question": "An internet company recently hired 15 new network engineers, adding to their existing team of 25 network engineers. The new hires graduated from four different universities - University A, University B, University C, and University D. The distribution of new hires from each university is as follows: 3 from University A, 4 from University B, 6 from University C, and 2 from University D. It is also known that among all the network engineers (new and original), 45% graduated from University A, 25% graduated from University B, 20% graduated from University C, and 10% graduated from University D. What proportion of the original 25 network engineers graduated from each of the four universities (A, B, C, and D)?", "answer": "Let's denote the number of original network engineers from each university as follows:\n\n- \\( A_o \\) for University A\n- \\( B_o \\) for University B\n- \\( C_o \\) for University C\n- \\( D_o \\) for University D\n\nThe total number of network engineers after the new hires is \\( 25 + 15 = 40 \\).\n\nAccording to the information given, the distribution of all network engineers (new and original) is:\n\n- 45% from University A\n- 25% from University B\n- 20% from University C\n- 10% from University D\n\nThis means the total number of engineers from each university is:\n\n- University A: \\( 40 \\times 0.45 = 18 \\)\n- University B: \\( 40 \\times 0.25 = 10 \\)\n- University C: \\( 40 \\times 0.20 = 8 \\)\n- University D: \\( 40 \\times 0.10 = 4 \\)\n\nNow, we know the number of new hires from each university:\n\n- University A: 3\n- University B: 4\n- University C: 6\n- University D: 2\n\nTo find the number of original engineers from each university, we subtract the new hires from the total number:\n\n- \\( A_o = 18 - 3 = 15 \\)\n- \\( B_o = 10 - 4 = 6 \\)\n- \\( C_o = 8 - 6 = 2 \\)\n- \\( D_o = 4 - 2 = 2 \\)\n\nNow we have the number of original engineers from each university. To find the proportion of the original 25 network engineers from each university, we divide the number of original engineers from each university by the total number of original engineers (25):\n\n- Proportion from University A: \\( \\frac{15}{25} = 0.60 \\) or 60%\n- Proportion from University B: \\( \\frac{6}{25} = 0.24 \\) or 24%\n- Proportion from University C: \\( \\frac{2}{25} = 0.08 \\) or 8%\n- Proportion from University D: \\( \\frac{2}{25} = 0.08 \\) or 8%\n\nSo, the proportions of the original 25 network engineers that graduated from each of the four universities (A, B, C, and D) are 60%, 24%, 8%, and 8%, respectively."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_835393", "question": "If $\\triangle + q = 59$ and $(\\triangle + q) + q = 106$, what is the value of $\\triangle$?", "answer": "From the first equation, we have $\\triangle + q = 59$.\nSubstituting this into the second equation, we get $(\\triangle + q) + q = \\triangle + 2q = 106$.\nSubtracting the first equation from the second equation, we have $\\triangle + 2q - (\\triangle + q) = 106 - 59$, which simplifies to $q = 47$.\nSubstituting this value of $q$ back into the first equation, we get $\\triangle + 47 = 59$, which gives us $\\triangle = 59 - 47 = \\boxed{12}$.\nThe answer is: 12"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_283681", "question": "Find the number of cubic centimeters in the volume of the cylinder formed by rotating a square with side length 14 centimeters about its vertical line of symmetry. Express your answer in terms of $\\pi$.", "answer": "When the square is rotated, it forms a cylinder with height equal to the side length of the square and radius equal to half the side length of the square.\nIn this case, the height of the cylinder is 14 centimeters and the radius is 7 centimeters.\nThe volume of a cylinder is given by the formula $V = \\pi r^2 h$.\nSubstituting the values, we have $V = \\pi (7^2)(14) = \\boxed{686\\pi}$ cubic centimeters.\nThe answer is: 686\\pi"}
