{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_34865", "question": "After removing the multiples of 2 and 3 from the set $S = \\{1, 2, 3, \\ldots , 49, 50\\}$, how many integers are left in the set?", "answer": "We can use the principle of inclusion-exclusion to count the number of integers left in the set.\nThere are 50 integers in total.\nWe remove the multiples of 2, which is 25 integers (every other number starting from 2).\nWe remove the multiples of 3, which is 16 integers (every third number starting from 3).\nHowever, we double-counted the multiples of 6 (which are multiples of both 2 and 3), so we need to add them back in.\nThere are 8 multiples of 6.\nTherefore, the number of integers left in the set is $50 - 25 - 16 + 8 = \\boxed{17}$.The answer is: 17"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_779945", "question": "A can is in the shape of a right circular cylinder. The base of the can has a circumference of 12 inches, and the height of the can is 5 inches. A spiral strip is painted on the can in such a way that it starts from the bottom and winds around the can exactly once, reaching the top directly above where it started. What is the length in inches of the painted strip?", "answer": "The circumference of the base of the can is 12 inches, so the radius of the base is $12/(2\\pi)=6/\\pi$ inches.\nThe height of the can is 5 inches.\nWhen we unroll the spiral strip, it forms a right triangle with the height of the can as the hypotenuse and the circumference of the base as the sum of the other two sides.\nUsing the Pythagorean theorem, we can find the length of the painted strip: \\[\n\\sqrt{(2\\pi r)^2+h^2}=\\sqrt{(2\\pi(6/\\pi))^2+5^2}=\\sqrt{144+25}=\\sqrt{169}=13.\n\\]\nTherefore, the length of the painted strip is $\\boxed{13}$ inches.\nThe answer is: 13"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_441053", "question": "Devise a Python program to generate a histogram to scrutinize the pattern of customer satisfaction ratings for the present week in comparison to the week before.\nscores_week1 = [4, 5, 5, 3, 4, 5, 4, 5]\nscores_week2 = [4, 4, 5, 3, 2, 4, 5, 4]", "answer": "Here is a Python program using matplotlib's pyplot module to generate a histogram for the given problem:\n\n```python\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\n# provided data\nscores_week1 = [4, 5, 5, 3, 4, 5, 4, 5]\nscores_week2 = [4, 4, 5, 3, 2, 4, 5, 4]\n\n# Define the range for the bins\nbins = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n\n# Plotting histogram for week 1\nplt.hist(scores_week1, bins, alpha=0.5, label='Week 1', color='g')\n\n# Plotting histogram for week 2\nplt.hist(scores_week2, bins, alpha=0.5, label='Week 2', color='b')\n\n# Setting labels for the axes and title for the plot\nplt.xlabel('Satisfaction Rating')\nplt.ylabel('Number of Customers')\nplt.title('Customer Satisfaction Ratings: Week 1 vs Week 2')\n\n# Adding legend to the plot\nplt.legend(loc='upper right')\n\n# Display the histogram\nplt.show()\n```\n\nIn this code:\n- The matplotlib library is imported to allow the creation of the histogram.\n- The data for the two weeks of scores are defined.\n- The bins for the histogram are defined (from 1 to 6 because these represent the possible scores a customer can give).\n- Two calls are made to plt.hist() to create histograms for each week's data, with the alpha parameter set to 0.5 for semi-transparent overlapping histograms.\n- Labels are added to the x and y axes and a title is added to the plot.\n- A legend is added and placed at the upper right corner of the plot.\n- Finally, plt.show() is called to display the completed histogram."}
