{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1085762", "question": "Using JavaScript, create a function that capitalizes the first letter of every word in a sentence.", "answer": "Here is a simple JavaScript function that capitalizes the first letter of every word in a sentence:\n\n```javascript\nfunction capitalizeFirstLetterOfEveryWord(sentence) {\n    return sentence.toLowerCase().split(' ').map(function(word) {\n        return word.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + word.slice(1);\n    }).join(' ');\n}\n```\n\nThis function works by converting the entire sentence to lowercase, splitting it into words, and then using `map` to create a new array where each word is transformed such that its first character is uppercase and the rest of the characters are as they were. The resulting array of words is then joined back together into a single string with spaces between the words.\n\nYou can use this function like so:\n\n```javascript\nlet sentence = \"hello world!\";\nconsole.log(capitalizeFirstLetterOfEveryWord(sentence)); // Outputs: \"Hello World!\"\n```"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_97956", "question": "Write a python function to parse a list of strings and extract the date that appears at the end of the strings?\nlist_of_strings = [\"April 11th, 2019\", \"July 2nd, 2018\", \"October 16th, 2012\"]", "answer": "Here is the Python function to parse a list of strings and extract the date that appears at the end of the strings.\n\n```python\nfrom dateutil.parser import parse\n\ndef extract_dates(list_of_strings):\n  dates = []\n  for string in list_of_strings:\n    try:\n      date = parse(string)\n      dates.append(date)\n    except ValueError:\n      continue\n  return dates\n\nlist_of_strings = [\"April 11th, 2019\", \"July 2nd, 2018\", \"October 16th, 2012\"]\n\ndates = extract_dates(list_of_strings)\n\nfor date in dates:\n  print(date.date())\n```\n\nWhen you run this script, it will print the dates that it was able to extract from the strings:\n\n```shell\n2019-04-11\n2018-07-02\n2012-10-16\n```\n\nPlease make sure that the `python-dateutil` package is installed in your environment. If not, you can install it by running `pip install python-dateutil` in your terminal.\n\nNotice that the `extract_dates` function also handles any exceptions that may occur if it isn't able to parse a date from one of the strings. This means that the script won't crash if it encounters a string that doesn't contain a valid date. Instead, it will just skip over that string and continue with the next one."}
