{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_484705", "question": "a train is travelling at 48 kmph . it crosses another train having half of its length , travelling in opposite direction at 42 kmph , in 12 seconds . it also passes a railway platform in 45 seconds . what is the length of the platform ?", "answer": "Let's denote the length of the first train as L meters. Since the second train has half the length of the first train, its length will be L/2 meters.\n\nWhen two trains are traveling in opposite directions, their relative speed is the sum of their individual speeds. Therefore, the relative speed of the two trains is:\n\n48 kmph + 42 kmph = 90 kmph\n\nTo convert this speed into meters per second, we use the conversion factor 1 kmph = 5/18 m/s:\n\n90 kmph * (5/18) = 25 m/s\n\nThe total length that the trains cover when passing each other is the sum of their lengths, which is L + (L/2) = (3/2)L.\n\nThe time taken to cross each other is 12 seconds, so we can use the formula:\n\nDistance = Speed * Time\n\n(3/2)L = 25 m/s * 12 s\n\nNow, we can solve for L:\n\n(3/2)L = 300 m\nL = (2/3) * 300 m\nL = 200 m\n\nSo, the length of the first train is 200 meters.\n\nNow, let's find the length of the platform. The first train passes the platform in 45 seconds at a speed of 48 kmph, which we convert to meters per second:\n\n48 kmph * (5/18) = 13.33 m/s\n\nThe distance covered when the train passes the platform is the length of the train plus the length of the platform. Let's denote the length of the platform as P meters. The formula for distance is again:\n\nDistance = Speed * Time\n\nL + P = 13.33 m/s * 45 s\n\nWe already know the length of the train (L) is 200 meters, so we can substitute that into the equation:\n\n200 m + P = 13.33 m/s * 45 s\n200 m + P = 599.85 m\n\nNow, we can solve for P:\n\nP = 599.85 m - 200 m\nP = 399.85 m\n\nTherefore, the length of the platform is approximately 399.85 meters."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_338932", "question": "Grover bought 3 boxes of face masks. He plans to sell them for $0.50 each. Each box has 20 face masks, and he bought the 3 boxes for $15. How much will be his total profit?", "answer": "First, let's calculate the total number of face masks Grover has:\n\n3 boxes * 20 face masks per box = 60 face masks\n\nNext, let's calculate the total revenue Grover will get from selling all the face masks:\n\n60 face masks * $0.50 per mask = $30\n\nNow, let's calculate Grover's total cost:\n\nHe bought 3 boxes for $15.\n\nFinally, let's calculate Grover's total profit:\n\nTotal revenue - Total cost = Total profit\n\n$30 - $15 = $15\n\nGrover's total profit will be $15."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1012313", "question": "I am new to Go and I'm building a simple API with it now. I have the following code:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"github.com/gorilla/mux\"\n    \"github.com/gorilla/handlers\"\n    \"log\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    port := \":3000\"\n    var router = mux.NewRouter()\n    router.HandleFunc(\"/m/{msg}\", handleMessage).Methods(\"GET\")\n    router.HandleFunc(\"/n/{num}\", handleNumber).Methods(\"GET\")\n\n    headersOk := handlers.AllowedHeaders([]string{\"Authorization\"})\n    originsOk := handlers.AllowedOrigins([]string{\"*\"})\n    methodsOk := handlers.AllowedMethods([]string{\"GET\", \"POST\", \"OPTIONS\"})\n\n    fmt.Printf(\"Server is running at http://localhost%s\\n\", port)\n    log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(port, handlers.CORS(originsOk, headersOk, methodsOk)(router)))\n}\n\nfunc handleMessage(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    vars := mux.Vars(r)\n    message := vars[\"msg\"]\n    response := map[string]string{\"message\": message}\n    w.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n    json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(response)\n}\n\nfunc handleNumber(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    vars := mux.Vars(r)\n    number := vars[\"num\"]\n    response := map[string]string{\"number\": number}\n    w.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n    json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(response)\n}\n```\n\nI feel like it's not clean to keep repeating `w.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")` line in every API function that I have.\n\nSo my question here is, does it possible to set that `http.ResponseWriter` Content-Type header globally for all API functions that I have?", "answer": "Yes, you can define middleware for the `mux` router to achieve this. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nfunc main() {\n    port := \":3000\"\n    var router = mux.NewRouter()\n    router.Use(commonMiddleware)\n\n    router.HandleFunc(\"/m/{msg}\", handleMessage).Methods(\"GET\")\n    router.HandleFunc(\"/n/{num}\", handleNumber).Methods(\"GET\")\n    // rest of code goes here\n}\n\nfunc commonMiddleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {\n    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n        w.Header().Add(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n        next.ServeHTTP(w, r)\n    })\n}\n```\n\nBy using the `router.Use(commonMiddleware)` line, the `commonMiddleware` function will be executed before every API function. Inside the `commonMiddleware` function, we set the `Content-Type` header of the `http.ResponseWriter` to `\"application/json\"`. This way, you don't need to repeat the same code in every API function.\n\nYou can find more information in the [documentation](http://www.gorillatoolkit.org/pkg/mux)."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_521190", "question": "Janet works as an exterminator and she also sells molten metal casts of fire ant nests on the Internet. She gets paid a certain amount per hour for exterminator work and makes $20/pound on her ant nest sculptures. She did 20 hours of exterminator work and sold a 5-pound sculpture and a 7-pound sculpture, making $1640. How much does she get paid per hour for exterminator work?", "answer": "Let's denote Janet's hourly wage for exterminator work as \\( x \\) dollars per hour.\n\nFrom the information given, we know that she sold a 5-pound sculpture and a 7-pound sculpture. Since she makes $20 per pound on her sculptures, the total earnings from the sculptures would be:\n\n\\( 5 \\text{ pounds} \\times \\$20/\\text{pound} + 7 \\text{ pounds} \\times \\$20/\\text{pound} \\)\n\n\\( = \\$100 + \\$140 \\)\n\n\\( = \\$240 \\)\n\nWe also know that she worked 20 hours as an exterminator. So her earnings from exterminator work would be:\n\n\\( 20 \\text{ hours} \\times x \\text{ dollars/hour} \\)\n\n\\( = 20x \\text{ dollars} \\)\n\nThe total earnings from both her exterminator work and the sculptures is $1640. So we can write the equation:\n\n\\( 20x + \\$240 = \\$1640 \\)\n\nNow, we can solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\( 20x = \\$1640 - \\$240 \\)\n\n\\( 20x = \\$1400 \\)\n\n\\( x = \\$1400 / 20 \\)\n\n\\( x = \\$70 \\)\n\nTherefore, Janet gets paid $70 per hour for exterminator work."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_681411", "question": "A number is doubled and 5 is added. If the resultant is trebled, it becomes 117. What is the ratio of the initial number to the number after doubling it?", "answer": "Let the initial number be x.\n\nAccording to the problem, the number is doubled and 5 is added, so we have:\n2x + 5\n\nThen, the resultant is trebled to become 117, so we have:\n3(2x + 5) = 117\n\nNow, let's solve for x:\n3(2x + 5) = 117\n6x + 15 = 117\n6x = 117 - 15\n6x = 102\nx = 102 / 6\nx = 17\n\nThe initial number is 17.\n\nAfter doubling it, the number becomes:\n2x = 2 * 17 = 34\n\nThe ratio of the initial number to the number after doubling it is:\nx : 2x\n17 : 34\n\nTo simplify the ratio, we divide both sides by 17:\n(17/17) : (34/17)\n1 : 2\n\nTherefore, the ratio of the initial number to the number after doubling it is 1:2."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_212070", "question": "The ISO 216 system used in most other countries is based on the surface area of a sheet of paper, not on a sheet's width and length. It was first adopted in Germany in 1922 and generally spread as nations adopted the metric system. The largest standard size paper is A0 (A zero), measuring one square meter (approx. 1189 × 841 mm). Two sheets of A1, placed upright side by side fit exactly into one sheet of A0 laid on its side. Similarly, two sheets of A2 fit into one sheet of A1 and so forth. Common sizes used in the office and the home are A4 and A3 (A3 is the size of two A4 sheets).\nTry to answer this question if possible (otherwise reply \"unanswerable\"): What country first adopted the ISO 216 standard?", "answer": "Germany"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_886958", "question": "There are 5 chess amateurs playing in Villa's chess club tournament. Each chess amateur plays with a certain number of other amateurs. The total number of chess games possible to be played in the tournament is 10. How many other amateurs does each chess amateur play with?", "answer": "In a chess tournament where each player plays against every other player exactly once, the total number of games that can be played is determined by the formula for combinations:\n\n\\[ \\text{Number of games} = \\binom{n}{2} = \\frac{n(n-1)}{2} \\]\n\nwhere \\( n \\) is the number of players.\n\nWe are given that the total number of games is 10, so we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ \\frac{n(n-1)}{2} = 10 \\]\n\nSolving for \\( n \\):\n\n\\[ n(n-1) = 20 \\]\n\n\\[ n^2 - n - 20 = 0 \\]\n\nThis is a quadratic equation, and we can factor it:\n\n\\[ (n - 5)(n + 4) = 0 \\]\n\nThis gives us two possible solutions for \\( n \\): \\( n = 5 \\) or \\( n = -4 \\). Since the number of players cannot be negative, we discard \\( n = -4 \\) and take \\( n = 5 \\).\n\nSo, there are 5 chess amateurs in the tournament. Each amateur plays with every other amateur exactly once. Since there are 5 players, each player plays with \\( n - 1 \\) other players (because they don't play against themselves). Therefore:\n\n\\[ \\text{Number of opponents for each player} = n - 1 = 5 - 1 = 4 \\]\n\nEach chess amateur plays with 4 other amateurs."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_688343", "question": "The average (arithmetic mean) of some students' first quiz scores in a difficult English class is 62.5. When one student dropped the class, the average of the remaining scores increased to 63.0. The quiz score of the student who dropped the class is 55. How many students were there initially?", "answer": "Let's denote the initial number of students as \\( n \\) and the total score of all students before the one student dropped as \\( T \\). \n\nThe average score before the student dropped is 62.5, so we can write the equation:\n\\[ \\frac{T}{n} = 62.5 \\]\n\\[ T = 62.5n \\]  (Equation 1)\n\nAfter the student with a score of 55 dropped the class, there are \\( n - 1 \\) students left, and the total score of the remaining students is \\( T - 55 \\). The new average is 63.0, so we can write the equation:\n\\[ \\frac{T - 55}{n - 1} = 63.0 \\]\n\\[ T - 55 = 63(n - 1) \\]\n\\[ T - 55 = 63n - 63 \\]\n\\[ T = 63n - 63 + 55 \\]\n\\[ T = 63n - 8 \\]  (Equation 2)\n\nNow we have two equations with two variables. We can set Equation 1 equal to Equation 2 to solve for \\( n \\):\n\\[ 62.5n = 63n - 8 \\]\n\\[ 8 = 63n - 62.5n \\]\n\\[ 8 = 0.5n \\]\n\\[ n = \\frac{8}{0.5} \\]\n\\[ n = 16 \\]\n\nSo, initially, there were 16 students in the class."}
