{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_410322", "question": "A line contains the points $(6,8)$, $(-2, k)$ and $(-10, 4)$. What is the value of $k$?", "answer": "The slope of a line passing through two points $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$ is given by $\\frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}$.\nUsing the points $(6, 8)$ and $(-2, k)$, the slope of the line passing through these points is $\\frac{k-8}{-2-6} = \\frac{k-8}{-8}$.\nUsing the points $(6, 8)$ and $(-10, 4)$, the slope of the line passing through these points is $\\frac{4-8}{-10-6} = \\frac{-4}{-16} = \\frac{1}{4}$.\nSince the line passes through the point $(-2, k)$, its slope is also equal to $\\frac{1}{4}$.\nTherefore, we have $\\frac{k-8}{-8} = \\frac{1}{4}$.\nCross multiplying, we get $4(k-8) = -8$.\nSimplifying, we have $4k - 32 = -8$.\nAdding 32 to both sides, we have $4k = 24$.\nFinally, dividing both sides by 4, we have $k = \\boxed{6}$.\nThe answer is: 6"}
