{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1174512", "question": "Christopher uses 2 packets of a sugar substitute in his coffee. On weekdays, he has 3 coffees a day, while on weekends he has 4 coffees a day. The packets come 50 to a box and cost $5.50 a box. If he purchases 5 or more boxes at once, he receives a 10% discount on the total cost. How much will it cost him to have enough sugar substitutes to last him 150 days, taking into account the fluctuating number of coffees per day and the possible discount for purchasing multiple boxes?", "answer": "First, let's calculate the total number of packets Christopher uses in a week.\n\nOn weekdays (Monday to Friday), he has 3 coffees a day, each with 2 packets of sugar substitute:\n5 days * 3 coffees/day * 2 packets/coffee = 30 packets\n\nOn weekends (Saturday and Sunday), he has 4 coffees a day, each with 2 packets of sugar substitute:\n2 days * 4 coffees/day * 2 packets/coffee = 16 packets\n\nSo in one week, he uses a total of:\n30 packets (weekdays) + 16 packets (weekends) = 46 packets\n\nNow, let's calculate how many weeks are in 150 days:\n150 days / 7 days/week = approximately 21.43 weeks\n\nSince we can't have a fraction of a week, we'll need to consider the full weeks and the remaining days separately. We have 21 full weeks and 0.43 of a week, which is approximately 3 days (since 0.43 * 7 days/week ≈ 3 days).\n\nFor the 21 full weeks, he will need:\n21 weeks * 46 packets/week = 966 packets\n\nFor the remaining 3 days, assuming they are weekdays (since we don't have information on which days they are, and weekdays are more frequent), he will need:\n3 days * 3 coffees/day * 2 packets/coffee = 18 packets\n\nSo in total, for 150 days, he will need:\n966 packets (for full weeks) + 18 packets (for remaining days) = 984 packets\n\nNow, let's calculate how many boxes he needs. Each box contains 50 packets:\n984 packets / 50 packets/box = 19.68 boxes\n\nSince he can't buy a fraction of a box, he will need to buy 20 boxes.\n\nThe cost for 20 boxes without the discount is:\n20 boxes * $5.50/box = $110.00\n\nSince he is buying 5 or more boxes, he gets a 10% discount. Let's calculate the discount amount and the final cost:\nDiscount amount = 10% of $110.00 = 0.10 * $110.00 = $11.00\n\nFinal cost with discount = $110.00 - $11.00 = $99.00\n\nTherefore, it will cost Christopher $99.00 to have enough sugar substitutes to last him 150 days."}
