{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_345966", "question": "Given that $f(x) = 3x^2 - 5$, what is the value of $f(f(1))$?", "answer": "First, we find $f(1)$ by substituting $x=1$ into the expression for $f(x)$:\n\\[f(1) = 3(1)^2 - 5 = 3-5 = -2.\\]\nThen, we find $f(-2)$ by substituting $x=-2$ into the expression for $f(x)$:\n\\[f(-2) = 3(-2)^2 - 5 = 3(4) - 5 = 12 - 5 = 7.\\]\nTherefore, $f(f(1)) = f(-2) = \\boxed{7}$.The answer is: 7"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_738733", "question": "The average mark of the students of a class in a particular exam is some value. If 2 students whose average mark in that exam is 45 are excluded, the average mark of the remaining will be 95. There were 20 students who wrote the exam. What was the initial average mark of the class?", "answer": "Let's denote the initial average mark of the class as \\( A \\). The total marks for the class before the two students were excluded would be \\( 20 \\times A \\).\n\nWhen the two students with an average mark of 45 are excluded, the total marks they contributed would be \\( 2 \\times 45 = 90 \\).\n\nThe remaining students, which are \\( 20 - 2 = 18 \\) in number, now have an average mark of 95. Therefore, the total marks for the remaining students would be \\( 18 \\times 95 \\).\n\nWe can set up the equation as follows:\n\nTotal marks with all students - Total marks of the 2 excluded students = Total marks of the remaining students\n\n\\( 20A - 90 = 18 \\times 95 \\)\n\nNow we can solve for \\( A \\):\n\n\\( 20A - 90 = 1710 \\)\n\n\\( 20A = 1710 + 90 \\)\n\n\\( 20A = 1800 \\)\n\n\\( A = \\frac{1800}{20} \\)\n\n\\( A = 90 \\)\n\nSo, the initial average mark of the class was 90."}
