{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_243550", "question": "I'm new in Rust and I'm trying to allocate computational work to threads. I have a vector of strings and I want to create one thread for each string to perform its job. I'm using the following code:\n\n```rust\nuse std::thread;\n\nfn child_job(s: &mut String) {\n    *s = s.to_uppercase();\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    // initialize\n    let mut thread_handles = vec![];\n    let mut strings = vec![\n        \"hello\".to_string(),\n        \"world\".to_string(),\n        \"testing\".to_string(),\n        \"good enough\".to_string(),\n    ];\n\n    // create threads\n    for s in &mut strings {\n        thread_handles.push(thread::spawn(|| child_job(s)));\n    }\n\n    // wait for threads\n    for handle in thread_handles {\n        handle.join().unwrap();\n    }\n\n    // print result\n    for s in strings {\n        println!(\"{}\", s);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nI'm getting errors while compiling the code:\n\n```\nerror[E0597]: `strings` does not live long enough\n  --> src/main.rs:18:14\n   |\n18 |     for s in &mut strings {\n   |              ^^^^^^^^^^^^\n   |              |\n   |              borrowed value does not live long enough\n   |              argument requires that `strings` is borrowed for `'static`\n...\n31 | }\n   | - `strings` dropped here while still borrowed\n\nerror[E0505]: cannot move out of `strings` because it is borrowed\n  --> src/main.rs:28:14\n   |\n18 |     for s in &mut strings {\n   |              ------------\n   |              |\n   |              borrow of `strings` occurs here\n   |              argument requires that `strings` is borrowed for `'static`\n...\n28 |     for s in strings {\n   |              ^^^^^^^ move out of `strings` occurs here\n```\n\nI'm having trouble understanding the issue with the lifetimes of pointers and how to fix it. To me, it seems like everything is fine because each thread only receives one mutable pointer to a string and doesn't affect the vector itself in any way.", "answer": "The error you're encountering is due to the borrow checker not being able to determine that the threads will finish before the `main` function exits. Therefore, it can't guarantee that the `strings` vector will live long enough for the threads to work on it. To solve this, you have a couple of options.\n\nOne option is to use `Arc`s (atomic reference counters) to manage the lifetimes of the strings. This approach allows you to share ownership of the strings among the threads. However, it requires runtime lifetime management. Here's an example using `Arc`:\n\n```rust\nuse std::thread;\nuse std::sync::Arc;\n\nfn child_job(s: &mut String) {\n    *s = s.to_uppercase();\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut thread_handles = vec![];\n    let strings = vec![\n        \"hello\".to_string(),\n        \"world\".to_string(),\n        \"testing\".to_string(),\n        \"good enough\".to_string(),\n    ];\n\n    for s in &strings {\n        let s = Arc::new(s.clone());\n        thread_handles.push(thread::spawn(move || {\n            let mut s = Arc::try_unwrap(s).unwrap();\n            child_job(&mut s);\n        }));\n    }\n\n    for handle in thread_handles {\n        handle.join().unwrap();\n    }\n\n    for s in strings {\n        println!(\"{}\", s);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAnother option is to use scoped threads, which allow you to specify that a thread will finish before a particular scope ends. With scoped threads, you can pass references to objects on the current thread's stack to another thread. However, this feature is not available in the standard library yet, so you'll need to use a crate like `crossbeam` to achieve it. Here's an example using `crossbeam`:\n\n```rust\nuse std::thread;\nuse crossbeam::thread::scope;\n\nfn child_job(s: &mut String) {\n    *s = s.to_uppercase();\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut strings = vec![\n        \"hello\".to_string(),\n        \"world\".to_string(),\n        \"testing\".to_string(),\n        \"good enough\".to_string(),\n    ];\n\n    scope(|scope| {\n        for s in &mut strings {\n            scope.spawn(|_| child_job(s));\n        }\n    }).unwrap();\n\n    for s in strings {\n        println!(\"{}\", s);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `scope` function from the `crossbeam` crate is used to create a scope where the threads will be spawned. The spawned threads will automatically join at the end of the scope, so there's no need to manually join them.\n\nNote that the second option requires using a crate, but it is a feature that is expected to eventually be included in the standard library."}
