{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1417318", "question": "A cricket match is conducted in the US. The run rate of a cricket game was only 3.2 in the first 10 overs. What should be the run rate in the remaining 40 overs to reach the target of 252 runs?", "answer": "To calculate the required run rate for the remaining 40 overs, we first need to determine how many runs have already been scored in the first 10 overs and how many runs are still needed to reach the target of 252 runs.\n\nRuns scored in the first 10 overs = Run rate in the first 10 overs × Number of overs\n= 3.2 runs/over × 10 overs\n= 32 runs\n\nNow, we subtract the runs scored in the first 10 overs from the target to find out how many runs are still needed:\n\nRuns needed to reach the target = Target - Runs scored in the first 10 overs\n= 252 runs - 32 runs\n= 220 runs\n\nThe remaining number of overs in which to score these runs is 40 overs. So, the required run rate for the remaining 40 overs is:\n\nRequired run rate = Runs needed in the remaining overs / Remaining number of overs\n= 220 runs / 40 overs\n= 5.5 runs/over\n\nTherefore, the required run rate for the remaining 40 overs to reach the target of 252 runs is 5.5 runs per over."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_397737", "question": "Acme T-Shirt Company charges a $\\$50$ set-up fee plus $\\$9$ for  each shirt printed. Beta T-shirt Company has no set up fee, but charges $\\$14$ per shirt. What is the minimum number of shirts for which a customer saves money by using Acme?", "answer": "Let $x$ represent the number of shirts a customer orders.\nThe total cost for Acme is $50 + 9x$ and the total cost for Beta is $14x$.\nWe want to find the minimum number of shirts for which the cost for Acme is less than the cost for Beta, so we set up the inequality $50 + 9x < 14x$.\nSimplifying, we get $50 < 5x$ and then $10 < x$.\nSince $x$ represents the number of shirts, we round up to the nearest whole number, so the minimum number of shirts for which a customer saves money by using Acme is $\\boxed{11}$.\nThe answer is: 11"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_521085", "question": "Luke had 20 stickers. He bought some stickers from a store in the mall and got 20 stickers for his birthday. Then Luke gave 5 of the stickers to his sister and used 8 to decorate a greeting card. Now, Luke has 39 stickers left. How many stickers did Luke buy from the store?", "answer": "Let's calculate the total number of stickers Luke had after receiving the birthday stickers and before giving any away or using them.\n\nLuke originally had 20 stickers.\nHe got 20 more stickers for his birthday.\nSo, before giving any away or using them, he had 20 (original) + 20 (birthday) = 40 stickers.\n\nNow, let's calculate how many stickers he had left after giving some to his sister and using some on a greeting card.\n\nHe gave 5 stickers to his sister.\nHe used 8 stickers on a greeting card.\nSo, he gave away a total of 5 (to sister) + 8 (on card) = 13 stickers.\n\nNow, we know that after giving away and using some stickers, Luke has 39 stickers left. So, before giving away and using the stickers, he must have had 39 (left) + 13 (given/used) = 52 stickers.\n\nSince we know he had 40 stickers before buying any from the store, we can now calculate how many stickers he bought from the store:\n\n52 (total after buying) - 40 (before buying) = 12 stickers.\n\nLuke bought 12 stickers from the store."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_280337", "question": "Celina enjoys hiking in the mountains. She decided to order a new pair of boots, a flashlight, and a special hoodie. The hoodie cost $80 and the flashlight was only 20% of that price. Due to a special promotion, Celina was able to buy the pair of boots 10% cheaper. Celina spent $195 in total on the above-mentioned equipment. What was the original price of the pair of boots before the promotion?", "answer": "Let's start by calculating the price of the flashlight, which is 20% of the price of the hoodie. Since the hoodie costs $80, the flashlight would cost:\n\nFlashlight price = 20% of $80\nFlashlight price = 0.20 * $80\nFlashlight price = $16\n\nNow, let's calculate the total cost of the hoodie and the flashlight:\n\nTotal cost of hoodie and flashlight = $80 (hoodie) + $16 (flashlight)\nTotal cost of hoodie and flashlight = $96\n\nCelina spent $195 in total, so the amount she spent on the pair of boots after the promotion is:\n\nAmount spent on boots after promotion = Total spent - Total cost of hoodie and flashlight\nAmount spent on boots after promotion = $195 - $96\nAmount spent on boots after promotion = $99\n\nThe boots were 10% cheaper due to the promotion, which means that the price after the promotion is 90% of the original price. Let's denote the original price of the boots as P. Then, 90% of P is equal to $99:\n\n0.90 * P = $99\n\nTo find the original price P, we divide $99 by 0.90:\n\nP = $99 / 0.90\nP = $110\n\nTherefore, the original price of the pair of boots before the promotion was $110."}
