{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1333103", "question": "Write a Python program to sort a list of integers using the insertion sort algorithm.", "answer": "Certainly! Here is a Python program that sorts a list of integers using the insertion sort algorithm:\n\n```python\ndef insertion_sort(nums):\n    \"\"\"\n    Sorts a list of integers using the insertion sort algorithm.\n\n    Parameters:\n    nums (list): A list of integers to be sorted.\n\n    Returns:\n    list: The sorted list of integers.\n\n    \"\"\"\n\n    for i in range(1, len(nums)):\n        key = nums[i]\n        j = i - 1\n        while j >= 0 and nums[j] > key:\n            nums[j + 1] = nums[j]\n            j -= 1\n        nums[j + 1] = key\n\n    return nums\n\n\n# Example usage:\nnumbers = [5, 2, 9, 1, 7]\nsorted_numbers = insertion_sort(numbers)\nprint(sorted_numbers)\n```\n\nIn the above code, the `insertion_sort` function takes a list of integers as input and performs the insertion sort algorithm on it. It iterates over the list starting from the second element (`i=1`) till the end. For each element, it takes the current element (`key`) and compares it with the elements on its left. If any element on the left is greater than the key, it shifts that element to the right until it finds the correct position for the key. Finally, it places the key at the correct position in the sorted sublist.\n\nThe `while` loop in the code performs the shifting of elements to the right. It compares the current element with the key and if it is greater, shifts the element one position to the right (`nums[j+1] = nums[j]`). The loop repeats until it reaches the beginning of the list (`j=0`) or finds an element that is smaller than or equal to the key.\n\nAfter the insertion sort algorithm is applied to the entire list, the function returns the sorted list.\n\nIn the example usage code, we create a list of integers (`numbers`) and pass it to the `insertion_sort` function. The sorted list is then printed."}
