{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_504379", "question": "Write a function called \"update_fruits\" that takes in two parameters: a list called \"fruits\" and a string called \"new_fruit\". \n\nInside the function, check if the list already contains the item \"banana\". If it does, remove all instances of it using a loop and keep track of the number of occurrences removed.\n\nAfter removing the occurrences of \"banana\", append the new_fruit to the end of the list.\n\nSort the list in descending order using the built-in sort() function.\n\nFinally, print the number of occurrences of \"banana\" that were removed and the sorted list.\n\nExample usage of the function:\n\nfruits = ['apple', 'orange', 'grapes']\nupdate_fruits(fruits, \"banana\")\n\nExpected output:\nOccurrences of 'banana' removed: 0\nSorted list: ['orange', 'grapes', 'apple', 'banana']\n\nNote: You can add additional checks or steps to make the problem more complex if needed.", "answer": "def update_fruits(fruits, new_fruit):\n    removed = 0\n    if \"banana\" in fruits:\n        while \"banana\" in fruits:\n            fruits.remove(\"banana\")\n            removed += 1\n    fruits.append(new_fruit)\n    fruits.sort(reverse=True)\n    print(\"Occurrences of 'banana' removed:\", removed)\n    print(\"Sorted list:\", fruits)"}
