{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_499486", "question": "How can I design a priority queue with insert, extract min, and decrease key operations using Python?", "answer": "You can design a priority queue using Python by implementing a class called PriorityQueue. This class will utilize the heapq module for the underlying heap implementation. Here's an example implementation:\n\n```python\nimport heapq\n\nclass PriorityQueue:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.heap = []\n\n    def compare(self, x, y):\n        return x[1] <= y[1]\n\n    def insert(self, item):\n        heapq.heappush(self.heap, item)\n\n    def extractmin(self):\n        return heapq.heappop(self.heap)\n\n    def decreasekey(self, item, key):\n        for i, element in enumerate(self.heap):\n            if element[0] == item:\n                self.heap[i] = (item, key)\n        heapq.heapify(self.heap)\n```\n\nTo use this PriorityQueue, you can create an instance of the class and then call the provided operations. For example:\n\n```python\npq = PriorityQueue()\n\n# Insertion operation\npq.insert((2, 'item2'))\npq.insert((1, 'item1'))\npq.insert((4, 'item4'))\npq.insert((3, 'item3'))\n\n# Extract Min operation\nmin_item = pq.extractmin()\nprint(min_item)  # Output: (1, 'item1')\n\n# Decrease Key operation\npq.decreasekey('item4', 0)\n```\n\nIn the above code, the `insert` method inserts an item into the priority queue. The `extractmin` method removes and returns the minimum item from the queue based on the priority. The `decreasekey` method allows you to update the priority of an item already present in the queue."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_720427", "question": "nicky and cristina are running a 100 meter race . since cristina is faster than nicky , she gives him a 12 second head start . if cristina runs at a pace of 5 meters per second and nicky runs at a pace of only 3 meters per second , how many seconds will nicky have run before cristina catches up to him ?", "answer": "Let's calculate the distance Cristina covers in the 12-second head start given to Nicky.\n\nCristina's speed is 5 meters per second, so in 12 seconds, she would cover:\nDistance = Speed × Time\nDistance = 5 m/s × 12 s\nDistance = 60 meters\n\nNow, when Cristina starts running, Nicky has already covered some distance. We need to find out how long it takes for Cristina to cover the remaining distance to catch up to Nicky.\n\nLet's denote the time it takes for Cristina to catch up to Nicky as t seconds. In this time, Cristina will cover a distance of 5t meters (since her speed is 5 m/s), and Nicky will cover a distance of 3t meters (since his speed is 3 m/s).\n\nHowever, we must remember that Nicky already has a 60-meter lead when Cristina starts. So, the total distance Nicky covers before Cristina catches up to him is 60 meters plus the distance he covers in t seconds (3t meters).\n\nWe can set up the equation that the distance Cristina covers (5t meters) is equal to the total distance Nicky covers (60 + 3t meters) because she catches up to him at that point.\n\n5t = 60 + 3t\n\nNow, let's solve for t:\n\n5t - 3t = 60\n2t = 60\nt = 60 / 2\nt = 30 seconds\n\nSo, Cristina will catch up to Nicky in 30 seconds after she starts running.\n\nSince Nicky had a 12-second head start, the total time Nicky will have run before Cristina catches up to him is:\n\n12 seconds (head start) + 30 seconds (time Cristina takes to catch up)\n= 42 seconds\n\nNicky will have run for 42 seconds before Cristina catches up to him."}
