{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1338056", "question": "In a class of 50 students, 12 enrolled for both English and German. 22 enrolled for German. If the students of the class enrolled for at least one of the two subjects, how many students enrolled for only English and not German?", "answer": "Let's denote the number of students enrolled only in English as E, only in German as G, and in both English and German as B.\n\nWe are given that:\n- The total number of students in the class is 50.\n- The number of students enrolled in both English and German (B) is 12.\n- The number of students enrolled in German (which includes those enrolled in both German and English) is 22.\n\nWe want to find the number of students enrolled only in English (E).\n\nFirst, let's find out how many students are enrolled only in German (G). Since 22 students are enrolled in German and 12 of those are also enrolled in English, the number of students enrolled only in German is:\n\nG = Total German - Both English and German\nG = 22 - 12\nG = 10\n\nNow, we know that every student is enrolled in at least one of the two subjects, so the total number of students enrolled in at least one subject is the sum of those enrolled only in English, only in German, and in both:\n\nTotal students = E + G + B\n\nWe can plug in the values we know:\n\n50 = E + 10 + 12\n\nNow, we can solve for E:\n\nE = 50 - 10 - 12\nE = 50 - 22\nE = 28\n\nSo, 28 students are enrolled only in English and not German."}
