{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1186560", "question": "Many bird species migrate to take advantage of global differences of seasonal temperatures, therefore optimising availability of food sources and breeding habitat. These migrations vary among the different groups. Many landbirds, shorebirds, and waterbirds undertake annual long distance migrations, usually triggered by the length of daylight as well as weather conditions. These birds are characterised by a breeding season spent in the temperate or polar regions and a non-breeding season in the tropical regions or opposite hemisphere. Before migration, birds substantially increase body fats and reserves and reduce the size of some of their organs. Migration is highly demanding energetically, particularly as birds need to cross deserts and oceans without refuelling. Landbirds have a flight range of around 2,500 km (1,600 mi) and shorebirds can fly up to 4,000 km (2,500 mi), although the bar-tailed godwit is capable of non-stop flights of up to 10,200 km (6,300 mi). Seabirds also undertake long migrations, the longest annual migration being those of sooty shearwaters, which nest in New Zealand and Chile and spend the northern summer feeding in the North Pacific off Japan, Alaska and California, an annual round trip of 64,000 km (39,800 mi). Other seabirds disperse after breeding, travelling widely but having no set migration route. Albatrosses nesting in the Southern Ocean often undertake circumpolar trips between breeding seasons.\nWhich birds often undertake circumpolar trips between breeding seasons?", "answer": "Albatrosses nesting in the Southern Ocean"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_221532", "question": "I need help writing a program in Python to find all the unique elements in a 2D array. However, I only want to consider the elements that are located at index positions which are Fibonacci sequence numbers. Additionally, the dimensions of the 2D array should not exceed 10x10. Can someone provide a code snippet to solve this problem?\n\n```python\narr = [[2, 3, 7, 11], [13, 17, 22, 31], [4, 33, 5, 18], [12, 22, 7, 39]]\n\n# code snippet goes here\n\n```", "answer": "Certainly! Here is a Python code snippet that solves your problem:\n\n```python\ndef get_fib_indexes(limit):\n    fib_indexes = [0, 1]\n    while fib_indexes[-1] < limit:\n        fib_indexes.append(fib_indexes[-1] + fib_indexes[-2])\n    return fib_indexes\n\ndef find_unique_elements(arr):\n    flatten_list = [elem for sublist in arr for elem in sublist]\n    fib_indexes = get_fib_indexes(len(flatten_list))\n    unique_elements = {flatten_list[i] for i in fib_indexes if i < len(flatten_list)}\n    return unique_elements\n\narr = [[2, 3, 7, 11], [13, 17, 22, 31], [4, 33, 5, 18], [12, 22, 7, 39]]\nprint(find_unique_elements(arr))\n```\n\nIn this solution, the `get_fib_indexes(limit)` function is used to calculate the Fibonacci sequence up to a certain limit. It starts with the initial Fibonacci sequence `[0, 1]` and iteratively adds the next number in the sequence until the last number is less than the given limit.\n\nThe `find_unique_elements(arr)` function first flattens the 2D array `arr` into a 1D list using a list comprehension. Then, it computes the Fibonacci sequence for the indices up to the length of the flattened list using the `get_fib_indexes()` function. \n\nFinally, the function selects the elements at these Fibonacci sequence indices from the flattened list, ensuring uniqueness by using a set. The unique elements are returned as the result.\n\nTo test the solution, the provided 2D array `arr` is passed to the `find_unique_elements()` function, and the result is printed using `print()`."}
