{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_402107", "question": "Given the following erroneous code, fix and optimize it. The goal is to design a cursor-based query in Python to retrieve a large record set from a database. The results should then be performed with transaction management commands (commit, rollback) to ensure data integrity. For the sake of this problem, consider the database to be PostgreSQL.\n\nErroneous Code:\n```python\nimport psycopg2\n\ntry:\n    connection = psycopg2.connect(user=\"sysadmin\",\n                                  password=\"sysadmin\",\n                                  host=\"127.0.0.1\",\n                                  port=\"5432\",\n                                  database=\"employees\")\n\n    cursor = connection.cursor()\n    cursor.execute(\"SELECT * FROM employees\")\n\n    print(\"Selecting rows from employees table using cursor.fetchall\")\n    employee_records = cursor.fetchall() \n    \n    print(\"Print each row and it's columns values\")\n    for row in employee_records:\n        print(\"Id = \", row[0], )\n        print(\"Name = \", row[1])\n        print(\"JoiningDate = \", row[2])\n        print(\"Salary = \", row[3])\n\nexcept (Exception, psycopg2.Error) as error:\n    print(\"Error fetching data from PostgreSQL table\", error)\n\nfinally:\n    #closing database connection.\n    if(connection):\n        cursor.close()\n        connection.close()\n        print(\"PostgreSQL connection is closed\")\n```\nThe code above fetches all the records at once which is not recommended for large record sets. Use a cursor-based approach and apply transaction management procedures.", "answer": "There are a few ways to optimize this and is mentioned in the problem that we will be fetching a large record set from the database. So, we may not be able to fetch all records at once into memory. We can iterate over the results in a loop using the cursor's fetchone() method which fetches the next row of a query result set, returning a single sequence, or None when no more data is available.\n\nAlso, it's a good practice to handle the psycopg database operations with the help of a context manager to maintain the transaction scope. This will manage the commit and rollback of the transactions implicitly in case of any exceptions.\n\nHere is an optimized version:\n\n```python\nimport psycopg2\nfrom psycopg2 import sql, Error\n\ntry:\n    # Create a new database session and return a new instance of the connection class.\n    with psycopg2.connect(user=\"sysadmin\",\n                          password=\"sysadmin\",\n                          host=\"127.0.0.1\",\n                          port=\"5432\",\n                          database=\"employees\") as connection:\n        \n        # Create a new cursor object using the cursor() method.\n        with connection.cursor() as cursor:\n            # Executing an SQL statement to fetch rows from the database table\n            cursor.execute(\"SELECT * FROM employees\")\n\n            print(\"Selecting rows from employees table using cursor\")\n            print(\"Print each row and its column values\")\n\n            while True:\n                # Fetch next row from the database table\n                record = cursor.fetchone()\n                \n                if record is None:\n                    break\n                \n                print(\"Id = \", record[0])\n                print(\"Name = \", record[1])\n                print(\"JoiningDate = \", record[2])\n                print(\"Salary = \", record[3])\n\nexcept (Exception, Error) as error:\n    print(\"Error fetching data from PostgreSQL table\", error)\n```\n\nThis code will help when working with very large datasets, where it's not feasible to fetch all records at once into the memory. Please be aware that you should take care of not opening too many connections to the same database from the same application, as it may lead to connection limit issues, depending on the database configuration."}
