{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_839833", "question": "A train of certain length crosses a tree in 80 sec. It takes 146.67 sec to pass a platform 1000 m long. What is the length of the train?", "answer": "Let's denote the length of the train as \\( L \\) meters.\n\nWhen the train passes the tree, it only needs to cover its own length, which it does in 80 seconds. Therefore, the speed of the train (\\( V \\)) can be calculated as:\n\n\\[ V = \\frac{L}{80} \\text{ meters per second} \\]\n\nWhen the train passes the platform, it needs to cover the length of itself plus the length of the platform (1000 meters) in 146.67 seconds. The total distance covered when passing the platform is \\( L + 1000 \\) meters. Using the same speed \\( V \\), we can write:\n\n\\[ V = \\frac{L + 1000}{146.67} \\text{ meters per second} \\]\n\nSince the speed of the train is the same in both cases, we can set the two expressions for \\( V \\) equal to each other:\n\n\\[ \\frac{L}{80} = \\frac{L + 1000}{146.67} \\]\n\nNow, we can solve for \\( L \\):\n\n\\[ L = \\frac{L + 1000}{146.67} \\times 80 \\]\n\n\\[ L = \\frac{80L + 80000}{146.67} \\]\n\n\\[ 146.67L = 80L + 80000 \\]\n\n\\[ 146.67L - 80L = 80000 \\]\n\n\\[ 66.67L = 80000 \\]\n\n\\[ L = \\frac{80000}{66.67} \\]\n\n\\[ L \\approx 1200 \\text{ meters} \\]\n\nTherefore, the length of the train is approximately 1200 meters."}
