{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_335683", "question": "Create a function in Python which takes a list of strings as an argument and returns a new list where each string is modified according to the following rules:\n\n1. The first character of each string should be converted to uppercase.\n2. Any leading or trailing whitespace in each string should be removed.\n\nThe function should have a time complexity of O(n), where n is the total number of characters in all the strings combined.", "answer": "Here is a Python function that meets the given requirements:\n\n```python\ndef modify_strings(strings):\n    modified_strings = []\n    for string in strings:\n        modified_string = string.strip().capitalize()\n        modified_strings.append(modified_string)\n    return modified_strings\n```\n\nThe function iterates over each string in the input list, strips any leading or trailing whitespace using the `strip()` method, and then capitalizes the first character using the `capitalize()` method. The modified string is then appended to a new list called `modified_strings`. Finally, the function returns this new list.\n\nThe time complexity of this function is O(n), where n is the total number of characters in all the strings combined. This is because the function needs to iterate over each character in each string in the input list to perform the necessary modifications."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1001838", "question": "Summarize the history of the Olympic Games, focusing on its origins in ancient Greece, its revival in the modern era, and significant changes over time such as the introduction of the Paralympics and Winter Olympics.", "answer": "The Olympic Games originated in ancient Greece around 776 BC, held in Olympia, a site in the western part of the Peloponnese. These games were one of four Panhellenic Games, religious and athletic festivals held every four years among representatives of several city-states and kingdoms from all over Greece. The Olympics were dedicated to the Olympian gods and included competitions in various disciplines like running, long jump, shot put, javelin, boxing, pankration, and equestrian events.\n\nThe ancient Olympic Games lasted for 12 centuries until Emperor Theodosius I decreed in 393 AD that all such \"pagan cults\" be banned. It was not until more than 1,500 years later that the Olympics would return.\n\nThe revival of the Olympic Games took place in much different circumstances. Inspired by the ideals of physical and moral improvement through sport, Frenchman Pierre de Coubertin sought to establish an international athletic competition that would occur every four years. His dream became reality when Athens hosted the first modern Summer Olympics in 1896. Initially, these games were modest, featuring about 280 participants representing 13 nations.\n\nSince then, the Olympic Games have grown exponentially in size and complexity. They are now split into two separate events: the Winter and Summer Olympics, which take place every four years but are staggered so there is an Olympics every two years. The Winter Olympics was introduced in Chamonix, France, in 1924, focusing on ice and snow sports.\n\nAnother significant change came with the introduction of the Paralympics, initially organized in 1948 for World War II veterans with spinal cord injuries. In 1960, the first official Paralympic Games were held in Rome, coinciding with the Summer Olympics. The Paralympics have since expanded to include athletes with a wide range of disabilities.\n\nOver time, the Olympic Games have also evolved to promote gender equality. While women were excluded from the first modern games, they began participating in 1900 at the Paris Games. Today, efforts are made to ensure equal representation of men and women across all sports.\n\nDespite controversies and challenges, including boycotts, doping scandals, and security concerns, the Olympic Games remain a prominent symbol of global unity and sporting excellence."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1060119", "question": "Sam and Jeff had a skipping competition at recess. The competition was split into four rounds. Sam completed 1 more skip than Jeff in the first round. Jeff skipped 3 fewer times than Sam in the second round. Jeff skipped 4 more times than Sam in the third round. Jeff got tired and only completed half the number of skips as Sam in the last round. If Sam skipped x times in each round, what is the average number of skips per round completed by Jeff?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 14, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "In the first round, Sam completed 1 more skip than Jeff, so Jeff completed x - 1 skips.\nIn the second round, Jeff skipped 3 fewer times than Sam, so Jeff completed x - 3 skips.\nIn the third round, Jeff skipped 4 more times than Sam, so Jeff completed x + 4 skips.\nIn the last round, Jeff completed half the number of skips as Sam, so Jeff completed (1/2)*x skips.\nThe total number of skips completed by Jeff in all four rounds is: (x - 1) + (x - 3) + (x + 4) + (1/2)*x.\nTo find the average number of skips per round completed by Jeff, we divide the total number of skips by 4: [(x - 1) + (x - 3) + (x + 4) + (1/2)*x] / 4.\nWe are given that the average number of skips per round completed by Jeff is 14, so we can write: [(x - 1) + (x - 3) + (x + 4) + (1/2)*x] / 4 = 14.\nMultiplying both sides by 4, we get: (x - 1) + (x - 3) + (x + 4) + (1/2)*x = 56.\nCombining like terms, we get: 3.5x = 56.\nDividing both sides by 3.5, we get: x = 16.\nThe value of x is 16.\n#### 16\nThe answer is: 16"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1446950", "question": "Write a Python script that serves as a server-side utility for creating and restoring elastic snapshots. The script should be able to handle the following functionalities:\n- Creating a new snapshot\n- Listing existing snapshots to restore from\n- Restoring a snapshot from a specified repository\n\nThe script should be able to accept command-line arguments for the following options:\n- Name of the repository to store the snapshot in\n- Name of the snapshot\n- URL to the Elastic cluster\n- Location path matching one of the paths defined as path.repo in /etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml\n\nThe script should be able to connect to an Elasticsearch cluster using the elasticsearch package and perform the specified actions based on the command-line arguments provided.", "answer": "```python\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\nfrom elasticsearch import Elasticsearch, exceptions\nfrom datetime import datetime\nimport argparse\n\ndef main():\n\tparser_desc = \"Server-side utility for creating and restoring elastic snapshots. NOTE: Be sure to set path.repo in elasticsearch.yml before attempting to use this tool.\"\n\tparser_epil = \"Be sure that you're running this from within the virtual environment for the server.\"\n\tparser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=parser_desc, epilog=parser_epil)\n\texgroup = parser.add_mutually_exclusive_group(required=True) # we need to specify either create or restore\n\tparser.add_argument(\"-r\", \"--repo\", metavar='REPO', help=\"Name of the repository to store our snapshot in\", default=\"natlas_backups\")\n\tparser.add_argument(\"-s\", \"--snapshot\", metavar='SNAPSHOT', help=\"Name of the snapshot\", default=\"snapshot-\")\n\tparser.add_argument(\"-e\", \"--elastic\", metavar=\"URL\", help=\"URL to Elastic cluster\", default=\"http://localhost:9200\")\n\tparser.add_argument(\"-l\", \"--location\", metavar=\"PATH\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\thelp=\"A path matching one of the paths defined as path.repo in /etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\tdefault=\"/tmp/natlas\")\n\texgroup.add_argument(\"--restore\", action='store_true', default=False, help=\"If you pass this flag, we will attempt to restore the snapshot named by --snapshot\")\n\texgroup.add_argument('--create', action='store_true', default=False, help=\"Create a new snapshot\")\n\texgroup.add_argument(\"--list\", action='store_true', default=False, help=\"List existing snapshots to restore from\")\n\targs = parser.parse_args()\n\n\tes = Elasticsearch(args.elastic)\n\n\tif args.create:\n\t\tbody = {\"type\": \"fs\",\n\t\t\t\t\"settings\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\"location\": args.location\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\tprint(\"[+]Checking to see if repository named %s exists\" % args.repo)\n\t\ttry:\n\t\t\tprint(es.snapshot.get_repository(args.repo))\n\t\texcept Exception:\n\t\t\tprint(\"[+]Creating Repository named: %s\" % args.repo)\n\t\t\tprint(es.snapshot.create_repository(args.repo, body, verify=True))\n\t\t\tprint(\"[+]Repository Information: %s\" % args.repo)\n\t\t\tprint(es.snapshot.get_repository(args.repo))\n\t\tif args.snapshot == \"snapshot-\":\n\t\t\tsnapshot_name = args.snapshot + datetime.utcnow().strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d-%H-%M-%S\")\n\t\telse:\n\t\t\tsnapshot_name = args.snapshot\n\t\tprint(\"[+]Creating Snapshot named %s. This may take a while...\" % snapshot_name)\n\t\tprint(es.snapshot.create(args.repo, snapshot_name, wait_for_completion=True))\n\t\tprint(\"[+]Getting details for snapshot named %s\" % snapshot_name)\n\t\tprint(es.snapshot.get(args.repo, snapshot_name, verbose=True))\n\tif args.list:\n\t\tprint(\"[+]Listing repositories and snapshots\")\n\t\trepositories = es.snapshot.get_repository(\"*\")\n\t\tfor item in repositories:\n\t\t\tprint(\"-%s\" % item)\n\t\t\tsnapshots = es.snapshot.get(item, \"*\")\n\t\t\tfor snap in snapshots[\"snapshots\"]:\n\t\t\t\tprint(\"--%s\" % snap[\"snapshot\"])\n\tif args.restore:\n\t\tprint(\"[+] Checking to see if repository named %s