{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_20449", "question": "More than 300 barrel jellyfish washed up in New Quay, Ceredigion.\nAnd in Pembrokeshire there have been sightings in Tenby, Saundersfoot and Newport.\nSarah Perry from Cardigan Bay Marine Wildlife Centre said: \"This is definitely a mega swarm. I have never seen them this big before.\"\nShe said the creatures do wash up each year but added that this was \"unusual because of the number on our shores and the size of them\".\nMs Perry said she believed the recent warm weather had sparked the boom in jellyfish, which can grow up to 88cm (35in) in diameter.\nNumbers have grown in recent years because of mild winters allowing plankton, their main food source, to thrive.\nHolidaymaker Wilson Dyer, from Suffolk, said: \"I've been holidaying here for 40 years and I've never seen this before.\n\"They're all the way up the Cardigan Bay coast. It's intriguing, it looks like they all keeled over at the same time.\"\nConservationist Ms Perry said the abundance of washed up jellyfish could attract feeding leatherback turtles which would be an \"amazing sight\".\nShe encouraged the public not to move or touch the jellyfish.\n\"While they're relatively harmless they can, if touched, leave you with a rash similar to what you may get after touching a stingy nettle,\" she said.\nWhat was that article about?", "answer": "Thousands of jellyfish have washed up on beaches in Pembrokeshire and Ceredigion in what a conservationist has described as a \"mega swarm\"."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_24538", "question": "Each of the cucumbers in 100 pounds of cucumbers is composed of 99% water, by weight. After some of the water evaporates, the cucumbers are now a certain percentage of water by weight. The new weight of the cucumbers is 20 pounds. What is the new percentage of water in the cucumbers?", "answer": "Let's start by determining the weight of the water and the weight of the solid part of the cucumbers before any water evaporates.\n\nInitially, the cucumbers are 99% water by weight. This means that for every 100 pounds of cucumbers, 99 pounds are water and the remaining 1 pound is the solid part of the cucumbers.\n\nNow, after some of the water evaporates, the total weight of the cucumbers is reduced to 20 pounds. However, the weight of the solid part does not change because only water evaporates. So, the solid part still weighs 1 pound.\n\nTo find the new percentage of water in the cucumbers, we need to calculate the weight of the water in the cucumbers after evaporation. Since the total weight after evaporation is 20 pounds and the solid part is 1 pound, the weight of the water is:\n\n20 pounds (total weight) - 1 pound (solid part) = 19 pounds (water)\n\nNow, we can calculate the new percentage of water by weight:\n\n(Weight of water / Total weight) * 100 = New percentage of water\n(19 pounds / 20 pounds) * 100 = 95%\n\nSo, the new percentage of water in the cucumbers after evaporation is 95%."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_63573", "question": "Let $n$ be a  positive integer and $a$ be an integer such that $a$ is its own inverse modulo $n$. What is the remainder when $a^2$ is divided by $n$?", "answer": "Since $a$ is its own inverse modulo $n$, we have $a^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{n}$.\nThis means that $n$ divides $a^2 - 1 = (a-1)(a+1)$.\nSince $n$ is a positive integer, it cannot divide both $a-1$ and $a+1$.\nTherefore, either $n$ divides $a-1$ or $n$ divides $a+1$.\nIn either case, we have $a^2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{n}$, so the remainder when $a^2$ is divided by $n$ is $\\boxed{1}$.\nThe answer is: 1"}
