{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_952071", "question": "In a survey, 210 school students were asked if they preferred windows or mac brand computers. 60 students claimed that they preferred mac to windows brand computers. One third as many of the students who preferred mac to windows, equally preferred both brands. How many students had no preference?", "answer": "Let's break down the information given:\n\n- 60 students preferred Mac to Windows.\n- One third as many of the students who preferred Mac to Windows equally preferred both brands. This means that 1/3 of 60 students equally preferred both brands. So, 60 / 3 = 20 students equally preferred both brands.\n\nNow, we have the number of students who preferred Mac and the number who equally preferred both. To find out how many students had no preference, we need to subtract the number of students who had a preference (either for Mac or for both) from the total number of students surveyed.\n\nTotal number of students surveyed = 210\nNumber of students who preferred Mac = 60\nNumber of students who equally preferred both = 20\n\nNumber of students who had a preference (either for Mac or for both) = 60 (Mac preference) + 20 (both preference) = 80\n\nNumber of students with no preference = Total number of students surveyed - Number of students who had a preference\nNumber of students with no preference = 210 - 80 = 130\n\nSo, 130 students had no preference between Windows or Mac brand computers."}
