{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_476095", "question": "A man completes a journey in 10 hours. He travels the first half of the journey at a certain speed and the second half at the rate of 24 km/hr. The total journey is 224 km. What was his speed during the first half of the journey?", "answer": "Let's denote the speed during the first half of the journey as \\( v \\) km/hr.\n\nSince the total journey is 224 km, the first half of the journey is \\( \\frac{224}{2} = 112 \\) km, and the second half is also 112 km.\n\nThe time taken to complete the second half of the journey at 24 km/hr is \\( \\frac{112}{24} \\) hours.\n\nNow, the total time for the journey is 10 hours, so the time taken for the first half of the journey is \\( 10 - \\frac{112}{24} \\) hours.\n\nThe speed during the first half of the journey is the distance of the first half divided by the time taken for the first half, so we have:\n\n\\[ v = \\frac{112}{10 - \\frac{112}{24}} \\]\n\nTo solve for \\( v \\), we first simplify the denominator:\n\n\\[ 10 - \\frac{112}{24} = \\frac{240}{24} - \\frac{112}{24} = \\frac{240 - 112}{24} = \\frac{128}{24} \\]\n\nNow we can find \\( v \\):\n\n\\[ v = \\frac{112}{\\frac{128}{24}} \\]\n\nTo divide by a fraction, we multiply by its reciprocal:\n\n\\[ v = 112 \\times \\frac{24}{128} \\]\n\nSimplify the fraction:\n\n\\[ v = 112 \\times \\frac{3}{16} \\]\n\n\\[ v = 7 \\times 3 \\]\n\n\\[ v = 21 \\]\n\nSo, the speed during the first half of the journey was 21 km/hr."}
