{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1422057", "question": "Drum X is 1/2 full of oil and Drum Y is 1/2 full of oil. If all of the oil in Drum X is poured into Drum Y, then Drum Y will be filled to 0.75 capacity. What is the ratio of the capacity of Drum Y to the capacity of Drum X?", "answer": "Let's denote the capacity of Drum X as \\( C_X \\) and the capacity of Drum Y as \\( C_Y \\).\n\nAccording to the problem, Drum X is \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\) full, so it contains \\( \\frac{1}{2}C_X \\) of oil.\n\nDrum Y is also \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\) full, so it initially contains \\( \\frac{1}{2}C_Y \\) of oil.\n\nWhen all the oil from Drum X is poured into Drum Y, the total amount of oil in Drum Y becomes \\( \\frac{1}{2}C_Y + \\frac{1}{2}C_X \\).\n\nWe are told that this total amount of oil fills Drum Y to 0.75 (or \\( \\frac{3}{4} \\)) of its capacity. Therefore, we can write the equation:\n\n\\[ \\frac{1}{2}C_Y + \\frac{1}{2}C_X = \\frac{3}{4}C_Y \\]\n\nNow, we can solve for \\( C_X \\) in terms of \\( C_Y \\):\n\n\\[ \\frac{1}{2}C_X = \\frac{3}{4}C_Y - \\frac{1}{2}C_Y \\]\n\\[ \\frac{1}{2}C_X = \\frac{1}{4}C_Y \\]\n\nMultiplying both sides by 2 to get rid of the fraction on the left side, we get:\n\n\\[ C_X = \\frac{1}{2}C_Y \\]\n\nThis means that the capacity of Drum X is half the capacity of Drum Y. Therefore, the ratio of the capacity of Drum Y to the capacity of Drum X is:\n\n\\[ \\frac{C_Y}{C_X} = \\frac{C_Y}{\\frac{1}{2}C_Y} = 2 \\]\n\nSo, the ratio of the capacity of Drum Y to Drum X is 2:1."}
