{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_119881", "question": "A patient is given a mixture of two medications daily. Medication A contains 40% pain killer and medication B contains 20% pain killer. The patient receives exactly 215 milliliters of pain killer daily. There are 425 milliliters of medication B in the mixture. How many milliliters of the mixture is given to the patient daily?", "answer": "Let's denote the total milliliters of the mixture given to the patient daily as \\( x \\).\n\nMedication A contains 40% pain killer, and medication B contains 20% pain killer. The patient receives 425 milliliters of medication B, which contributes to the total pain killer amount.\n\nThe amount of pain killer in medication B is \\( 0.20 \\times 425 \\) milliliters.\n\nThe remaining amount of pain killer comes from medication A, which is \\( x - 425 \\) milliliters of medication A in the mixture.\n\nThe amount of pain killer in medication A is \\( 0.40 \\times (x - 425) \\) milliliters.\n\nThe total amount of pain killer from both medications is 215 milliliters, so we can set up the following equation:\n\n\\[ 0.20 \\times 425 + 0.40 \\times (x - 425) = 215 \\]\n\nNow, let's solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\[ 0.20 \\times 425 + 0.40x - 0.40 \\times 425 = 215 \\]\n\n\\[ 85 + 0.40x - 170 = 215 \\]\n\n\\[ 0.40x - 85 = 215 \\]\n\n\\[ 0.40x = 215 + 85 \\]\n\n\\[ 0.40x = 300 \\]\n\n\\[ x = \\frac{300}{0.40} \\]\n\n\\[ x = 750 \\]\n\nSo, the patient is given 750 milliliters of the mixture daily."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_792737", "question": "How can I run a script with elevated privilege on Windows for a pyqt application I am writing that requires executing admin tasks? I have attempted to use the solution suggested in this Stack Overflow question: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/130763/request-uac-elevation-from-within-a-python-script. \n\nI have placed the following code at the top of my main file:\n\n```python\nimport os\nimport sys\nimport win32com.shell.shell as shell\nASADMIN = 'asadmin'\n\nif sys.argv[-1] != ASADMIN:\n    script = os.path.abspath(sys.argv[0])\n    params = ' '.join([script] + sys.argv[1:] + [ASADMIN])\n    shell.ShellExecuteEx(lpVerb='runas', lpFile=sys.executable, lpParameters=params)\n    sys.exit(0)\nprint \"I am root now.\"\n```\n\nHowever, while it does ask for permission to elevate, the print line never gets executed. Can someone assist me in running this code successfully?", "answer": "The problem you're facing is due to the fact that you're adding 'asadmin' as a parameter and then checking if the last parameter is 'asadmin'. The script gets called twice, but the second time, 'asadmin' is present as the parameter, so it doesn't go into the if block. Hence, the 'print' statement never gets executed.\n\nTo resolve this issue, you need to modify the code to remove the 'asadmin' parameter after it gets executed the first time. This ensures that the 'print' statement gets executed the second time. Here's how you can achieve this:\n\n```python\nimport os\nimport sys\nimport win32com.shell.shell as shell\nASADMIN = 'asadmin'\n\nif sys.argv[-1] == ASADMIN:\n    # The script was run with admin rights\n    sys.argv.pop()  # remove 'asadmin' from the argument list\n    print \"I am root now.\"\nelse:\n    # The script was run without admin rights\n    script = os.path.abspath(sys.argv[0])\n    params = ' '.join([script] + sys.argv[1:] + [ASADMIN])\n    shell.ShellExecuteEx(lpVerb='runas', lpFile=sys.executable, lpParameters=params)\n    sys.exit(0)\n```\n\nThis code first checks if the last argument is 'asadmin'. If it is, it removes 'asadmin' from the argument list and prints \"I am root now.\". If not, it elevates the script's privileges and reruns the script with 'asadmin' as the last argument."}
