{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_969250", "question": "Henry went to the beach and picked up 17 perfect shells and 52 broken shells. Out of those 52 broken shells, half of them were spiral. Out of the 17 perfect shells, 12 of them were not spiral. How many more broken spiral shells were there than perfect spiral shells?", "answer": "Out of the 52 broken shells, half of them were spiral, so there were 52/2 = 26 broken spiral shells.\nOut of the 17 perfect shells, 12 of them were not spiral, so there were 17-12 = 5 perfect spiral shells.\nThe difference between the number of broken spiral shells and perfect spiral shells is 26-5 = 21.\nSo, there were 21 more broken spiral shells than perfect spiral shells.\n#### 21\nThe answer is: 21"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_884876", "question": "The shopkeeper increased the price of a product by 25% so that the customer finds it difficult to purchase the required amount. The customer managed to purchase only 76% of the required amount. What is the net difference in the expenditure on that product?", "answer": "Let's assume the original price of the product is \\( P \\) and the original required amount is \\( Q \\).\n\nThe original expenditure on the product would be:\n\\[ \\text{Original Expenditure} = P \\times Q \\]\n\nAfter the price increase of 25%, the new price of the product becomes:\n\\[ \\text{New Price} = P + \\frac{25}{100} \\times P = P \\times (1 + 0.25) = P \\times 1.25 \\]\n\nThe customer purchases only 76% of the required amount, so the new quantity is:\n\\[ \\text{New Quantity} = Q \\times \\frac{76}{100} = Q \\times 0.76 \\]\n\nThe new expenditure on the product would be:\n\\[ \\text{New Expenditure} = \\text{New Price} \\times \\text{New Quantity} = P \\times 1.25 \\times Q \\times 0.76 \\]\n\nTo find the net difference in the expenditure, we subtract the original expenditure from the new expenditure:\n\\[ \\text{Net Difference} = \\text{New Expenditure} - \\text{Original Expenditure} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Net Difference} = (P \\times 1.25 \\times Q \\times 0.76) - (P \\times Q) \\]\n\nNow, let's factor out \\( P \\times Q \\) from both terms:\n\\[ \\text{Net Difference} = P \\times Q \\times (1.25 \\times 0.76 - 1) \\]\n\nCalculating the value inside the parentheses:\n\\[ 1.25 \\times 0.76 = 0.95 \\]\n\nSo the net difference is:\n\\[ \\text{Net Difference} = P \\times Q \\times (0.95 - 1) \\]\n\\[ \\text{Net Difference} = P \\times Q \\times (-0.05) \\]\n\nThis means the net difference in the expenditure is a 5% decrease from the original expenditure. The customer spends 5% less than what they would have spent if they had purchased the full amount at the original price."}
