{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1041660", "question": "You are working on a research project involving statistical simulations, and you need to create visualizations for the results. The code snippet provided includes calls to three functions: `make_power_figures`, `make_null_figures`, and `make_EW_figures`. These functions are responsible for generating different types of figures using specified colors and a results directory.\n\nYour task is to implement the `make_power_figures`, `make_null_figures`, and `make_EW_figures` functions to create the required visualizations based on the given colors and results directory. Each function has a specific purpose:\n- `make_power_figures`: Generate power figures using the provided colors and save them in the results directory.\n- `make_null_figures`: Generate null figures and save them in the results directory.\n- `make_EW_figures`: Generate EW (Expected Wins) figures using the specified colors and save them in the results directory.\n\nYou need to write the implementations for these functions to produce the required visualizations based on the given colors and results directory.", "answer": "```python\nimport os\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\ndef make_power_figures(colors, results_dir):\n    # Create power figures using the specified colors\n    for i, color in enumerate(colors):\n        # Generate power figure using color\n        fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n        ax.set_facecolor('lightgray')  # Set background color\n        ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color=color, linewidth=2)  # Example plot\n        ax.set_title(f'Power Figure {i+1}')  # Set title\n        # Save the figure in the results directory\n        fig.savefig(os.path.join(results_dir, f'power_figure_{i+1}.png'))\n        plt.close(fig)  # Close the figure to release memory\n\ndef make_null_figures(results_dir):\n    # Create null figures\n    for i in range(3):  # Generate 3 null figures\n        fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n        ax.set_facecolor('lightgray')  # Set background color\n        ax.text(0.5, 0.5, 'Null Figure', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12, color='black')  # Example text\n        ax.set_title(f'Null Figure {i+1}')  # Set title\n        # Save the figure in the results directory\n        fig.savefig(os.path.join(results_dir, f'null_figure_{i+1}.png'))\n        plt.close(fig)  # Close the figure to release memory\n\ndef make_EW_figures(colors, results_dir):\n    # Create EW figures using the specified colors\n    for i, color in enumerate(colors):\n        # Generate EW figure using color\n        fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n        ax.set_facecolor('lightgray')  # Set background color\n        ax.plot([0, 1], [1, 0], color=color, linewidth=2)  # Example plot\n        ax.set_title(f'EW Figure {i+1}')  # Set title\n        # Save the figure in the results directory\n        fig.savefig(os.path.join(results_dir, f'EW_figure_{i+1}.png'))\n        plt.close(fig)  # Close the figure to release memory\n```\nIn the solution, the `make_power_figures`, `make_null_figures`, and `make_EW_figures` functions are implemented to create power figures, null figures, and EW figures, respectively. Each function uses the specified colors and saves the generated figures in the provided results directory. The figures are created using matplotlib and saved as PNG files."}
