{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1278942", "question": "In his company, Kenzo has 80 office chairs with a certain number of legs each and 20 round tables with three legs each. After a month, 40% of the chairs are damaged and have to be disposed of. Kenzo has a total of 300 legs of furniture remaining in his company. How many legs does each office chair have?", "answer": "Let's denote the number of legs each office chair has as \\( x \\).\n\nInitially, Kenzo has 80 office chairs, so the total number of legs for the chairs is \\( 80x \\).\n\nHe also has 20 round tables with 3 legs each, so the total number of legs for the tables is \\( 20 \\times 3 = 60 \\).\n\nAfter 40% of the chairs are damaged, 60% of the chairs remain. The number of remaining chairs is \\( 60\\% \\times 80 = 0.6 \\times 80 = 48 \\).\n\nThe total number of legs for the remaining chairs is \\( 48x \\).\n\nAccording to the information given, after disposing of the damaged chairs, Kenzo has a total of 300 legs of furniture remaining. This includes the legs of the remaining chairs and the legs of all the tables. So we can write the equation:\n\n\\( 48x + 60 = 300 \\)\n\nNow, let's solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\( 48x = 300 - 60 \\)\n\n\\( 48x = 240 \\)\n\n\\( x = \\frac{240}{48} \\)\n\n\\( x = 5 \\)\n\nTherefore, each office chair has 5 legs."}
