{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_435891", "question": "Hallie borrows a book from the library. She reads the entire book in four days. She read x pages the first day. On the second day, she read twice the number of pages that she'd read on day one. On the third day, she read 10 mores pages than she read on day two. If the book is 354 pages long, how many pages did she read on the fourth day?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 29, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "We know that Hallie read the entire book in four days, which means she read 354 pages in total.\nOn the first day, she read x pages.\nOn the second day, she read twice the number of pages she read on day one, which means she read 2x pages.\nOn the third day, she read 10 more pages than she read on day two, which means she read 2x + 10 pages.\nThe total number of pages she read in the first three days is x + 2x + (2x + 10) = 5x + 10.\nTo find out how many pages she read on the fourth day, we can subtract the total number of pages she read in the first three days from the total number of pages in the book: 354 - (5x + 10) = 344 - 5x.\nWe are given that she read 29 pages on the fourth day, so we can write: 344 - 5x = 29.\nSolving for x, we get: x = 63.\nThe value of x is 63.\n#### 63\nThe answer is: 63"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_18373", "question": "Janeth bought 5 bags of round balloons with x balloons in each bag. She also bought 4 bags of long balloons with 30 balloons in each bag. While blowing up the balloons, 5 round balloons burst. How many balloons are left?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 215, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "Janeth bought 5 bags of round balloons with x balloons in each bag, so she bought a total of 5x round balloons.\nShe also bought 4 bags of long balloons with 30 balloons in each bag, so she bought a total of 4 * 30 = 120 long balloons.\nThe total number of balloons Janeth bought is the sum of the round balloons and the long balloons: 5x + 120.\nWhile blowing up the balloons, 5 round balloons burst, so the number of balloons left is: 5x + 120 - 5 = 5x + 115.\nWe are given that the number of balloons left is 215, so we can write: 5x + 115 = 215.\nSolving for x, we get: 5x = 100.\nDividing both sides by 5, we get: x = 20.\nThe value of x is 20.\n#### 20\nThe answer is: 20"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_724892", "question": "In the game of Frood, dropping $n$ froods gives a score of the sum of the first $n$ positive integers. For example, dropping five froods scores $1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5 = 15$ points. Eating $n$ froods earns $10n$ points. For example, eating five froods earns $10(5) = 50$ points. What is the least number of froods for which dropping them will earn more points than eating them?", "answer": "Dropping $n$ froods earns $\\frac{n(n+1)}{2}$ points, while eating $n$ froods earns $10n$ points.\nWe want to find the least $n$ such that $\\frac{n(n+1)}{2} > 10n$.\nMultiplying both sides by 2 gives $n(n+1) > 20n$.\nExpanding and rearranging, we have $n^2 - 19n > 0$.\nFactoring out an $n$, we get $n(n-19) > 0$.\nSince neither $n$ nor $n-19$ can be zero, the inequality holds true for $n > 19$.\nTherefore, the least number of froods for which dropping them will earn more points than eating them is $\\boxed{20}$.\nThe answer is: 20"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1199937", "question": "Could you help me write this in Lua?\ndef advanced_vowels_count(s):\n    if not isinstance(s, str):\n        raise TypeError(\"Input must be a string.\")\n    \n    vowels = 'aeiou'\n    s = s.lower() # convert the string to lowercase for easy comparison\n    count = sum(1 for char in s if char in vowels)\n    # consider 'y' as a vowel only if it is at the end of the string\n    if s[-1] == 'y':\n        count += 1\n    return count\nPlease annotate the Lua code to make it easier for me to grasp.", "answer": "Certainly! Below is the annotated Lua code equivalent to the provided Python function:\n\n```lua\n-- Define a function named advanced_vowels_count that takes a single parameter 's'\nfunction advanced_vowels_count(s)\n    -- Check if the input is a string, if not, raise a TypeError\n    if type(s) ~= \"string\" then\n        error(\"Input must be a string.\", 2)\n    end\n    \n    -- Define a variable 'vowels' containing all vowels\n    local vowels = \"aeiou\"\n    \n    -- Convert the input string to lowercase for easier comparison\n    s = string.lower(s)\n    \n    -- Initialize a variable 'count' to store the count of vowels in the string\n    local count = 0\n    \n    -- Iterate over each character in the string\n    for i = 1, #s do\n        -- Check if the character is a vowel\n        if string.find(vowels, s:sub(i, i), 1, true) then\n            count = count + 1\n        end\n    end\n    \n    -- Consider 'y' as a vowel only if it is at the end of the string\n    if s:sub(-1) == 'y' then\n        count = count + 1\n    end\n    \n    -- Return the final count of vowels\n    return count\nend\n\n-- Example usage\nprint(advanced_vowels_count(\"Hello World\"))  -- Output: 3\n```\n\nIn this Lua code:\n- We define a function `advanced_vowels_count` that takes a string parameter `s`.\n- We check if the input is a string. If not, we raise an error.\n- We define a variable `vowels` containing all vowels.\n- We convert the input string to lowercase using `string.lower`.\n- We initialize a `count` variable to store the count of vowels.\n- We iterate over each character in the string and check if it is a vowel.\n- If the character is a vowel, we increment the `count`.\n- We consider 'y' as a vowel only if it is at the end of the string.\n- Finally, we return the count of vowels in the string.\n\nYou can test this Lua code with different input strings to verify its correctness."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_342271", "question": "How can I create an HTML web page with a text input and a submit button, and display an alert message with the value in the input field when the button is clicked?", "answer": "You can achieve this by using HTML and JavaScript. Here's an example code that you can use:\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n<head>\n <title>Input Form</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n <form>\n  <input type=\"text\" id=\"textInput\" name=\"inputValue\" />\n  <input type=\"submit\" value=\"Submit\" onClick=\"alertInputValue()\" />\n </form>\n\n <script>\n  function alertInputValue() {\n   let inputValue = document.getElementById(\"textInput\").value;\n   alert(inputValue);\n  }\n </script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\nIn this code, we have an HTML form with a text input field and a submit button. The `onClick` attribute in the submit button tells the browser to call the `alertInputValue()` function when it is clicked.\n\nInside the `alertInputValue()` function, we retrieve the value of the input field using `document.getElementById(\"textInput\").value`. This gets the element with the id \"textInput\" and retrieves its value property.\n\nFinally, we display an alert message with the input value using `alert(inputValue)`. This will show a popup box with the value that the user entered in the input field.\n\nYou can simply copy this code and save it as an HTML file to see it in action. When you open the file in a web browser, you'll see the text input and submit button. Try entering some text in the input field and hitting the submit button to see the alert message with the entered value."}
