{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_53760", "question": "If the sum of two numbers, x and y, is 399 and the value of the fraction x/y is 0.9, what is the value of y - x?", "answer": "We have the equations $x + y = 399$ and $\\frac{x}{y} = 0.9$.\nWe can rewrite the second equation as $x = 0.9y$.\nSubstituting this into the first equation, we get $0.9y + y = 399$.\nCombining like terms, we have $1.9y = 399$.\nDividing both sides by 1.9, we find $y = \\frac{399}{1.9} = 210$.\nSubstituting this back into the first equation, we find $x + 210 = 399$.\nSubtracting 210 from both sides, we get $x = 189$.\nFinally, we can find $y - x$ by subtracting x from y: $y - x = 210 - 189 = \\boxed{21}$.\nThe answer is: 21"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1143608", "question": "I have a Maven project with a main project A and modules B and C. The children inherit from A's pom. It already builds jars for all the modules. Is there a way to include the dependencies in those jars, such as getting `B-1.0-with-dependencies.jar` and `C-1.0-with-dependencies.jar`? I have tried setting the `maven-assembly-plugin` in the parent pom, but it doesn't seem to work. The build succeeds, but I still get regular jars without dependencies. I'd like to avoid putting something in each child pom since I have more than 2 modules. Can anyone help me figure out how to achieve this? Thanks!", "answer": "To include the dependencies in your module jars, you can configure the `maven-assembly-plugin` in your parent/aggregate pom.xml file. Here's a solution that should work for you:\n\nIn the aggregator/parent pom, add the following configuration:\n\n```xml\n<properties>\n    <skip.assembly>true</skip.assembly>\n</properties>\n\n<build>\n    <plugins>\n        <plugin>\n            <artifactId>maven-assembly-plugin</artifactId>\n            <version>2.6</version>\n            <configuration>\n                <descriptorRefs>\n                    <descriptorRef>jar-with-dependencies</descriptorRef>\n                </descriptorRefs>\n                <skipAssembly>${skip.assembly}</skipAssembly>\n            </configuration>\n            <executions>\n                <execution>\n                    <id>make-assembly</id>\n                    <phase>package</phase>\n                    <goals>\n                        <goal>single</goal>\n                    </goals>\n                </execution>\n            </executions>\n        </plugin>\n    </plugins>\n</build>\n```\n\nMake sure to note the `skip.assembly` property, which is set to `true` by default. This property is used to skip the assembly execution on the parent module since it doesn't provide any code (having packaging `pom`).\n\nThen, in each module (B and C), you can simply add the following configuration:\n\n```xml\n<properties>\n    <skip.assembly>false</skip.assembly>\n</properties>\n```\n\nThis configuration disables the skip on each submodule and allows the assembly to be executed as configured in the parent. It also provides flexibility if you want to skip the assembly for a certain module.\n\nWith this setup, when you run `mvn clean package` or `mvn clean install`, the assembly plugin will be triggered automatically and the dependencies will be included in the generated jars for each module.\n\nI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_972203", "question": "Assuming that the prime numbers p = 7 and q = 11 are used to generate RSA encryption keys, what is the public key (e, n) and private key (d, n) for the encryption and decryption of messages, if n is the product of p and q? Also, if the message \"23\" is to be encrypted, what is the ciphertext?", "answer": "To generate the RSA encryption keys, we first need to calculate n, φ(n), and then find suitable values for e and d.\n\n1. Calculate n:\nn = p * q\nn = 7 * 11\nn = 77\n\n2. Calculate φ(n) (Euler's totient function):\nφ(n) = (p - 1) * (q - 1)\nφ(n) = (7 - 1) * (11 - 1)\nφ(n) = 6 * 10\nφ(n) = 60\n\n3. Choose a value for e such that 1 < e < φ(n) and gcd(e, φ(n)) = 1 (e and φ(n) are coprime):\nWe can choose e = 13, as gcd(13, 60) = 1.\n\n4. Calculate d such that (d * e) % φ(n) = 1:\nWe can use the Extended Euclidean Algorithm to find the modular inverse of e (mod φ(n)). In this case, d = 37, as (13 * 37) % 60 = 1.\n\nNow we have the public key (e, n) and private key (d, n):\nPublic key (e, n) = (13, 77)\nPrivate key (d, n) = (37, 77)\n\nTo encrypt the message \"23\", we use the public key (e, n) and the following formula:\nCiphertext = (Message ^ e) % n\nCiphertext = (23 ^ 13) % 77\nCiphertext = 62\n\nSo, the encrypted message (ciphertext) is 62."}
