{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1272001", "question": "What is the correct command to compile a C++ program on a Linux operating system using g++ compiler with optimization flags enabled, producing a static binary executable, while also specifying the target architecture as x86_64 and linking with an external library named \"libfoo.a\"?", "answer": "The correct command to compile a C++ program on a Linux operating system using g++ compiler with optimization flags enabled, producing a static binary executable, while also specifying the target architecture as x86_64 and linking with an external library named \"libfoo.a\" is as follows:\n\n```bash\ng++ -O2 -march=x86-64 -o output_binary source_file.cpp -L/path/to/library -lfoo\n```\n\nExplanation of the flags used:\n- `-O2` enables level 2 optimization flags for improved performance.\n- `-march=x86-64` specifies the target architecture as x86_64.\n- `-o output_binary` specifies the name of the output binary file.\n- `source_file.cpp` is the name of the C++ source file to compile.\n- `-L/path/to/library` specifies the directory where the external library \"libfoo.a\" is located.\n- `-lfoo` links with the library named \"libfoo.a\". Note that the \"lib\" prefix and \".a\" extension are automatically added by the linker."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_710115", "question": "def remove_tuple_elements(input_list: list) -> tuple:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a list, remove all elements that are tuples and return a tuple containing the removed elements.\n\n    Args:\n    input_list (list): The list to be processed.\n\n    Returns:\n    tuple: A tuple containing the removed elements.\n\n    Example:\n    remove_tuple_elements([1, 2, (3, 4), 5, (6, 7)]) -> ((3, 4), (6, 7))\n\n    Note:\n    - Do not use built-in functions or methods that directly remove elements from a list.\n    - Elements can be nested tuples as well.\n    - Preserve the order of the removed elements in the resulting tuple.\n    \"\"\"", "answer": "removed_elements = []  # List to store the removed elements\n\n    # Iterate through the input list in reverse order to avoid index shifting after removal\n    for i in range(len(input_list)-1, -1, -1):\n        if isinstance(input_list[i], tuple):\n            removed_elements.append(input_list.pop(i))  # Remove and append the tuple element\n\n    return tuple(removed_elements)"}
