{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1218964", "question": "If the total number of Oreos is 36 and James has 3 more than 2 times the number of Oreos Jordan has, how many Oreos does Jordan have?", "answer": "Let's assume the number of Oreos Jordan has is J.\nAccording to the given information, James has 3 more than 2 times the number of Oreos Jordan has. So, James has 2J + 3 Oreos.\nThe total number of Oreos is 36, so we can set up an equation: J + (2J + 3) = 36.\nSimplifying the equation, we get 3J + 3 = 36.\nSubtracting 3 from both sides of the equation, we get 3J = 33.\nDividing both sides of the equation by 3, we get J = 11.\nTherefore, Jordan has 11 Oreos.\n#### 11\nThe answer is: 11"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_314818", "question": "If Beth purchased 15 more cans of peas than twice the number of cans of corn she bought, and she bought 35 cans of peas, what is the number of cans of corn that she purchased?", "answer": "Let's assume the number of cans of corn that Beth purchased is C.\nTwice the number of cans of corn she bought is 2C.\nBeth purchased 15 more cans of peas than twice the number of cans of corn she bought, so 35 = 2C + 15.\nSubtracting 15 from both sides of the equation, we get 20 = 2C.\nDividing both sides of the equation by 2, we get C = 10.\nTherefore, Beth purchased 10 cans of corn.\n#### 10\nThe answer is: 10"}
