{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_48054", "question": "Martiza is studying for the citizenship test. There are 60 questions on the test. 30 are multiple-choice and 30 are fill-in-the-blank. It takes her some minutes to learn each multiple-choice question and 25 minutes each to learn the fill-in-the-blank questions. She will need 20 hours to study before she is ready for the test. How many minutes does it take her to learn each multiple-choice question?", "answer": "Let's denote the time it takes Martiza to learn each multiple-choice question as \\( x \\) minutes.\n\nWe know that there are 30 multiple-choice questions and 30 fill-in-the-blank questions. It takes her \\( x \\) minutes for each multiple-choice question and 25 minutes for each fill-in-the-blank question.\n\nThe total time she spends studying for multiple-choice questions is \\( 30x \\) minutes, and for fill-in-the-blank questions, it is \\( 30 \\times 25 \\) minutes.\n\nWe are given that she needs 20 hours to study for the test. Since there are 60 minutes in an hour, 20 hours is equivalent to \\( 20 \\times 60 = 1200 \\) minutes.\n\nThe total study time is the sum of the time spent on multiple-choice questions and fill-in-the-blank questions, which should equal 1200 minutes:\n\n\\[ 30x + (30 \\times 25) = 1200 \\]\n\nNow, let's solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\[ 30x + 750 = 1200 \\]\n\nSubtract 750 from both sides:\n\n\\[ 30x = 1200 - 750 \\]\n\n\\[ 30x = 450 \\]\n\nNow, divide both sides by 30 to find \\( x \\):\n\n\\[ x = \\frac{450}{30} \\]\n\n\\[ x = 15 \\]\n\nSo, it takes Martiza 15 minutes to learn each multiple-choice question."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1172851", "question": "What are some tips for selecting the best ski equipment for casual skiers on a budget?", "answer": "1. Look for last year's models: You can often find great equipment at discounted prices by purchasing gear from the previous ski season. This is a great way to save money, especially if you're not too concerned about having the latest and greatest gear.\n\n2. Rent gear instead of buying: If you're only planning on skiing a few times a year, consider renting your equipment instead of purchasing it. This can save you money in the short-term, and you'll have the option to upgrade your gear as your skills improve.\n\n3. Purchase used gear: If you're on a tight budget, buying used gear can be a great option. Just be sure to inspect the equipment carefully before making a purchase.\n\n4. Look for deals and discounts: Many ski resorts and equipment retailers offer sales, promotions, and discounts throughout the year. Signing up for newsletters and checking social media pages can help you stay up-to-date on these deals.\n\n5. Focus on the essentials: When purchasing ski equipment, prioritize the essentials such as skis, boots, and poles. You can always add additional gear (such as clothing or accessories) later on.\n\n6. Try before you buy: If possible, test out equipment before making a purchase. Many ski shops offer demos or rental programs that allow you to try out different gear to see what works best for you. \n\n7. Consider purchasing a package deal: Some retailers will offer package deals on ski equipment, which can be a great way to save money. These bundles typically include skis, boots, and poles, and often come at a discounted price compared to buying each item separately."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_959446", "question": "A woman falls to the ground after receiving a blow to the head. Her attacker continues to circle above her, threatening more to come when she gets to her feet.\nIt is all taking place within Kabul's main stadium, the same place where the Taliban used to publicly flog and even execute women.\nThankfully the Taliban, who banned women from taking part in all sports, are long gone. Goodness knows what they would have to say about the scene in front of me.\nAbout 20 young women, wearing headscarves and bright orange boxing gloves, are trading the most unladylike of blows.\n\"The first punch that I got was on my nose and it hurt very much and it also bled and was very painful,\" says Sonaya, a teenager with long dark hair.\n\"But after a while the pain went away and I realised I could learn from that punch. It was the only punch in the face that I've had so far in here.\"\nShe takes her boxing seriously. Like others here she hopes to qualify for a future Olympics and has been training hard.\nI asked this rather shy looking girl with a sensitive smile whether she ever returned the favour.\n\"Yes, I have punched lots of girls on the nose,\" she says. Have you knocked anyone out? \"No, not yet.\" Are you working on it? \"Yes.\"\nIn a country where many husbands do not even allow their wives to leave their homes, never mind step into a boxing ring, what do Sonaya's family make of her chosen sport?\nAt first, she says, her father was very unhappy and frequently asked her to stop. But now he has accepted the idea on the grounds that the exercise is good for her health.\nMike Thomson reports from Afghanistan for the Today programme. Listen to his reports weekdays at 0600 GMT on BBC Radio 4\nAfghanistan's 'tough fight'\nThe street children of Kabul\n'I tried to burn myself to death'\nAnother member of her family took much less convincing.\n\"My mother has been encouraging me a lot. She tells me to practise hard and then