{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_954741", "question": "As a freelancer, Baylor is paid for every finished work of a client he does on a freelance marketplace. Currently, he has $4000 on his dashboard from previous work done. He is currently working for three clients, with the first client paying him half the amount of money he currently has on his dashboard once the job is done. The second client will pay him 2/5 times more money than the first client once Baylor finishes his work. The third client will pay him a certain multiple of the amount of money the first and second clients pay him together once he finishes the job. Baylor will have $18400 in his dashboard after all the clients pay him for his work. What is the multiple of the amount the third client pays him compared to the combined payment of the first and second clients?", "answer": "Let's break down the payments Baylor is expecting from each client.\n\n1. The first client will pay Baylor half the amount of money he currently has on his dashboard, which is $4000. So the first client will pay him:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{2} \\times 4000 = 2000 \\]\n\n2. The second client will pay Baylor 2/5 times more money than the first client. So the second client will pay him:\n\\[ \\frac{2}{5} \\times 2000 + 2000 = 800 + 2000 = 2800 \\]\n\n3. The third client's payment is a certain multiple of the amount the first and second clients pay him together. Let's call this multiple \"x\". So the third client will pay him:\n\\[ x \\times (2000 + 2800) = x \\times 4800 \\]\n\nNow, we know that after all the clients pay him, Baylor will have $18400 in his dashboard. We can set up an equation to find the value of x:\n\n\\[ 4000 + 2000 + 2800 + x \\times 4800 = 18400 \\]\n\nCombining the known payments, we get:\n\n\\[ 8800 + x \\times 4800 = 18400 \\]\n\nNow, let's solve for x:\n\n\\[ x \\times 4800 = 18400 - 8800 \\]\n\\[ x \\times 4800 = 9600 \\]\n\nDivide both sides by 4800 to find x:\n\n\\[ x = \\frac{9600}{4800} \\]\n\\[ x = 2 \\]\n\nSo, the multiple of the amount the third client pays him compared to the combined payment of the first and second clients is 2."}
