{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_297785", "question": "A contractor undertook to do a piece of work in 15 days. He employed 20 laborers, but a certain number of them were absent from the very first day, and the rest could finish the work in only 20 days. How many laborers were absent from the very first day?", "answer": "Let's denote the number of laborers absent from the very first day as \\( x \\).\n\nThe contractor originally planned to finish the work in 15 days with 20 laborers. This means the total amount of labor required to finish the work is \\( 20 \\text{ laborers} \\times 15 \\text{ days} = 300 \\text{ laborer-days} \\).\n\nHowever, due to the absence of \\( x \\) laborers, the remaining \\( 20 - x \\) laborers could only finish the work in 20 days. This means the total amount of labor with the reduced number of laborers is \\( (20 - x) \\text{ laborers} \\times 20 \\text{ days} \\).\n\nSince the amount of work is the same in both scenarios, we can set the two expressions equal to each other:\n\n\\[ 20 \\times 15 = (20 - x) \\times 20 \\]\n\nNow, let's solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\[ 300 = 20 \\times 20 - 20x \\]\n\\[ 300 = 400 - 20x \\]\n\\[ 20x = 400 - 300 \\]\n\\[ 20x = 100 \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{100}{20} \\]\n\\[ x = 5 \\]\n\nSo, 5 laborers were absent from the very first day."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1190573", "question": "Ramanujan and Hardy played a game where they both picked a complex number. If the product of their numbers was $32-8i$, and Hardy picked $5+3i$, what number did Ramanujan pick?", "answer": "Let Ramanujan's number be $a+bi$.\nWe are given that $(a+bi)(5+3i) = 32-8i$.\nExpanding, we get $(5a-3b) + (3a+5b)i = 32-8i$.\nThis gives us the system of equations\n\\begin{align*}\n5a-3b &= 32, \\\\\n3a+5b &= -8.\n\\end{align*}\nMultiplying the first equation by 3 and the second equation by 5, we can eliminate $b$ by adding the two equations:\n\\begin{align*}\n15a-9b &= 96, \\\\\n15a+25b &= -40.\n\\end{align*}\nSubtracting the first equation from the second equation, we get $34b = -136$, or $b = -4$.\nSubstituting this value of $b$ into the first equation, we get $5a - 3(-4) = 32$, or $5a + 12 = 32$.\nSolving for $a$, we find $a = 4$.\nTherefore, Ramanujan picked the number $\\boxed{4-4i}$.The answer is: 4-4i"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1459940", "question": "Caroline has 40 pairs of socks. She loses 4 pairs of socks at the laundromat. Of the remaining pairs of socks, she donates two-thirds to the thrift store. Then she purchases 10 new pairs of socks, and she receives x new pairs of socks as a gift from her dad. How many pairs of socks does Caroline have in total?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 25, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "Caroline starts with 40 pairs of socks.\nShe loses 4 pairs of socks, so she has 40 - 4 = 36 pairs of socks remaining.\nShe donates two-thirds of the remaining socks, which means she donates (2/3)*36 = 24 pairs of socks.\nAfter donating, she has 36 - 24 = 12 pairs of socks remaining.\nShe purchases 10 new pairs of socks, so she now has 12 + 10 = 22 pairs of socks.\nShe also receives x new pairs of socks as a gift from her dad, so the total number of pairs of socks she has is 22 + x.\nWe are given that the total number of pairs of socks she has is 25, so we can write: 22 + x = 25.\nSolving for x, we get: x = 3.\nThe value of x is 3.\n#### 3\nThe answer is: 3"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1148794", "question": "(3x + 2)(2x - 3) = ax^2 + kx + n. What is the value of a - n + k?", "answer": "To find the value of a - n + k, we first need to expand the expression (3x + 2)(2x - 3) and then compare it to the general form ax^2 + kx + n.\n\nExpanding (3x + 2)(2x - 3), we get:\n\n(3x + 2)(2x - 3) = 3x(2x) + 3x(-3) + 2(2x) + 2(-3)\n= 6x^2 - 9x + 4x - 6\n= 6x^2 - 5x - 6\n\nNow we compare this to the general form ax^2 + kx + n:\n\n6x^2 - 5x - 6 = ax^2 + kx + n\n\nFrom this comparison, we can see that:\na = 6\nk = -5\nn = -6\n\nNow we can calculate a - n + k:\n\na - n + k = 6 - (-6) + (-5)\n= 6 + 6 - 5\n= 12 - 5\n= 7\n\nTherefore, the value of a - n + k is 7."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_723531", "question": "Can you create a C++ algorithm that can identify the image format of a file without using any external libraries or APIs, including those from the operating system? The algorithm should be self-contained and not depend on any third-party tools. The algorithm must be able to identify specific image formats rather than just general ones.", "answer": "Yes, it is possible to create a C++ algorithm that can identify the image format of a file without using any external libraries or APIs. Here is a general approach to implement such an algorithm:\n\n1. Read the first few bytes of the file (usually 8-16 bytes) into a buffer. These bytes are called the \"magic number\" and contain specific values that identify the file format. The size of the magic number depends on the file format.\n\n2. Check the magic number against known values for different image formats. Here are some examples:\n\n   - JPEG: The magic number is \"FF D8 FF E0\" or \"FF D8 FF E1\".\n   - PNG: The magic number is \"89 50 4E 47 0D 0A 1A 0A\".\n   - BMP: The magic number is \"42 4D\".\n   - GIF: The magic number is either \"47 49 46 38 37 61\" (GIF87a) or \"47 49 46 38 39 61\" (GIF89a).\n\n   These are just a few examples. You can find the magic numbers for other image formats online.\n\n3. If the magic number matches a known value, then the file format can be identified. Otherwise, the algorithm cannot identify the file format.\n\nHere is an example implementation of this algorithm:\n\n```c++\n#include <iostream>\n#include <fstream>\n\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main(int argc, char* argv[])\n{\n    // Open the file for reading\n    ifstream file(argv[1], ios::binary);\n    if (!file)\n    {\n        cerr << \"Error: Cannot open file \" << argv[1] << endl;\n        return 1;\n    }\n\n    // Read the first few bytes into a buffer\n    char buffer[16];\n    file.read(buffer, sizeof(buffer));\n\n    // Check for known magic numbers\n    if (buffer[0] == 0xFF && buffer[1] == 0xD8 && buffer[2] == 0xFF &&\n        (buffer[3] == 0xE0 || buffer[3] == 0xE1)) {\n        cout << \"JPEG image detected.\" << endl;\n    }\n    else if (buffer[0] == 0x89 && buffer[1] == 0x50 && buffer[2] == 0x4E &&\n             buffer[3] == 0x47 && buffer[4] == 0x0D && buffer[5] == 0x0A &&\n             buffer[6] == 0x1A && buffer[7] == 0x0A) {\n        cout << \"PNG image detected.\" << endl;\n    }\n    else if (buffer[0] == 0x42 && buffer[1] == 0x4D) {\n        cout << \"BMP image detected.\" << endl;\n    }\n    else if (buffer[0] == 0x47 && buffer[1] == 0x49 && buffer[2] == 0x46 &&\n             buffer[3] == 0x38 && (buffer[4] == 0x37 || buffer[4] == 0x39) &&\n             buffer[5] == 0x61) {\n        cout << \"GIF image detected.\" << endl;\n    }\n    else {\n        cout << \"Unknown image format.\" << endl;\n    }\n\n    // Close the file\n    file.close();\n\n    return 0;\n}\n```"}
