{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_170300", "question": "Summarize this article in one sentence.\n\nA reports shows Stoke-on-Trent City Council planned to cut 14 of its 37 senior bosses, to save more than £1m.\nA report revealed a salary in the top tier would have become £131,500 on average under proposals, compared to £128,667 on average currently.\nBut the council's leadership has now withdrawn the plans.\nThe authority has wider plans to save £33m.\nUnder proposals in a leaked report seen by the BBC, the 23 remaining managers in the top two tiers would have earned more than £2m between them, compared to more than £3.3m spent on such salaries currently.\nIt revealed in the second tier, which would have been cut from 31 people to 19, the average salary would have fallen to £80,526, compared to an average of £84,419 currently.\nIn a statement, Councillor Mohammed Pervez, leader of the Labour-led coalition council, said a report was due to go to a committee on 30 November \"which was addressing the issue of job evaluations for tiers 1 and 2 within the organisation\".\nHe said: \"One of the implications of the report would have been a pay rise for senior officers by increasing the upper limits of the salary grades, a position which quite simply I do not support.\n\"Hence a decision was made to cancel the meeting and withdraw the report.\"\nThe council is a four-way coalition of Labour, the Conservative and Independent Alliance, the Liberal Democrats and City Independents.\nMick Salih, from the Community Voice group on the council, said: \"That report should never have been put together.\n\"We're talking about cutting services and cutting jobs and then one report actually saying about increasing senior officers' salary.\n\"It's absolutely ridiculous.\"\n\nSummary:", "answer": "Plans which would have seen some of a council's most senior managers getting pay rises, according to a report seen by the BBC, have been withdrawn."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_754988", "question": "In x years, Suzy will be twice Mary's age then. If Suzy is 20 now, Mary is 8 years old. What is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "To solve this problem, we need to determine the value of x, which represents the number of years in the future when Suzy will be twice Mary's age.\nWe know that Suzy is currently 20 years old and Mary is currently 8 years old.\nIn x years, Suzy will be 20 + x years old and Mary will be 8 + x years old.\nAccording to the given information, in x years, Suzy will be twice Mary's age. We can set up the equation as follows:\n20 + x = 2(8 + x)\nLet's simplify and solve for x:\n20 + x = 16 + 2x\nTo isolate x, we subtract x from both sides of the equation:\n20 + x - x = 16 + 2x - x\n20 = 16 + x\nTo isolate x, we subtract 16 from both sides of the equation:\n20 - 16 = 16 + x - 16\n4 = x\nThe value of x is 4.\n#### 4\nThe answer is: 4"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_806539", "question": "The true discount on Rs. 1760 due after a certain time at 12% per annum is Rs. 160. The time after which it is due is:\nAnswer Choices: (A) 6 months (B) 8 months (C) 9 months (D) 10 months (E) 12 months", "answer": "Let's think about the multi-choice question.\nTD=Amt*R*T/(100+RT)\ngiven TD=160,Amt=1760,R=12,T=?\nby substituting the values we get,\n160=(1760*12T)/(100+12T)\n160(100+12T)=1760*12T\n100+12T=(1760*12T)/160\n100+12T=132T\n120T=100\nt=100/120=5/6yrs i.e (5/6)*12=10months\nThe answer is D"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_422245", "question": "A train passes a station platform in 36 seconds and a man standing on the platform in 25 seconds. If the speed of the train is 54 km/hr, what is the length of the platform?\nAnswer Choices: (A) 37 (B) 240 (C) 288 (D) 267 (E) 165", "answer": "Let's think about the multi-choice question step by step.\nSpeed = (54 * 5/18) m/sec = 15 m/sec. Length of the train = (15 x 25)m = 375 m. Let the length of the platform be x meters. Then, (x + 375)/36 = 15 ==> x + 375 = 540 ==> x = 165 m.The answer is E"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_476036", "question": "The difference between two numbers is some value. When the larger number is divided by the smaller one, the quotient is 6 and the remainder is 15. The smaller number is 270. What is the difference between the two numbers?", "answer": "Let's denote the smaller number as S and the larger number as L. We are given that S = 270.\n\nAccording to the problem, when L is divided by S, the quotient is 6 and the remainder is 15. This can be expressed as:\n\nL = 6S + 15\n\nNow we substitute the value of S into the equation:\n\nL = 6(270) + 15\nL = 1620 + 15\nL = 1635\n\nNow we have the value of the larger number, L. The difference between the two numbers is:\n\nDifference = L - S\nDifference = 1635 - 270\nDifference = 1365\n\nSo, the difference between the two numbers is 1365."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_577567", "question": "A cook had 300 carrots in a bucket he was using to cook meals for a restaurant. Before lunch, he had used 2/5 of the carrots. By the end of the day, he had chopped and used 3/5 of the remaining carrots. How many carrots were not used that day?", "answer": "The cook used 2/5 of the carrots before lunch, so he used 2/5 * 300 = 120 carrots.\nThis means there were 300 - 120 = 180 carrots remaining after lunch.\nBy the end of the day, he used 3/5 of the remaining carrots, so he used 3/5 * 180 = 108 carrots.\nTherefore, there were 180 - 108 = 72 carrots that were not used that day.\n#### 72\nThe answer is: 72"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_511781", "question": "def calculate_shifts(message, keyword):\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a message and a keyword, calculate the shifts needed for each character in the message\n    based on the corresponding character in the keyword.\n\n    Parameters:\n    message (str): The message to be encrypted\n    keyword (str): The keyword used for encryption\n\n    Returns:\n    list: A list of tuples, where each tuple contains the character from the message and the\n          corresponding shift value based on the character from the keyword\n    \"\"\"", "answer": "shifts = []\n    keyword_len = len(keyword)\n\n    for i, char in enumerate(message):\n        # Iterate over each character in the message\n        if char.isalpha():\n            # Check if the character is a letter\n            keyword_index = i % keyword_len\n            keyword_char = keyword[keyword_index]\n\n            shift = ord(keyword_char.lower()) - ord('a')\n            if char.isupper():\n                shift = -shift\n\n            shifts.append((char, shift))\n\n    return shifts"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_170566", "question": "Given the question: I have a test where I am given the following article, what is an answer for the question: What was the man who was considered a \"dangerous modernist\" elected president of in March 1863? ?  In 1861, it was announced that a Provisional Theatre would be built in Prague, as a home for Czech opera. Smetana saw this as an opportunity to write and stage opera that would reflect Czech national character, similar to the portrayals of Russian life in Mikhail Glinka's operas. He hoped that he might be considered for the theatre's conductorship, but the post went to Jan Nepomuk Maýr, apparently because the conservative faction in charge of the project considered Smetana a \"dangerous modernist\", in thrall to avant garde composers such as Liszt and Wagner. Smetana then turned his attention to an opera competition, organised by Count Jan von Harrach, which offered prizes of 600 gulden each for the best comic and historical operas based on Czech culture. With no useful model on which to base his work—Czech opera as a genre scarcely existed—Smetana had to create his own style. He engaged Karel Sabina, his comrade from the 1848 barricades, as his librettist, and received Sabina's text in February 1862, a story of the 13th century invasion of Bohemia by Otto of Brandenburg. In April 1863 he submitted the score, under the title of The Brandenburgers in Bohemia. At this stage in his career, Smetana's command of the Czech language was poor. His generation of Czechs was educated in German, and he had difficulty expressing himself in what was supposedly his native tongue. To overcome these linguistic deficiencies he studied Czech grammar, and made a point of writing and speaking in Czech every day. He had become Chorus Master of the nationalistic Hlahol Choral Society soon after his return from Sweden, and as his fluency in the Czech language developed he composed patriotic choruses for the Society; The Three Riders and The Renegade were performed at concerts in early 1863. In March of that year Smetana was elected president of the music section of Umělecká Beseda, a society for Czech artists. By 1864 he was proficient enough in the Czech language to be appointed as music critic to the main Czech language newspaper...\nThe answer is:", "answer": "Umělecká Beseda, a society for Czech artists."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_19548", "question": "Write a function in Java to delete all occurrences of a specific item from an ArrayList. The function should have a time complexity of O(n) and a space complexity of O(1). Additionally, the function should handle a case where the specific item is a nested ArrayList and delete all occurrences of the nested ArrayList from the main ArrayList. The function should also handle a case where the specific item is a HashMap and delete all occurrences of the HashMap from the main ArrayList. \nExample: \nlist = [1,2,3,[4,5,2,3,2],2,{1=2,2=3},[4,5,2,3,2],{1=2,2=3}]\n\nThe function should remove all occurrences of [4,5,2,3,2], {1=2,2=3}, and [4,5,2,3,2], {1=2,2=3} from the main list.", "answer": "Here is an implementation of the function you described:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        ArrayList<Object> list = new ArrayList<>();\n        list.add(1);\n        list.add(2);\n        list.add(3);\n        list.add(Arrays.asList(4, 5, 2, 3, 2));\n        list.add(2);\n        list.add(new HashMap<Integer, Integer>(){{put(1,2); put(2,3);}});\n        list.add(Arrays.asList(4, 5, 2, 3, 2));\n        list.add(new HashMap<Integer, Integer>(){{put(1,2); put(2,3);}});\n        \n        System.out.println(\"Before: \" + list);\n        \n        deleteOccurrences(list, Arrays.asList(4, 5, 2, 3, 2));\n        deleteOccurrences(list, new HashMap<Integer, Integer>(){{put(1,2); put(2,3);}});\n        \n        System.out.println(\"After: \" + list);\n    }\n    \n    public static void deleteOccurrences(ArrayList<Object> list, Object item) {\n        int writeIndex = 0;\n        \n        for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {\n            Object element = list.get(i);\n            \n            if (!element.equals(item)) {\n                list.set(writeIndex, element);\n                writeIndex++;\n            }\n        }\n        \n        // Remove any remaining elements\n        while (list.size() > writeIndex) {\n            list.remove(list.size() - 1);\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nOutput:\n```\nBefore: [1, 2, 3, [4, 5, 2, 3, 2], 2, {1=2, 2=3}, [4, 5, 2, 3, 2], {1=2, 2=3}]\nAfter: [1, 2, 3, 2]\n```"}
