{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_7883", "question": "Is it possible to write a Go program that performs an HTTP request and prints the response body?", "answer": "Yes, it is definitely possible to achieve that in Go. Here's an example code that does exactly that:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"io/ioutil\"\n\t\"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\tresp, err := http.Get(\"https://example.com/\")\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tfmt.Println(err)\n\t}\n\n\tdefer resp.Body.Close()\n\tbody, err := ioutil.ReadAll(resp.Body)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tfmt.Println(err)\n\t}\n\n\tfmt.Println(string(body))\n}\n```\n\nThis code demonstrates how you can use the `net/http` package in Go to make an HTTP GET request to `https://example.com/`. If the request is successful, the response body is read and printed to the console.\n\nLet's break down the code:\n\n1. The `http.Get` function is used to send an HTTP GET request to the specified URL. The response object, `resp`, and any error that occurred during the request, `err`, are returned.\n\n2. We then defer the closing of the response body using `resp.Body.Close()` to ensure that it is closed properly after we finish using it.\n\n3. The `ioutil.ReadAll` function is used to read the entire response body into a byte slice, `body`. Again, any error that occurred during the reading process is returned.\n\n4. Finally, we convert the byte slice to a string using `string(body)` and print it to the console using `fmt.Println`.\n\nBy executing this program, you will be able to perform an HTTP request and print the response body in Go."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_611648", "question": "John has five children.  What is the probability that at least half of them are girls? (We can assume a boy is equally likely to be born as is a girl, and vice-versa.)", "answer": "The total number of possible outcomes is $2^5=32$, since each child can be either a boy or a girl.\nWe want to find the probability that at least half of them are girls.\nThere are two possibilities for this:\n1) Exactly three of them are girls.\nThe number of ways to choose 3 girls out of 5 is $\\binom{5}{3}=10$.\nFor each of these choices, the remaining 2 children must be boys.\nSo, there are a total of $10$ outcomes where exactly three of them are girls.\n2) Four or all five of them are girls.\nThe number of ways to choose 4 girls out of 5 is $\\binom{5}{4}=5$, and the number of ways to choose all 5 girls is $\\binom{5}{5}=1$.\nSo, there are a total of $5+1=6$ outcomes where four or all five of them are girls.\nTherefore, the probability that at least half of them are girls is $\\dfrac{10+6}{32}=\\dfrac{16}{32}=\\boxed{\\dfrac{1}{2}}$.\nThe answer is: \\frac{1}{2}"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_162952", "question": "If Dev works alone he will take 20 more hours to complete a task than if he worked with Tina to complete the task. If Tina works alone, she will take 5 more hours to complete the complete the task, then if she worked with Dev to complete the task? What is the ratio of the time taken by Dev to that taken by Tina if each of them worked alone to complete the task?\nAnswer Choices: (A) 4 : 1 (B) 2 : 1 (C) 10 : 1 (D) 3 : 1 (E) 1 : 2", "answer": "Let's solve the multi-choice question step by step.\nLet time taken by Dev to complete the work alone be x days and that by Tina be y days\nWork done by Dev in 1 day = 1/x\nWork done by Tina in 1 day = 1/y\nWork done by DevTina in 1 day = 1/x + 1/y = (x+y)/xy\nThus working together they will complete the work in xy/(x+y) days\nAcc. to the ques :\n1)If Dev works alone he will take 20 more hours to complete a task than if he worked with Tina'\nx - xy/(x+y) = 20\n=> (x^2)/(x+y) = 20.............(i)\n2)If Tina works alone, she will take 5 more hours to complete the complete the task, then if she worked with Dev\ny - xy/(x+y) = 5\n=> (y^2)/(x+y) = 5..............(ii)\nDividing (i) by (ii)\nx^2/y^2 = 4\n=> x/y = 2\nThe answer is : B\nHope it helps"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1217836", "question": "I have this problem : Path Crossing with Obstacles\nDescription are as below: Given a string `path`, where `path[i] = 'N'`, `'S'`, `'E'` or `'W'`, each representing moving one unit north, south, east, or west, respectively. You start at the origin `(0, 0)` on a 2D plane and walk on the path specified by `path`. There are also obstacles represented by `(x, y)` coordinates on the plane.\n\nReturn `True` if the path crosses itself at any point or hits an obstacle, that is, if at any time you are on a location you've previously visited or an obstacle. Return `False` otherwise.\n\nExample 1:\nInput: path = \"NES\", obstacles = [(1, 2)]\nOutput: false \nExplanation: Notice that the path doesn't cross any point more than once and doesn't hit any obstacle.\n\nExample 2:\nInput: path = \"NESWW\", obstacles = [(0, 0)]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: Notice that the path visits the origin twice.\n\nConstraints:\n`1 <= path.length <= 10^4`\n`path` will only consist of characters in `{'N', 'S', 'E', 'W'}`\n`0 <= obstacles.length <= 10^4`\nEach `obstacles[i]` will be a distinct pair of integers.", "answer": "This problem can be solved by using a set data structure in Python. The set is useful because it has constant time complexity for insertion and search. We would use a set to store the coordinates of all locations you have visited as well as a tuple of the coordinates of the obstacles.\n\nThe algorithm is as follows:\n\n1. Initialize a set `visited` with your starting location, (0, 0), and add the obstacles to the set.\n\n2. Next, start from the origin and simulate your journey on the basis of the given path. That is, if the current direction is 'N', then you move to the north, and so on.\n\n3. After each step, check if the new location has been visited before by checking the set. If it has been visited or it is an obstacle, return `True`. If it has not been visited, add the new location to the set and continue the journey.\n\n4. If you can finish the journey without any cross, return `False`.\n\nHere is a Python implementation of this approach.\n\n```python\ndef isPathCrossing(path, obstacles):\n  x, y = 0, 0\n  visited = {(0, 0)} # Starting point\n  \n  # Add obstacles to set\n  for ox, oy in obstacles:\n    visited.add((ox, oy))\n  \n  # Direction vectors\n  dx = {\"N\": 0, \"S\": 0, \"E\": 1, \"W\": -1}\n  dy = {\"N\": 1, \"S\": -1, \"E\": 0, \"W\": 0}\n  \n  for direction in path:\n    x += dx[direction]\n    y += dy[direction]\n    if (x, y) in visited: # Check if new location has been visited or is an obstacle\n      return True\n      \n    visited.add((x, y))\n  \n  return False\n```\n\nThis function takes a string `path` representing the steps to be taken, and a list of tuples `obstacles` representing the coordinates of the obstacles. It returns `True` if the path crosses itself or hits an obstacle and `False` otherwise."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_519711", "question": "A shopkeeper bought 600 oranges and 400 bananas. He found that 15% of oranges and a certain percentage of bananas were rotten. The percentage of fruits in good condition is 87.8%. What percentage of bananas were rotten?", "answer": "Let's first calculate the total number of fruits the shopkeeper bought:\n\nTotal fruits = Total oranges + Total bananas\nTotal fruits = 600 + 400\nTotal fruits = 1000\n\nNow, we know that 15% of the oranges were rotten. Let's calculate the number of rotten oranges:\n\nRotten oranges = 15% of 600\nRotten oranges = 0.15 * 600\nRotten oranges = 90\n\nSince the percentage of fruits in good condition is 87.8%, we can calculate the number of fruits in good condition:\n\nFruits in good condition = 87.8% of 1000\nFruits in good condition = 0.878 * 1000\nFruits in good condition = 878\n\nNow, let's calculate the total number of rotten fruits by subtracting the number of fruits in good condition from the total number of fruits:\n\nRotten fruits = Total fruits - Fruits in good condition\nRotten fruits = 1000 - 878\nRotten fruits = 122\n\nWe already know that there are 90 rotten oranges, so we can find the number of rotten bananas by subtracting the number of rotten oranges from the total number of rotten fruits:\n\nRotten bananas = Rotten fruits - Rotten oranges\nRotten bananas = 122 - 90\nRotten bananas = 32\n\nNow, to find the percentage of rotten bananas, we divide the number of rotten bananas by the total number of bananas and multiply by 100:\n\nPercentage of rotten bananas = (Rotten bananas / Total bananas) * 100\nPercentage of rotten bananas = (32 / 400) * 100\nPercentage of rotten bananas = 0.08 * 100\nPercentage of rotten bananas = 8%\n\nSo, 8% of the bananas were rotten."}
