{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1259824", "question": "Enhance the programming complexity for the given function:\n\ndef complex_fibber(n: int, m: int, p: int, q: int):\n    \"\"\"\n    Expanding the Fibber series that extends the Fibonacci sequence, this more complex function includes additional parameters and operations:\n    complex_fibber(0,m,p,q) == 0, complex_fibber(1,m,p,q) == 0, complex_fibber(2,m,p,q) == 1, and \n    complex_fibber(n,m,p,q) == complex_fibber(n-1,m,p,q) + complex_fibber(n-2,m,p,q) + complex_fibber(n-3,m,p,q) - complex_fibber(n-m,p,q) + 3*complex_fibber(n-p,p,q) - 2*complex_fibber(n-q,q) for m <= n, m > 2, p < m and q < p.\n    The function should implement advanced dynamic programming techniques for efficient computation of the n-th, m-th, p-th, and q-th number in this series.\n    \"\"\"", "answer": "Here's the Python code for this problem:\n\n```python\ndef complex_fibber(n: int, m: int, p: int, q: int):\n    # check for base cases\n    if n == 0 or n == 1:\n        return 0\n    elif n == 2:\n        return 1\n\n    # create initial cases\n    dp = [0] * (n+1)\n    dp[2] = 1\n\n    # compute the series for numbers 3 to n\n    for i in range(3, n+1):\n        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2] + (dp[i-3] if i>=3 else 0) - (dp[i-m] if i>=m else 0) + 3*(dp[i-p] if i>=p else 0) - 2*(dp[i-q] if i>=q else 0)\n    \n    # at this point, dp[n] is the n-th number in the series\n    return dp[n]\n```\n\nPlease note that the question is a little ambiguous on details for when the indices go negative (for the expressions `complex_fibber(n-m,p,q)` and `complex_fibber(n-q,p,q)`). Thus, the code above considers that for negative indices, the series' value is 0.\n\nThe function above, `complex_fibber`, uses dynamic programming for efficient computation of the number in the series. We initialize the array `dp` with size `n+1`. `dp[i]` will hold the `i-th` number in the series. \n\nWe start from n=3, and with each number i until n, we calculate the corresponding series value using previously calculated values. The series calculation logic is implemented inside the for-loop. \n\nFinally, we return `dp[n]` which is our answer. The time complexity for this function is O(n) - we iterate the dp array once, calculating each value in constant time. The space complexity is also O(n) because of the dp array."}
