{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1292783", "question": "Find the number of functions $f  : \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}$ such that\n\\[f(xy) + f(xz) - f(x) f(yz) \\ge 1\\]for all real numbers $x,$ $y,$ and $z.$", "answer": "Setting $x = y = z = 0,$ we get $3f(0) \\ge 1.$\nSetting $y = z = 0,$ we get $f(0) + f(0) - f(x) f(0) \\ge 1,$ so $2f(0) - f(x) f(0) \\ge 1.$\nThis means $f(x) f(0) \\le 2f(0) - 1.$\n\nWe claim that $f(0) = 1.$\nSuppose $f(0) \\neq 1,$ so $f(0) < 1.$\nThen $f(x) f(0) \\le 2f(0) - 1 < f(0),$ so $f(x) < f(0)$ for all $x.$\nBut then $f(0) f(xy) < f(x)$ by the given equation, contradiction.\n\nHence, $f(0) = 1.$\nSetting $y = z = 0,$ we get $2 - f(x) \\ge 1,$ so $f(x) \\le 1.$\nSetting $y = z = 1,$ we get $2f(x) - f(x)^2 \\ge 1,$ so $f(x)^2 - 2f(x) + 1 \\le 0,$ which means $(f(x) - 1)^2 \\le 0.$\nHence, $f(x) = 1$ for all $x.$\n\nTherefore, there is only $\\boxed{1}$ function that works, namely $f(x) = 1$ for all $x.$The answer is: 1"}
