{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_734229", "question": "Find the constant $b$ such that\n$$\\left(5x^2-3x+\\frac{7}{3}\\right)(ax^2+bx+c) = 15x^4 - 14x^3 + 20x^2 - \\frac{25}{3}x + \\frac{14}{3}$$", "answer": "Expanding the left side, we get\n$$5ax^4 + (5bx^3 - 3ax^3) + \\left(\\frac{7}{3}ax^2 + \\frac{7}{3}bx^2 + 5cx^2\\right) + \\left(\\frac{7}{3}bx + 5cx - \\frac{25}{3}x\\right) + 7cx = 15x^4 - 14x^3 + 20x^2 - \\frac{25}{3}x + \\frac{14}{3}.$$\nComparing like terms, we have the following system of equations:\n$$\\begin{aligned} 5a &= 15 \\\\ 5b - 3a &= -14 \\\\ \\frac{7}{3}a + \\frac{7}{3}b + 5c &= 20 \\\\ \\frac{7}{3}b + 5c &= -\\frac{25}{3} \\\\ 7c &= \\frac{14}{3} \\end{aligned}$$\nFrom the first equation, we find that $a = 3$.\nSubstituting this into the second equation, we get $5b - 9 = -14$, so $b = -1$.\nSubstituting $a = 3$ and $b = -1$ into the third equation, we have $\\frac{7}{3}(3) + \\frac{7}{3}(-1) + 5c = 20$, which simplifies to $7 + 5c = 20$.\nSolving this equation gives $c = \\frac{13}{5}$.\nTherefore, the constant $b$ is $\\boxed{-1}$.\nThe answer is: -1"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1061927", "question": "A trapezoid has a height of 8 cm, a base of 12 cm, and a top base of 6 cm. Find the area of the trapezoid.", "answer": "To find the area of a trapezoid, we use the formula:\n\nArea = (1/2) × (sum of bases) × height\n\nIn this case, the height is 8 cm, the top base is 6 cm, and the bottom base is 12 cm. Plugging these values into the formula, we get:\n\nArea = (1/2) × (6 + 12) × 8\n\nArea = (1/2) × 18 × 8\n\nArea = 9 × 8\n\nArea = 72 square centimeters\n\nSo, the area of the trapezoid is 72 square centimeters."}
