{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_3218", "question": "The Cookie Monster encounters a cookie whose boundary is the equation $x^2+y^2 + 21 = 4x + 18 y$ and is very confused. He wants to know if this cookie is a lunch-sized cookie or a snack-sized cookie. What is the radius of this cookie?", "answer": "We can rewrite the equation as $x^2 - 4x + y^2 - 18y = -21$ and complete the square,\nresulting in $(x-2)^2 - 4 + (y-9)^2 - 81 = -21$,\nor $(x-2)^2 + (y-9)^2 = 64$.\nThis is the equation of a circle with center $(2,9)$ and radius $\\sqrt{64}=8$.\nTherefore, the radius of this cookie is $\\boxed{8}$.The answer is: 8"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_829236", "question": "Create a presentation outlining the importance of proper nutrition in relation to both mental and physical health. Include statistics, scientific studies, and practical examples to effectively inform your audience about the impact of nutrition on overall well-being. Use clear language and engaging visuals to keep your audience’s attention throughout the presentation.", "answer": "Good afternoon everyone, thank you for joining me for this presentation on the importance of proper nutrition for both our mental and physical health. Today, we will discuss the effects of nutrition on our overall well-being, and the importance of making good dietary choices.\n\nThe Importance of Proper Nutrition - A Global Perspective\n\nBefore we delve into the specifics, let's take a global point of view. In 2019, an estimated 690 million people, or 9% of the global population, were undernourished. At the same time, 1.9 billion adults, 39% of the global population, were overweight, while 38 million children were overweight or obese. Poor nutrition can cause a range of health problems, ranging from stunted growth in children to obesity and cardiovascular disease in adults.\n\nThe Mental Impact of Proper Nutrition\n\nProper nutrition is essential for our mental health, too. Studies have shown that our diet can significantly affect our mood, cognitive functioning, and mental health. For instance, consuming a diet high in processed and refined foods, unhealthy fats, and sugars and low in vegetables and fruits, whole grains, and lean proteins has been linked to higher rates of depression, anxiety, and stress. Poor nutrition can also cause inflammation in the brain, which has been found to lead to cognitive decline and neurological issues.\n\nOn the other hand, consuming nutrient-dense, whole foods full of antioxidants, vitamins, and minerals is linked with better mental health outcomes. Eating a balanced diet including leafy greens,