{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1121269", "question": "Find the inverse of the matrix\n\\[\\begin{pmatrix} 9 & 18 \\\\ -6 & -12 \\end{pmatrix}.\\]If the inverse does not exist, then enter the zero matrix.", "answer": "To find the inverse of a $2 \\times 2$ matrix $\\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\\\ c & d \\end{pmatrix},$ we use the formula\n\\[\\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\\\ c & d \\end{pmatrix}^{-1} = \\frac{1}{ad - bc} \\begin{pmatrix} d & -b \\\\ -c & a \\end{pmatrix}.\\]In this case, $ad - bc = (9)(-12) - (18)(-6) = 0,$ so the inverse does not exist. Therefore, the answer is the zero matrix $\\boxed{\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\\\ 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}}.$The answer is: \\begin{pmatrix}0&0\\0&0\\end{pmatrix}"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_277159", "question": "If vectors a and b have magnitudes 7 and 11, respectively, what are all the possible values of the dot product a · b? Express your answer in interval notation.", "answer": "The dot product of two vectors is given by $a \\cdot b = |a||b|\\cos \\theta$, where $\\theta$ is the angle between the two vectors.\nSince the magnitudes of vectors $a$ and $b$ are 7 and 11, respectively, we have $|a| = 7$ and $|b| = 11$.\nThe dot product $a \\cdot b$ can take on any value between $|a||b| = 7 \\cdot 11 = 77$ (when $\\theta = 0\\degree$ and the vectors are parallel) and $-|a||b| = -77$ (when $\\theta = 180\\degree$ and the vectors are anti-parallel).\nTherefore, the possible values of the dot product $a \\cdot b$ are $[-77, 77]$ in interval notation.\nThe answer is: [-77,77]"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_958722", "question": "Calculate the value of $\\frac{1}{(-7^{3})^{3}}\\cdot(-7)^{10}$.", "answer": "First, we simplify the expression $(-7^{3})^{3}$, which is equal to $(-7)^{9}$.\nNext, we evaluate $\\frac{1}{(-7^{3})^{3}}\\cdot(-7)^{10}$.\nSince $\\frac{1}{(-7^{3})^{3}} = \\frac{1}{(-7)^{9}} = (-7)^{-9}$,\nwe have $(-7)^{-9}\\cdot(-7)^{10}$.\nUsing the rule $a^{-m} = \\frac{1}{a^{m}}$, we get $\\frac{1}{(-7)^{9}}\\cdot(-7)^{10}$.\nSimplifying, we have $\\frac{(-7)^{10}}{(-7)^{9}} = (-7)^{10-9} = (-7)^{1} = \\boxed{-7}$.\nThe answer is: -7"}
