{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_367274", "question": "Two cars started at the same time, from the same point, driving along the same road. The rate of the first car is 50 mph and the rate of the second car is some mph. It takes 3 hours for the distance between the two cars to be 30 miles. What is the rate of the second car?", "answer": "Let's denote the rate of the second car as \\( v \\) mph.\n\nSince the first car travels at 50 mph, after 3 hours, it will have covered a distance of \\( 50 \\times 3 = 150 \\) miles.\n\nLet's assume the second car travels at a slower rate than the first car since they start at the same point and the distance between them increases. After 3 hours, the second car will have covered a distance of \\( v \\times 3 \\) miles.\n\nThe distance between the two cars after 3 hours is 30 miles. Therefore, the distance covered by the first car minus the distance covered by the second car should equal 30 miles.\n\nSo we have the equation:\n\n\\[ 150 - 3v = 30 \\]\n\nNow, we solve for \\( v \\):\n\n\\[ 3v = 150 - 30 \\]\n\\[ 3v = 120 \\]\n\\[ v = \\frac{120}{3} \\]\n\\[ v = 40 \\]\n\nTherefore, the rate of the second car is 40 mph."}
