{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_78242", "question": "Find the positive real value of $t$ that satisfies $|t+2i\\sqrt{3}| |6-4i| = 26$.", "answer": "We can simplify the equation as $|t+2i\\sqrt{3}| |6-4i| = 26$.\nThe magnitude of a complex number $a+bi$ is $\\sqrt{a^2+b^2}$.\nSo, $|t+2i\\sqrt{3}| = \\sqrt{t^2+(2\\sqrt{3})^2} = \\sqrt{t^2+12}$.\nAnd $|6-4i| = \\sqrt{6^2+(-4)^2} = \\sqrt{52} = 2\\sqrt{13}$.\nTherefore, we have $\\sqrt{t^2+12} \\cdot 2\\sqrt{13} = 26$.\nSimplifying, we get $\\sqrt{t^2+12} = \\frac{26}{2\\sqrt{13}} = \\frac{13}{\\sqrt{13}} = \\sqrt{13}$.\nSquaring both sides, we have $t^2+12 = 13$.\nSolving for $t$, we get $t^2 = 1$.\nSince we are looking for a positive value of $t$, the solution is $t = \\boxed{1}$.\nThe answer is: 1"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_427317", "question": "I'm trying to figure out how to solve this problem without disabling \"only_full_group_by\" in my.ini. Here is my query:\n\n```\nSELECT \n  p.title,\n  COUNT(t.qty) AS total \nFROM\n  payments t \n  LEFT JOIN products AS p \n    ON p.id = t.item \nWHERE t.user = 1 \nGROUP BY t.item\nORDER BY t.created DESC;\n```\n\nand here are the tables:\n\nPayments:\n```\nid     item   user   created\n============================\n1      1      1      2017-01-10\n2      2      1      2017-01-11\n3      3      1      2017-01-12\n4      4      1      2017-01-13\n5      1      1      2017-01-14\n```\n\nProducts:\n```\nid     title    created\n==========================\n1      First     2016-12-10\n1      Second    2016-12-11\n1      Third     2016-12-12\n1      Fourth    2016-12-13\n```\n\nThe final result should look like this:\n\n```\nName    Total\nFirst   2\nSecond  1\nThird   1\nFourth  1\n```\n\nBut if I change my query to `GROUP BY t.item, t.created`, the error is gone. However, I end up with five records instead of four, which is not what I want. Since I'm grouping items based on the \"item\" field, there should be only four records.", "answer": "This is your query:\n\n```\nSELECT p.title, COUNT(t.qty) AS total \n-------^\nFROM payments t LEFT JOIN\n     products AS p \n     ON p.id = t.item \nWHERE t.user = 1 \nGROUP BY t.item\n---------^\nORDER BY t.created DESC;\n---------^\n```\n\nThe points I have highlighted have issues. Notice that the `SELECT` and `GROUP BY` clauses are referring to different columns. In a `LEFT JOIN`, you usually want to aggregate by something in the first table, not the second.\n\nThe `ORDER BY` clause is another problem. You are not aggregating by this column, so you need to decide which value you want. I am assuming you want the maximum value, so I have used `MAX(t.created)`.\n\nTo fix your query and achieve the desired result, you can modify it as follows:\n\n```\nSELECT p.title, COUNT(t.qty) AS total \nFROM payments t LEFT JOIN\n     products AS p \n     ON p.id = t.item \nWHERE t.user = 1 \nGROUP BY p.title\nORDER BY MAX(t.created) DESC;\n```\n\nI would also like to mention that `COUNT(t.qty)` might not be the correct aggregation function in this case. Usually, `qty` refers to \"quantity\" and what you want is the sum. So you may want to use `SUM(t.qty)` instead."}
