{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_582634", "question": "You are given a task: Finding the Lexicographically Largest String After Applying Operations. Here are the details: You are given an odd-length string `t` composed of digits from `0` to `9`, and two integers `x` and `y`.\n\nYou can perform either of the following two operations on `t` in any order and as many times as you want:\n1. Decrease all even indices of `t` (0-indexed) by `x`. If a digit falls below `0`, it cycles back to `9`. For example, if `t = \"1237\"` and `x = 2`, `t` transforms into `\"9037\"`.\n2. Shift `t` to the left by `y` positions. For example, if `t = \"1237\"` and `y = 1`, `t` transforms into `\"2371\"`.\n\nYour task is to return the lexicographically largest string achievable by applying the above operations on `t` as many times as needed.\n\nA string `a` is considered lexicographically larger than a string `b` (of the same length) if at the first position where `a` and `b` differ, string `a` has a digit that appears later in the numerical sequence than the corresponding digit in `b`. For instance, `\"0190\"` is lexicographically larger than `\"0158\"` because the first position they differ is at the third digit, and `'9'` comes after `'5'`.\n\nConstraints:\nThe length of `t` is between `3` and `101` and is odd.\n`t` is composed of digits from `0` to `9` only.\n`x` is between `1` and `9`.\n`y` is between `1` and `t.length - 1`.", "answer": "You can apply the following Python solution using the deque from the collections module to solve this problem:\n\nPython Code:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import deque\nimport copy\n\ndef largest_string(t, x, y):\n    # Declare and initialize a deque from the given string t\n    de = deque(t)\n    \n    # Calculate the repeat value by taking the modulo of length of t with y\n    repeat = len(t) % y\n\n    # Create an empty list to store all possible results\n    possible_results = []\n\n    # Apply rotation & decrement operations\n    for _ in range(repeat):   \n        # Apply decrementation operation by x on all even indices\n        decrement_list = copy.deepcopy(de)\n        for i in range(0, len(de), 2):\n            decrement_list[i] = str((int(decrement_list[i]) - x + 10) % 10)\n        possible_results.append(''.join(list(decrement_list)))\n\n        # Apply rotation operation by y to the left\n        de.rotate(-y)\n\n    # The maximum string in the list possible_results is the lexicographically largest string.\n    return max(possible_results)\n```\n\nThis code uses a dynamic programming approach by generating and storing all possible strings after applying operations for several rounds, then it returns the lexicographically largest string.\n\nPlease note that this function will only work properly if the inputs meet the constraints: The length of `t` is between `3` and `101` and is odd. `t` is composed of digits from `0` to `9` only. `x` in between `1` and `9`. `y` is between `1` and `t.length - 1`."}
