{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_223112", "question": "In an election, candidate Douglas won some percent of the total vote in counties X and Y. He won 72 percent of the vote in county X, and the ratio of people who voted in county X to county Y is 2:1. If candidate Douglas won 36 percent of the vote in county Y, what percent of the total vote did he win in both counties?", "answer": "Let's assume that the number of people who voted in county X is 2V and in county Y is V (since the ratio is 2:1).\n\nDouglas won 72% of the votes in county X, so he won 0.72 * 2V votes there.\nDouglas won 36% of the votes in county Y, so he won 0.36 * V votes there.\n\nThe total number of votes Douglas won in both counties is:\n0.72 * 2V + 0.36 * V = 1.44V + 0.36V = 1.8V\n\nThe total number of votes cast in both counties is 2V (from county X) + V (from county Y) = 3V.\n\nTo find the percentage of the total vote Douglas won in both counties, we divide the total votes he won by the total votes cast and multiply by 100:\n\n(1.8V / 3V) * 100 = (1.8 / 3) * 100 = 0.6 * 100 = 60%\n\nTherefore, candidate Douglas won 60% of the total vote in both counties."}
