{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_17118", "question": "Kylie has x daisies. Her sister gave her another 9 daisies. Kylie then gave half her daisies to her mother. How many daisies does Kylie have left?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 7, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "Kylie starts with x daisies.\nHer sister gave her another 9 daisies, so now she has x + 9 daisies.\nKylie then gave half of her daisies to her mother, which means she gave away (1/2)(x + 9) daisies.\nThe number of daisies Kylie has left is: (x + 9) - (1/2)(x + 9) = (1/2)(x + 9).\nWe are given that Kylie has 7 daisies left, so we can write: (1/2)(x + 9) = 7.\nSimplifying the left side, we get: (x + 9)/2 = 7.\nMultiplying both sides by 2, we get: x + 9 = 14.\nSubtracting 9 from both sides, we get: x = 5.\nThe value of x is 5.\n#### 5\nThe answer is: 5"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_812806", "question": "Let A = {1, 2, 3} and B = {2, 3, 4}. Find the Cartesian product of A x (B ∩ {3,4}).", "answer": "First, we need to find the intersection of B and {3,4}. The intersection of two sets is the set of elements that are common to both sets. In this case, B ∩ {3,4} = {3,4} since both 3 and 4 are present in set B.\n\nNow, we can find the Cartesian product of A x (B ∩ {3,4}). The Cartesian product of two sets A and B, denoted as A x B, is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is in A and b is in B.\n\nSo, A x (B ∩ {3,4}) = A x {3,4} = {(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), (3,3), (3,4)}\n\nThe Cartesian product of A x (B ∩ {3,4}) is {(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), (3,3), (3,4)}."}
