{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1053146", "question": "A hiker walked for some days. She walked 18 miles on the first day, walking 3 miles per hour. On the second day she walked for one less hour but she walked one mile per hour faster than on the first day. On the third day she walked at 5 miles per hour for 3 hours. She walked a total of 53 miles. How many days did she walk?", "answer": "Let's calculate the distance the hiker walked each day and then sum them up to see if it matches the total distance of 53 miles.\n\nDay 1:\nShe walked 18 miles at a speed of 3 miles per hour. \n\nDay 2:\nShe walked one less hour than on the first day and one mile per hour faster. On the first day, she walked for \\( \\frac{18 \\text{ miles}}{3 \\text{ mph}} = 6 \\text{ hours} \\). So on the second day, she walked for 6 - 1 = 5 hours. Her speed on the second day was 3 + 1 = 4 miles per hour. Therefore, the distance she walked on the second day was 5 hours * 4 mph = 20 miles.\n\nDay 3:\nShe walked at 5 miles per hour for 3 hours. The distance she walked on the third day was 5 mph * 3 hours = 15 miles.\n\nNow let's add up the distances:\nDay 1: 18 miles\nDay 2: 20 miles\nDay 3: 15 miles\nTotal: 18 + 20 + 15 = 53 miles\n\nThe total distance matches the given total of 53 miles, so the hiker walked for 3 days."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1270390", "question": "During summer break, 60.7% of kids from Lawrence county stay home and the other 39.3% go to camp. If there are 907,611 kids staying home, how many kids are in Lawrence county?", "answer": "To find the total number of kids in Lawrence county, we can set up a proportion where 60.7% corresponds to the 907,611 kids staying home. \n\nLet's denote the total number of kids in Lawrence county as T.\n\nWe have that 60.7% of T is equal to 907,611 kids.\n\nSo, 0.607 * T = 907,611\n\nTo find T, we divide both sides of the equation by 0.607:\n\nT = 907,611 / 0.607\n\nT ≈ 1,495,100\n\nTherefore, there are approximately 1,495,100 kids in Lawrence county."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_905609", "question": "a 270 metres long train running at the speed of 120 kmph crosses another train running in opposite direction at the speed of 80 kmph in 9 seconds . what is the length of the other train ?", "answer": "First, let's convert the speeds from km/h to m/s, because the length of the train is given in meters and the time in seconds.\n\nSpeed of the first train in m/s = 120 km/h * (1000 m / 1 km) * (1 h / 3600 s) = 120 * 1000 / 3600 = 33.33 m/s\n\nSpeed of the second train in m/s = 80 km/h * (1000 m / 1 km) * (1 h / 3600 s) = 80 * 1000 / 3600 = 22.22 m/s\n\nSince the trains are running in opposite directions, their relative speed is the sum of their individual speeds.\n\nRelative speed = 33.33 m/s + 22.22 m/s = 55.55 m/s\n\nThe time taken to cross each other is 9 seconds.\n\nThe distance covered when they cross each other is the sum of their lengths.\n\nDistance = Relative speed * Time = 55.55 m/s * 9 s = 500 m\n\nWe know the length of the first train is 270 meters, so we can find the length of the second train by subtracting the length of the first train from the total distance.\n\nLength of the second train = Distance - Length of the first train = 500 m - 270 m = 230 m\n\nTherefore, the length of the other train is 230 meters."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1409962", "question": "Tom originally was able to lift 80 kg farmer handles per hand. After some training, he was able to increase this number by a certain factor. He then decided to specialize and was able to get an extra 10%. He can hold a total of 352 kg. What was the factor by which he increased his lifting capacity after training?", "answer": "Let's denote the factor by which Tom increased his lifting capacity after training as \\( F \\).\n\nOriginally, Tom could lift 80 kg per hand, so for both hands, he could lift a total of \\( 80 \\times 2 = 160 \\) kg.\n\nAfter training, his capacity increased by a factor of \\( F \\), so he could lift \\( 160 \\times F \\) kg.\n\nThen, he specialized and increased this number by an extra 10%, so his final lifting capacity became \\( 160 \\times F \\times 1.10 \\).\n\nWe know that his final lifting capacity is 352 kg, so we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ 160 \\times F \\times 1.10 = 352 \\]\n\nNow, we can solve for \\( F \\):\n\n\\[ F = \\frac{352}{160 \\times 1.10} \\]\n\n\\[ F = \\frac{352}{176} \\]\n\n\\[ F = 2 \\]\n\nSo, the factor by which Tom increased his lifting capacity after training is 2."}
