{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1328078", "question": "Alia has 2 times as many markers as Austin. Austin has one-third as many markers as Steve does. If Steve has x markers, Alia has 40. What is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "To solve this problem, we need to determine the value of x, which represents the number of markers Steve has.\nLet's break down the information given:\nNumber of markers Austin has: 1/3 * x\nNumber of markers Alia has: 2 * (1/3 * x)\nNumber of markers Alia has: 40\nWe can set up the equation as follows:\n2 * (1/3 * x) = 40\nLet's simplify and solve for x:\n2/3 * x = 40\nTo isolate x, we multiply both sides of the equation by 3/2:\n(2/3 * x) * (3/2) = 40 * (3/2)\nx = 60\nThe value of x is 60.\n#### 60\nThe answer is: 60"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_653067", "question": "Compute $\\dbinom{25}{2}$.", "answer": "The formula for combinations is $\\dbinom{n}{r} = \\dfrac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}$, where $n! = n \\times (n-1) \\times \\dots \\times 3 \\times 2 \\times 1$.\nSo, $\\dbinom{25}{2} = \\dfrac{25!}{2!(25-2)!} = \\dfrac{25!}{2!23!}$.\nCanceling out the common factors, we get $\\dbinom{25}{2} = \\dfrac{25 \\times 24}{2 \\times 1} = \\boxed{300}$.\nThe answer is: 300"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_620613", "question": "A company claims that their new product has a mean lifetime of at least 500 hours. To verify the claim, a sample of 20 products is taken and their lifetimes are recorded. The sample has a mean lifetime of 480 hours and a standard deviation of 30 hours. Calculate the 95% confidence interval for the true mean lifetime of the new product.", "answer": "To calculate the 95% confidence interval for the true mean lifetime of the new product, we will use the following formula:\n\nConfidence Interval = Sample Mean ± (t-score * (Standard Deviation / √Sample Size))\n\nFirst, we need to find the t-score for a 95% confidence interval with 19 degrees of freedom (sample size - 1 = 20 - 1 = 19). Using a t-table or calculator, we find that the t-score is approximately 2.093.\n\nNext, we will plug in the values into the formula:\n\nConfidence Interval = 480 ± (2.093 * (30 / √20))\n\nConfidence Interval = 480 ± (2.093 * (30 / 4.472))\n\nConfidence Interval = 480 ± (2.093 * 6.708)\n\nConfidence Interval = 480 ± 14.045\n\nSo, the 95% confidence interval for the true mean lifetime of the new product is approximately (465.955, 494.045) hours."}
