{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_929325", "question": "The interest on a certain deposit at a certain percentage p.a. is Rs. 202.50 in one year. The additional interest in one year on the same deposit at 5% p.a. is Rs. 22.5. What was the initial interest rate percentage?", "answer": "Let's denote the initial interest rate as \\( r \\% \\) per annum and the principal amount (the initial deposit) as \\( P \\).\n\nAccording to the problem, the interest for one year at the initial rate \\( r \\% \\) is Rs. 202.50. The interest can be calculated using the formula:\n\n\\[ \\text{Interest} = \\frac{\\text{Principal} \\times \\text{Rate} \\times \\text{Time}}{100} \\]\n\nSo, for the initial rate, we have:\n\n\\[ 202.50 = \\frac{P \\times r \\times 1}{100} \\]\n\\[ 20250 = P \\times r \\]\n\nNow, the additional interest when the rate is increased by 5% is Rs. 22.5. This means that the interest at \\( (r + 5) \\% \\) is \\( 202.50 + 22.5 = 225 \\) Rs. Using the interest formula again:\n\n\\[ 225 = \\frac{P \\times (r + 5) \\times 1}{100} \\]\n\\[ 22500 = P \\times (r + 5) \\]\n\nNow we have two equations:\n\n1. \\( 20250 = P \\times r \\)\n2. \\( 22500 = P \\times (r + 5) \\)\n\nWe can solve these two equations simultaneously to find the value of \\( r \\). Let's subtract the first equation from the second:\n\n\\[ 22500 - 20250 = P \\times (r + 5) - P \\times r \\]\n\\[ 2250 = P \\times 5 \\]\n\nNow, we can solve for \\( P \\):\n\n\\[ P = \\frac{2250}{5} \\]\n\\[ P = 450 \\]\n\nNow that we have \\( P \\), we can substitute it back into the first equation to find \\( r \\):\n\n\\[ 20250 = 450 \\times r \\]\n\\[ r = \\frac{20250}{450} \\]\n\\[ r = 45 \\]\n\nSo, the initial interest rate was \\( 45\\% \\) per annum."}
