{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_921494", "question": "a and b can finish a job in 15 days, while a, b, and c can finish it in some days. If c alone can finish the job in 30 days, how many days do a, b, and c take to finish the job together?", "answer": "Let's denote the work rate of a and b together as \\( W_{ab} \\), the work rate of c alone as \\( W_c \\), and the work rate of a, b, and c together as \\( W_{abc} \\).\n\nWe know that a and b can finish the job in 15 days, so their combined work rate is \\( W_{ab} = \\frac{1}{15} \\) (job per day).\n\nWe also know that c alone can finish the job in 30 days, so c's work rate is \\( W_c = \\frac{1}{30} \\) (job per day).\n\nWhen a, b, and c work together, their combined work rate is the sum of their individual work rates:\n\\[ W_{abc} = W_{ab} + W_c \\]\n\nSubstituting the known work rates, we get:\n\\[ W_{abc} = \\frac{1}{15} + \\frac{1}{30} \\]\n\nTo find the common denominator, we can multiply the first fraction by 2/2 to get:\n\\[ W_{abc} = \\frac{2}{30} + \\frac{1}{30} \\]\n\nAdding the fractions, we get:\n\\[ W_{abc} = \\frac{3}{30} \\]\n\nSimplifying the fraction, we get:\n\\[ W_{abc} = \\frac{1}{10} \\]\n\nThis means that a, b, and c together can finish the job at a rate of \\( \\frac{1}{10} \\) job per day.\n\nTo find out how many days they take to finish the job together, we take the reciprocal of the work rate:\n\\[ \\text{Days taken by a, b, and c together} = \\frac{1}{W_{abc}} \\]\n\n\\[ \\text{Days taken by a, b, and c together} = \\frac{1}{\\frac{1}{10}} \\]\n\n\\[ \\text{Days taken by a, b, and c together} = 10 \\]\n\nTherefore, a, b, and c together can finish the job in 10 days."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_536308", "question": "Lauren's social media channel makes $0.50 for every commercial that's viewed and a certain amount for every person who subscribes. On Tuesday, 100 people watched commercials before viewing her content and 27 people subscribed. She made $77. How much does she make for every subscription?", "answer": "Let's denote the amount Lauren makes for every subscription as \\( S \\).\n\nFrom the information given, we know that Lauren makes $0.50 for every commercial viewed. Since 100 people watched commercials, the total amount made from commercials is \\( 100 \\times $0.50 = $50 \\).\n\nWe also know that Lauren made a total of $77 on Tuesday. This total is the sum of the amount made from commercials and the amount made from subscriptions. Therefore, the amount made from subscriptions is \\( $77 - $50 = $27 \\).\n\nSince 27 people subscribed and this resulted in $27, we can find the amount made per subscription by dividing the total amount made from subscriptions by the number of subscribers:\n\n\\( S = \\frac{$27}{27 \\text{ subscribers}} = $1 \\text{ per subscription} \\).\n\nSo, Lauren makes $1 for every subscription."}
