1]:\n                sorted = False\n                badList[element], badList[element + 1] = badList[element + 1], badList[element]\n                print(badList)\n\n    return badList\n\nprint(bubble(mylist))\n```\n\nIn this version of the code, the `sorted` flag starts as `True` and is only set to `False` if a swap has occurred. This way, if you go through the entire list without swapping, the flag remains `True` and the loop exits. Additionally, the swapping of elements has been written in a more Pythonic way."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1108650", "question": "Let $a$ and $b$ be angles such that $\\sin (a + b) = \\frac{3}{4}$ and $\\sin (a - b) = \\frac{1}{2}.$  Find $\\frac{\\tan a}{\\tan b}.$", "answer": "From the angle addition formula,\n\\[\\sin (a + b) = \\sin a \\cos b + \\cos a \\sin b = \\frac{3}{4}\\]and\n\\[\\sin (a - b) = \\sin a \\cos b - \\cos a \\sin b = \\frac{1}{2}.\\]Dividing these equations, we get\n\\[\\frac{\\sin (a + b)}{\\sin (a - b)} = \\frac{\\frac{3}{4}}{\\frac{1}{2}} = \\frac{3}{2},\\]which simplifies to\n\\[\\frac{\\sin a \\cos b + \\cos a \\sin b}{\\sin a \\cos b - \\cos a \\sin b} = \\frac{3}{2}.\\]Dividing the numerator and denominator by $\\cos a \\cos b,$ we get\n\\[\\frac{\\tan a + \\tan b}{\\tan a - \\tan b} = \\frac{3}{2}.\\]Cross-multiplying, we get $(\\tan a + \\tan b)(2) = (\\tan a - \\tan b)(3),$ or\n\\[2 \\tan a + 2 \\tan b = 3 \\tan a - 3 \\tan b.\\]Then $\\tan a = 5 \\tan b.$  Hence, $\\frac{\\tan a}{\\tan b} = \\boxed{5}.$The answer is: 5"}
