{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1287184", "question": "A, B, and C started a business with capitals of Rs. 6000, Rs. 8000, and Rs. 10000 respectively. At the end of the year, the profit shares of A and C have a difference of Rs 500. If the difference between the profit shares of A and C is Rs 500, what is the profit share of B?", "answer": "Let's first calculate the ratio of their investments:\n\nA's investment: Rs. 6000\nB's investment: Rs. 8000\nC's investment: Rs. 10000\n\nThe ratio of their investments is:\nA : B : C = 6000 : 8000 : 10000\n\nWe can simplify this ratio by dividing each term by the greatest common divisor of the three amounts, which is 2000 in this case:\n\nA : B : C = 6000/2000 : 8000/2000 : 10000/2000\nA : B : C = 3 : 4 : 5\n\nNow, let's assume the total profit is P. According to the ratio, the profit will be divided as follows:\n\nA's share = 3/12 * P\nB's share = 4/12 * P\nC's share = 5/12 * P\n\nWe are given that the difference between the profit shares of A and C is Rs 500:\n\nC's share - A's share = Rs 500\n(5/12 * P) - (3/12 * P) = Rs 500\n(2/12 * P) = Rs 500\nP/6 = Rs 500\nP = Rs 500 * 6\nP = Rs 3000\n\nNow that we know the total profit (P) is Rs 3000, we can find B's share:\n\nB's share = 4/12 * P\nB's share = 4/12 * Rs 3000\nB's share = Rs 1000\n\nTherefore, the profit share of B is Rs 1000."}
