{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_91034", "question": "A particular triangle has sides of length 14 cm, X cm and 9 cm. In centimeters, The perimeter of the triangle is 31. What is the value of unknown variable X?", "answer": "To solve this problem, we need to determine the value of x, which represents the length of one side of the triangle.\nLet's break down the information given:\nLength of the first side: 14 cm\nLength of the second side: X cm\nLength of the third side: 9 cm\nPerimeter of the triangle: 31 cm\nWe can set up the equation as follows:\nLength of the first side + Length of the second side + Length of the third side = Perimeter of the triangle\n14 + X + 9 = 31\nLet's simplify and solve for x:\n23 + X = 31\nTo isolate x, we subtract 23 from both sides of the equation:\n23 + X - 23 = 31 - 23\nX = 8\nThe value of x is 8.\nThe answer is: 8"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_653808", "question": "Codify an algorithm to order the array using the principles of the Bubble Sort technique. The array includes duplicates and negative numbers. Consider algorithm efficiency when handling large array sizes. \nunsorted_list = [3, 5, -1, 0, 9, 3, -2]", "answer": "Here is a Python solution using the Bubble Sort technique. The Bubble Sort algorithm repeatedly goes through the list, compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. The pass through the list is repeated until the list is sorted.\n\nHere is an implementation:\n\n```python\ndef bubble_sort(unsorted_list):\n    n = len(unsorted_list)\n    for i in range(n):\n        # Create a flag that will allow the function to terminate early if there's nothing left to sort\n        already_sorted = True\n        for j in range(n - i - 1):\n            if unsorted_list[j] > unsorted_list[j + 1]:\n                # Swap elements\n                unsorted_list[j], unsorted_list[j + 1] = unsorted_list[j + 1], unsorted_list[j]\n                # Set the flag to False so we'll loop again\n                already_sorted = False\n        # If there were no swaps during the last loop, the list is already sorted\n        if already_sorted:\n            break\n    return unsorted_list\n\nunsorted_list = [3, 5, -1, 0, 9, 3, -2]\nprint(bubble_sort(unsorted_list))\n```\n\nWhen you run this code, it will print: `[-2, -1, 0, 3, 3, 5, 9]`.\n\nNotice that the Bubble Sort technique has a worst-case and average time complexity of O(n²), where n is the number of items being sorted. This happens when we have to go through the maximum number of iterations, i.e., when the smallest element is at the end of the list. It's not the most efficient sorting algorithm for large lists, but it's relatively easy to understand and implement."}
