{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_360077", "question": "A reduction in the price of petrol by 15% enables a motorist to buy 7 gallons more for $300. Find the original price of petrol?", "answer": "Let's denote the original price of petrol per gallon as P dollars. After a 15% reduction, the new price of petrol per gallon becomes 0.85P dollars.\n\nWith the original price P, the motorist could buy a certain number of gallons for $300. Let's call this number of gallons G. So we have:\n\nG * P = $300\n\nAfter the price reduction, the motorist can buy 7 more gallons for the same amount of money. So we have:\n\n(G + 7) * 0.85P = $300\n\nNow we have two equations with two variables. We can solve for P by first expressing G in terms of P from the first equation:\n\nG = $300 / P\n\nNow we substitute G in the second equation:\n\n($300 / P + 7) * 0.85P = $300\n\nDividing both sides by 0.85P, we get:\n\n$300 / P + 7 = $300 / 0.85P\n\nNow we solve for P:\n\n$300 + 7P = $300 / 0.85\n\n7P = $300 / 0.85 - $300\n\n7P = $352.94 - $300\n\n7P = $52.94\n\nP = $52.94 / 7\n\nP = $7.56\n\nSo the original price of petrol per gallon was $7.56."}
