{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1403048", "question": "I have 5 friends, and we compared out scores after taking an exam. The overall average was 81.6. The average of the scores from 1st to 4th is 6 points higher than the average of the scores from 2nd to 5th, and the scores for 2nd, 3rd and 4th are said to be 88, 84, and 76. How many points is 1st place worth?", "answer": "Let's denote the scores of the 1st and 5th friends as S1 and S5, respectively. We know the scores of the 2nd, 3rd, and 4th friends are 88, 84, and 76, respectively.\n\nThe overall average score for all 5 friends is 81.6, so the sum of all their scores is:\n\n5 * 81.6 = 408\n\nNow, let's calculate the sum of the scores for the 2nd, 3rd, and 4th friends:\n\n88 + 84 + 76 = 248\n\nSince the average of the scores from 1st to 4th is 6 points higher than the average of the scores from 2nd to 5th, we can set up the following equation:\n\n(S1 + 248) / 4 = (S5 + 248) / 4 + 6\n\nSolving for S1:\n\n(S1 + 248) = (S5 + 248) + 24\nS1 = S5 + 24\n\nNow, we know that the sum of all scores is 408, so:\n\nS1 + 88 + 84 + 76 + S5 = 408\nS1 + S5 + 248 = 408\nS1 + S5 = 408 - 248\nS1 + S5 = 160\n\nWe also have the equation S1 = S5 + 24. Let's substitute S1 in the equation S1 + S5 = 160:\n\n(S5 + 24) + S5 = 160\n2S5 + 24 = 160\n2S5 = 160 - 24\n2S5 = 136\nS5 = 136 / 2\nS5 = 68\n\nNow that we have S5, we can find S1:\n\nS1 = S5 + 24\nS1 = 68 + 24\nS1 = 92\n\nTherefore, the 1st place score is worth 92 points."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_917157", "question": "Evaluate $\\left|\\frac12 - \\frac38i\\right|$.", "answer": "The absolute value of a complex number $a+bi$ is defined as $\\sqrt{a^2 + b^2}$.\nIn this case, $a=\\frac12$ and $b=-\\frac38$.\nSo, $\\left|\\frac12 - \\frac38i\\right|=\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac12\\right)^2 + \\left(-\\frac38\\right)^2}=\\sqrt{\\frac14 + \\frac{9}{64}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{25}{64}}=\\boxed{\\frac{5}{8}}$.\nThe answer is: \\frac{5}{8}"}
