{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_485996", "question": "Define a function that takes in two numbers, a base and an exponent, and calculates the power of the base raised to the power of the exponent. The function should have a time complexity of O(log(n)) where n is the value of the exponent. Additionally, the function should not use any built-in exponentiation or logarithmic functions.\n\nThe base and exponent values will be positive integers greater than 1. The function should also handle cases where the exponent is negative, returning the reciprocal of the result.\n\nTo solve this problem, you should implement a binary exponentiation algorithm.\n\n1. Start by defining a function `power(base, exponent)`.\n2. Check if the exponent is equal to 0. If so, return 1, as any number raised to the power of 0 is 1.\n3. Check if the exponent is equal to 1. If so, return the base, as any number raised to the power of 1 is the number itself.\n4. If the exponent is negative, calculate the reciprocal of the result by returning 1 divided by `power(base, -exponent)`.\n5. Initialize a variable `result` with a value of 1. This variable will store the final result.\n6. Initialize a variable `current_base` with a value of `base`. This variable will store the current base during the calculations.\n7. Start a while loop with the condition `exponent > 0`.\n8. Inside the loop, check if the exponent is odd (i.e., if `exponent % 2 == 1`).\n   a. If the exponent is odd, multiply `result` by `current_base`.\n   b. Update `current_base` by multiplying it with itself (i.e., `current_base *= current_base`).\n   c. Divide the exponent by 2 (i.e., `exponent //= 2`).\n9. Finally, return the value of `result`.\n\nBy using binary exponentiation, the number of multiplications is reduced significantly, resulting in a time complexity of O(log(n)).\n\nExample:\n\npower(2, 3) should return 8.\n\nExplanation:\n2^3 = 2 * 2 * 2 = 8.\n\npower(3, 4) should return 81.\n\nExplanation:\n3^4 = 3 * 3 * 3 * 3 = 81.\n\npower(5, -2) should return 0.04.\n\nExplanation:\n5^-2 = 1 / (5 * 5) = 0.04.", "answer": "Here is the implementation of the `power` function:\n\n```python\ndef power(base, exponent):\n    if exponent == 0:\n        return 1\n    if exponent == 1:\n        return base\n    if exponent < 0:\n        return 1 / power(base, -exponent)\n    \n    result = 1\n    current_base = base\n    \n    while exponent > 0:\n        if exponent % 2 == 1:\n            result *= current_base\n        current_base *= current_base\n        exponent //= 2\n    \n    return result\n```\n\nLet's test the function with the provided examples:\n\n```python\nprint(power(2, 3))  # Output: 8\nprint(power(3, 4))  # Output: 81\nprint(power(5, -2))  # Output: 0.04\n```\n\nThe function correctly calculates the power of the base raised to the power of the exponent."}
