{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_800625", "question": "Team Soccer Stars plays in a soccer league. They played a total of 20 games, and won 14 games, lost x, and drew the rest of the matches. They earn 3 points for a win, 1 point for a draw, and nothing for a loss. How many points did they have at the end of the season?\nIf we know the answer to the above question is 46, what is the value of unknown variable x?", "answer": "Team Soccer Stars played a total of 20 games.\nThey won 14 games, which means they earned 14 * 3 = 42 points from wins.\nThey lost x games, which means they earned 0 points from losses.\nThe remaining games are draws, and they earn 1 point for each draw.\nSo, the number of draws is 20 - 14 - x = 6 - x.\nThe points earned from draws are (6 - x) * 1 = 6 - x.\nThe total points at the end of the season is the sum of the points earned from wins and draws: 42 + (6 - x) = 48 - x.\nWe are given that the total points at the end of the season is 46, so we can write: 48 - x = 46.\nSolving for x, we get: x = 2.\nThe value of x is 2.\n#### 2\nThe answer is: 2"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_859194", "question": "There are two types of pumps in a facility, type A and type B. Three pumps of type A, working 8 hours a day, can empty a 4800-gallon tank in 2 days. Two pumps of type B can empty the same amount of water in the tank in 3 days, working 10 hours a day. If there are 3 pumps of type A and 4 pumps of type B available, how many hours a day should the combined pumps work in order to empty the tank in 1 day?", "answer": "Let's first calculate the rate at which each type of pump can empty the tank.\n\nFor type A pumps:\nThree pumps working together can empty the tank in 2 days, working 8 hours a day. This means they can empty the tank in a total of \\(2 \\times 8 = 16\\) hours.\n\nThe rate at which the three pumps together can empty the tank is:\n\\[\\text{Rate of 3 type A pumps} = \\frac{4800 \\text{ gallons}}{16 \\text{ hours}} = 300 \\text{ gallons/hour}\\]\n\nSince this is the rate for 3 pumps working together, the rate for 1 type A pump is:\n\\[\\text{Rate of 1 type A pump} = \\frac{300 \\text{ gallons/hour}}{3} = 100 \\text{ gallons/hour}\\]\n\nFor type B pumps:\nTwo pumps working together can empty the tank in 3 days, working 10 hours a day. This means they can empty the tank in a total of \\(3 \\times 10 = 30\\) hours.\n\nThe rate at which the two pumps together can empty the tank is:\n\\[\\text{Rate of 2 type B pumps} = \\frac{4800 \\text{ gallons}}{30 \\text{ hours}} = 160 \\text{ gallons/hour}\\]\n\nSince this is the rate for 2 pumps working together, the rate for 1 type B pump is:\n\\[\\text{Rate of 1 type B pump} = \\frac{160 \\text{ gallons/hour}}{2} = 80 \\text{ gallons/hour}\\]\n\nNow, we have 3 type A pumps and 4 type B pumps available. The combined rate at which they can empty the tank is:\n\\[\\text{Combined rate} = (3 \\times 100) + (4 \\times 80) = 300 + 320 = 620 \\text{ gallons/hour}\\]\n\nWe want to empty the 4800-gallon tank in 1 day (24 hours). To find out how many hours a day the combined pumps should work, we divide the total volume by the combined rate:\n\\[\\text{Hours needed} = \\frac{4800 \\text{ gallons}}{620 \\text{ gallons/hour}} \\approx 7.74 \\text{ hours}\\]\n\nSince we can't work a fraction of an hour, we would need to round up to ensure the tank is emptied in 1 day. Therefore, the combined pumps should work for 8 hours a day to empty the tank in 1 day."}
