{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_64167", "question": "I didn't like this Bill Murray vehicle when it was originally released in the 80s, so I tried watching it again to see if my distaste for this film was down to my movie-going tastes in the 80s or was it that \"Stripes\" is simply a bad movie. Well, the verdict is in and \"Stripes\" is a bad movie.\n\nNow, \"Stripes\" may have been innovative comedy in the early 80s, and it may appeal to people who have gone through basic training or who are Bill Murray fans, but its still a bad movie.\n\nWhy is it bad? Mostly because \"Stripes\" is supposed to be a comedy but it's just not that funny. There are some laughs, but they are few and far between. Most of the movie is consumed by the dramatic plot which is incredibly convoluted and not very interesting. This lack of comedy is especially noticeable if you're used to more contemporary comedies such as \"Anchorman\" which strive for laughs in every part of the movie.\n\n\"Stripes\" further suffers from Bill Murray and Harold Ramis's lack of acting ability. Bill Murray is a great comedian but he was not a very compelling dramatic actor at this point in his career, and Harold Ramis is playing Harold Ramis. These two are just not good enough as actors to carry the dramatic arch of the movie.\n\nLastly, most of the comedy that there is in \"Stripes\" revolves around Bill Murray's self-centered, smart-alec man-child character so if you don't find that character funny (like I didn't) you're not going to find most of what little comedy there is in \"Stripes\" funny either.\n\n\"Stripes\" is very much a movie of its era, it hasn't aged well and is not worth watching. If you want to watch an early 80's \"buddy\" comedy I would recommend \"Stir Crazy.\" Like \"Stripes\" the humor in \"Stir Crazy\" is not as fast-paced as in contemporary comedies, but unlike \"Stripes\" it has aged much better and as a result is still watchable.\n\nIs the sentiment of this review positive or negative?\nSelect from the following.\n* negative\n* positive", "answer": "negative"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_551239", "question": "I need help creating a Python script that can filter a list of email addresses based on a specific domain. Can someone provide a solution?\n\n```python\nlist = [\"john@gmail.com\", \"sarah@yahoo.com\", \"bob@microsoft.com\", \"sophie@gmail.com\"]\n\ndef filter_by_domain(emails, domain):\n    return [email for email in emails if email.split('@')[1] == domain]\n\ndomain = \"gmail.com\"\nfiltered_list = filter_by_domain(list, domain)\n\nprint(\"Email addresses from domain '{}':\".format(domain))\nfor email in filtered_list:\n    print(email)\n```\n\nI would like the script to take a list of email addresses as input and only print the email addresses that belong to a particular domain. Can someone please explain how this code works?", "answer": "Certainly! The provided Python script will help you filter a list of email addresses based on a specific domain. Let me break it down for you:\n\nFirst, we define a list of email addresses `list`:\n```python\nlist = [\"john@gmail.com\", \"sarah@yahoo.com\", \"bob@microsoft.com\", \"sophie@gmail.com\"]\n```\n\nNext, we have a function `filter_by_domain` that takes two parameters: `emails` (the list of email addresses) and `domain` (the domain we want to filter by). This function uses a list comprehension to iterate over each email address in the `emails` list.\n\nInside the list comprehension, `email.split('@')[1]` is used to split the email address into two parts: the username and the domain. By accessing the second element (`[1]`) of the resulting list, we can compare it with the provided `domain` to check if it matches. If it does, the email address is included in the filtered list.\n\n```python\ndef filter_by_domain(emails, domain):\n    return [email for email in emails if email.split('@')[1] == domain]\n```\n\nWe then define the `domain` variable as \"gmail.com\", but you can customize it to any domain you want to filter the emails by.\n\nNext, the `filtered_list` variable is assigned the result of calling the `filter_by_domain` function with the `list` of email addresses and the `domain` we want to filter by.\n\n```python\ndomain = \"gmail.com\"\nfiltered_list = filter_by_domain(list, domain)\n```\n\nFinally, we print the filtered email addresses in a user-friendly manner by iterating over each email in the `filtered_list` and printing it.\n\n```python\nprint(\"Email addresses from domain '{}':\".format(domain))\nfor email in filtered_list:\n    print(email)\n```\n\nThis script will output only the email addresses from the specified domain, in this case, \"gmail.com\". You can easily modify the `domain` variable to filter by a different domain if needed."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1141161", "question": "Call a positive integer $n$ $k$-pretty if $n$ has exactly $k$ positive divisors and $n$ is divisible by $k$. For example, $18$ is $6$-pretty. Let $S$ be the sum of positive integers less than $2019$ that are $20$-pretty. Find $\\tfrac{S}{20}$.", "answer": "Every 20-pretty integer can be written in form $n = 2^a 5^b k$, where $a \\ge 2$, $b \\ge 1$, $\\gcd(k,10) = 1$, and $d(n) = 20$, where $d(n)$ is the number of divisors of $n$. Thus, we have $20 = (a+1)(b+1)d(k)$, using the fact that the divisor function is multiplicative. As $(a+1)(b+1)$ must be a divisor of 20, there are not many cases to check.\nIf $a+1 = 4$, then $b+1 = 5$. But this leads to no solutions, as $(a,b) = (3,4)$ gives $2^3 5^4 > 2019$.\nIf $a+1 = 5$, then $b+1 = 2$ or $4$. The first case gives $n = 2^4 \\cdot 5^1 \\cdot p$ where $p$ is a prime other than 2 or 5. Thus we have $80p < 2019 \\implies p = 3, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23$. The sum of all such $n$ is $80(3+7+11+13+17+19+23) = 7440$. In the second case $b+1 = 4$ and $d(k) = 1$, and there is one solution $n = 2^4 \\cdot 5^3 = 2000$.\nIf $a+1 = 10$, then $b+1 = 2$, but this gives $2^9 \\cdot 5^1 > 2019$. No other values for $a+1$ work.\nThen we have $\\frac{S}{20} = \\frac{80(3+7+11+13+17+19+23) + 2000}{20} = 372 + 100 = 472$."}
