{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_40970", "question": "There is three less than four times the number of students in Elementary School as there are in Middle School. If the number of students in Middle school is 50, calculate the total number of students in both levels.", "answer": "Let's denote the number of students in Middle School as M and the number of students in Elementary School as E.\n\nAccording to the problem, we have the following relationship:\n\nE = 4M - 3\n\nWe are given that the number of students in Middle School (M) is 50. So we can substitute M with 50 in the equation:\n\nE = 4(50) - 3\nE = 200 - 3\nE = 197\n\nNow, to find the total number of students in both levels, we add the number of students in Elementary School (E) to the number of students in Middle School (M):\n\nTotal number of students = E + M\nTotal number of students = 197 + 50\nTotal number of students = 247\n\nTherefore, the total number of students in both Elementary School and Middle School is 247."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_931447", "question": "Convert a binary tree into a binary circular DLL in spiral order.", "answer": "Sure! Below is a Python code snippet that converts a binary tree into a binary circular doubly linked list (DLL) in spiral order:\n\n```python\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, data):\n        self.data = data\n        self.prev = None\n        self.next = None\n\nclass BinaryTree:\n    def __init__(self, root):\n        self.root = Node(root)\n\n    def _spiral_order_util(self, node, level, left_to_right, dll_head, dll_tail):\n        if node is None:\n            return\n\n        if dll_head[0] is None:\n            dll_head[0] = node\n        else:\n            dll_tail[0].next = node\n            node.prev = dll_tail[0]\n        \n        dll_tail[0] = node\n\n        if left_to_right:\n            if node.left:\n                self._spiral_order_util(node.left, level+1, left_to_right, dll_head, dll_tail)\n            if node.right:\n                self._spiral_order_util(node.right, level+1, left_to_right, dll_head, dll_tail)\n        else:\n            if node.right:\n                self._spiral_order_util(node.right, level+1, left_to_right, dll_head, dll_tail)\n            if node.left:\n                self._spiral_order_util(node.left, level+1, left_to_right, dll_head, dll_tail)\n\n    def spiral_order_dll(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Converts a binary tree into a binary circular doubly linked list in spiral order.\n        \n        Returns:\n            Node: The head node of the doubly linked list.\n        \n        Raises:\n            ValueError: If the binary tree is empty.\n        \"\"\"\n        if self.root is None:\n            raise ValueError(\"The binary tree is empty.\")\n\n        dll_head = [None]\n        dll_tail = [None]\n\n        # Traverse the binary tree in spiral order and store the DLL head and tail\n        self._spiral_order_util(self.root, 1, True, dll_head, dll_tail)\n        \n        dll_tail[0].next = dll_head[0]\n        dll_head[0].prev = dll_tail[0]\n        \n        return dll_head[0]\n```\n\nTo use this code, you first need to create a binary tree object with the root value. Then you can call the `spiral_order_dll` method on the binary tree object to obtain the head node of the doubly linked list.\n\nHere's an example usage:\n\n```python\n# Create a binary tree with root value 1\ntree = BinaryTree(1)\n\n# Add some nodes to the binary tree\ntree.root.left = Node(2)\ntree.root.right = Node(3)\ntree.root.left.left = Node(4)\ntree.root.left.right = Node(5)\ntree.root.right.left = Node(6)\ntree.root.right.right = Node(7)\n\n# Convert binary tree to binary circular DLL in spiral order\ndll_head = tree.spiral_order_dll()\n\n# Print the DLL (traverse in both directions)\nnode = dll_head\nwhile True:\n    print(node.data)\n    node = node.next\n    if node == dll_head:\n        break\n\nnode = dll_head.prev\nwhile True:\n    print(node.data)\n    node = node.prev\n    if node == dll_head.prev:\n        break\n```\n\nThe above example will output the following sequence of values in spiral order: 1, 2, 3, 7, 6, 5, 4."}
