{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_653719", "question": "The price of 2 saris and some shirts is Rs. 1600. With the same money, one can buy 1 saree and 6 shirts. If one wants to buy 12 shirts, he shall have to pay Rs. 2400. How many shirts were bought with the 2 saris?", "answer": "Let the price of one saree be S and the price of one shirt be T.\n\nAccording to the first statement, the price of 2 sarees and some shirts (let's say x shirts) is Rs. 1600. So we can write the equation:\n2S + xT = 1600  ...(1)\n\nAccording to the second statement, with the same money (Rs. 1600), one can buy 1 saree and 6 shirts. So we can write the equation:\nS + 6T = 1600  ...(2)\n\nAccording to the third statement, the price of 12 shirts is Rs. 2400. So we can write the equation:\n12T = 2400  ...(3)\n\nFrom equation (3), we can find the price of one shirt:\nT = 2400 / 12\nT = 200\n\nNow we can substitute the value of T into equation (2) to find the price of one saree:\nS + 6(200) = 1600\nS + 1200 = 1600\nS = 1600 - 1200\nS = 400\n\nNow we have the price of one saree (S = 400) and one shirt (T = 200). We can substitute these values into equation (1) to find the number of shirts (x) that were bought with the 2 sarees:\n2(400) + x(200) = 1600\n800 + 200x = 1600\n200x = 1600 - 800\n200x = 800\nx = 800 / 200\nx = 4\n\nSo, with the 2 sarees, 4 shirts were bought."}
