{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1376916", "question": "Solve the following math problem step-by-step.\nSimplify your answer as much as possible. Present your final answer as \\boxed{Your Answer}.\nThe function \\[f(x) = \\left\\{ \\begin{aligned} x-2 & \\quad \\text{ if } x < 4 \\\\ \\sqrt{x} & \\quad \\text{ if } x \\ge 4 \\end{aligned} \\right.\\]has an inverse $f^{-1}.$ Find the value of $f^{-1}(-5) + f^{-1}(-4) + \\dots + f^{-1}(4) + f^{-1}(5).$", "answer": "Step 1:  To find the value of $f^{-1}(-5) + f^{-1}(-4) + \\dots + f^{-1}(4) + f^{-1}(5),$ we need to compute the corresponding values of the inverse function $f^{-1}$ for each input.\nStep 2:  First, we analyze the given function $f(x) = \\left\\{ \\begin{aligned} x-2 & \\quad \\text{ if } x < 4 \\\\ \\sqrt{x} & \\quad \\text{ if } x \\ge 4 \\end{aligned} \\right\\}.$\nStep 3:  We observe that for $x < 4,$ the function evaluates to $x - 2,$ and for $x \\ge 4,$ the function evaluates to $\\sqrt{x}.$\nStep 4:  To work with the inverse $f^{-1},$ we must consider the range of each component of $f(x).$\nStep 5:  Let's define $g(x) = x - 2$ for $x < 4,$ and $h(x) = \\sqrt{x}$ for $x \\ge 4.$\nStep 6:  For $x < 4,$ we have $x - 2 < 2,$ so the range of $g$ is the interval $(-\\infty, -2).$\nStep 7:  For $x \\ge 4,$ we have $\\sqrt{x} \\ge 2,$ so the range of $h$ is $[2, \\infty).$\nStep 8:  The inverse of $g$ is $g^{-1}(x) = x+2,$ while the inverse of $h$ is $h^{-1}(x) = x^2.$\nStep 9:  To compute $f^{-1}(x),$ we must use $g^{-1}$ if $x < 2,$ and use $h^{-1}$ if $x \\ge 2$.\nStep 10:  Now, we can substitute the values of $x$ from $-5$ to $5$ and compute the corresponding values of $f^{-1}(x).$\nStep 11:  By summing up these computed values, we can find the required value of $f^{-1}(-5) + f^{-1}(-4) + \\dots + f^{-1}(4) + f^{-1}(5).$\nStep 12:  Performing the calculations, we get $0 + 54 = \\boxed{54}.$\n\nAnswer:\n\\boxed{54}"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_653983", "question": "In 2008, the profits of Company N were 10 percent of revenues. In 2009, the revenues of Company N fell by 20 percent, but profits were 16 percent of revenues. In 2010, the revenues fell by 25 percent from 2009, however the profits were 20 percent of revenues. \n\nDuring the same time, in 2008, Company M had profits of 15 percent of revenues. In 2009, the revenues of Company M increased by 10 percent, and the profits increased to 20 percent of revenues. In 2010, the revenues increased by another 15 percent from 2009, but the profit percentage remained the same at 20 percent of revenues.\n\nCompare the profit growth of both companies from 2008 to 2010.", "answer": "To compare the profit growth of both companies from 2008 to 2010, we need to calculate the profits for each year and then compare the growth rates.\n\nLet's assume the revenue for Company N in 2008 was $100 (for simplicity, we will use this as a base and not actual currency). \n\nFor Company N:\n- In 2008, profits were 10% of $100, so profits = $10.\n- In 2009, revenues fell by 20%, so revenues = $100 - 20% of $100 = $80. Profits were 16% of $80, so profits = 16% of $80 = $12.8.\n- In 2010, revenues fell by another 25%, so revenues = $80 - 25% of $80 = $60. Profits were 20% of $60, so profits = 20% of $60 = $12.\n\nFor Company M, let's also assume the revenue in 2008 was $100.\n\nFor Company M:\n- In 2008, profits were 15% of $100, so profits = $15.\n- In 2009, revenues increased by 10%, so revenues = $100 + 10% of $100 = $110. Profits were 20% of $110, so profits = 20% of $110 = $22.\n- In 2010, revenues increased by another 15%, so revenues = $110 + 15% of $110 = $126.5. Profits were 20% of $126.5, so profits = 20% of $126.5 = $25.3.\n\nNow let's calculate the profit growth from 2008 to 2010 for both companies.\n\nFor Company N:\nProfit growth from 2008 to 2010 = (Profit in 2010 - Profit in 2008) / Profit in 2008\nProfit growth = ($12 - $10) / $10 = $2 / $10 = 0.2 or 20%\n\nFor Company M:\nProfit growth from 2008 to 2010 = (Profit in 2010 - Profit in 2008) / Profit in 2008\nProfit growth = ($25.3 - $15) / $15 = $10.3 / $15 ≈ 0.6867 or 68.67%\n\nComparing the profit growth of both companies from 2008 to 2010:\n- Company N had a profit growth of 20%.\n- Company M had a profit growth of approximately 68.67%.\n\nTherefore, Company M had a significantly higher profit growth compared to Company N from 2008 to 2010."}
