{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_27837", "question": "How can I write a program in Kotlin that swaps the positions of two elements in an array?", "answer": "You can achieve this by defining a function in Kotlin that takes an array, along with the indices of the elements you want to swap, as parameters. Here's an example solution:\n\n```kotlin\nfun swapElements(arr: Array<Int>, index1: Int, index2: Int) {\n    // Temporary variable to help with swapping\n    val temp = arr[index1]\n\n    // Swap elements\n    arr[index1] = arr[index2]\n    arr[index2] = temp\n}\n\nval arr = arrayOf(4, 7, 1, 3)\nswapElements(arr, 0, 3)\n\nprintln(\"Swapped Array: ${arr.joinToString()}\")\n```\n\nIn this code, the `swapElements` function takes in the array (`arr`), along with the indices of the two elements (`index1` and `index2`). It uses a temporary variable (`temp`) to store the value of the element at `index1`. Then, it assigns the value of the element at `index2` to `arr[index1]`, effectively swapping the two elements. Finally, it assigns the value of `temp` (which was the original value of the element at `index1`) to `arr[index2]`, completing the swap.\n\nThe example provided swaps the elements at index 0 and index 3 in the array `[4, 7, 1, 3]`. After the swap, the resulting array is `[3, 7, 1, 4]`. The `println` statement outputs the swapped array as a string, using `joinToString()` to concatenate the elements with a comma separator."}
