{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_3188", "question": "Police dashcam footage showed the green flash in Wisconsin and Illinois at about 01:30 local time.\nBut residents in other states including Michigan and Indiana also reported seeing the fireball light up the skies.\nThe American Meteor Society said it had received more than 185 reported sightings of the glowing object.\n\"The fireball was seen primarily from Illinois and Wisconsin, but witnesses from Michigan, Indiana, Ohio, Iowa, New York, Kentucky, Minnesota and Ontario (Canada) also reported the event,\" the society, which monitors meteor showers, said on its website.\nThe meteor travelled south-west to the north-east, ending its journey on Lake Michigan between Sheboygan and Manitowoc, Wisconsin, according to the society.\nThe fireball was also reportedly accompanied by a sonic boom that rattled homes in the area, according to meteorologist Jeff Last of the National Weather Service's office in Green Bay, Wisconsin.\nIt was not clear if the meteor landed in the water or broke up in the sky, he said.\nSeveral onlookers captured the fireball streaking across the skies on police dashcam footage and other cameras, including one atop the University of Wisconsin's Atmospheric, Oceanic and Space Sciences building in Madison, Wisconsin.\n\"It was basically visible for a long distance,\" said Ricky Castro, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service's Chicago office.\n\"It was certainly an interesting event, uncommon for the area.\"\n\nThis article was about:", "answer": "A meteor was spotted blazing across the skies in several US Midwest states early on Monday and appeared to fall over Lake Michigan."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1393148", "question": "How many distinct groups of order 10 are there, and which groups are they? Prove that all of these groups are isomorphic to either the cyclic group C10, the dihedral group D5, or the non-abelian group of order 10.", "answer": "There are three distinct groups of order 10: the cyclic group C10, the dihedral group D5, and the non-abelian group of order 10.\n\n1. Cyclic group C10:\nThe cyclic group of order 10 is generated by a single element, say a, such that a^10 = 1 and a^n ≠ 1 for 0 < n < 10. This group is abelian, and its elements are {1, a, a^2, ..., a^9}. The group operation is multiplication modulo 10.\n\n2. Dihedral group D5:\nThe dihedral group of order 10, denoted as D5, is the group of symmetries of a regular pentagon. It consists of 5 rotations and 5 reflections. We can represent the elements of D5 as {r^n, sr^n | n = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4}, where r is the rotation by 72 degrees (1/5 of a full rotation) and s is a reflection. The group operation is composition of symmetries, and the group has the following relations: r^5 = 1, s^2 = 1, and sr = r^4s.\n\n3. Non-abelian group of order 10:\nLet G be a non-abelian group of order 10. By the Sylow theorems, G must have a normal Sylow 5-subgroup, say H, of order 5. Since the order of H is prime, H must be cyclic, so H ≅ C5. Let K be a Sylow 2-subgroup of G, which has order 2. Since G is non-abelian, K cannot be a normal subgroup of G. The group G can be expressed as a semi-direct product of H and K: G = H ⋊ K.\n\nNow, we will show that all groups of order 10 are isomorphic to one of these three groups:\n\n1. If a group of order 10 is abelian, it must be isomorphic to C10. This is because the only abelian groups of order 10 are C10 and C2 × C5, but C2 × C5 is isomorphic to C10.\n\n2. If a group of order 10 is non-abelian and has a normal Sylow 2-subgroup, it must be isomorphic to D5. This is because the semi-direct product of a cyclic group of order 5 and a cyclic group of order 2 with the non-trivial action is isomorphic to D5.\n\n3. If a group of order 10 is non-abelian and has a normal Sylow 5-subgroup, it must be isomorphic to the non-abelian group of order 10 described above. This is because the semi-direct product of a cyclic group of order 5 and a cyclic group of order 2 with the trivial action is isomorphic to the non-abelian group of order 10.\n\nThus, all groups of order 10 are isomorphic to either C10, D5, or the non-abelian group of order 10."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_893066", "question": "How can I compile a C++ function that takes an array and its length and outputs a rotated version of the array?", "answer": "Here is an example code snippet that demonstrates how to achieve this in C++:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nvoid rightRotate(int arr[], int n)\n{\n    int temp = arr[n-1];\n     \n    for (int i = n-1; i > 0; i--)\n       arr[i] = arr[i-1];\n     \n    arr[0] = temp;\n}\n\nint main(){\n    int arr[] = {2, 3, 4, 5, 6};\n    int length = 5;\n    rightRotate(arr, length);\n    \n    for (int i = 0; i < length; i++)\n        std::cout << arr[i] << \" \";\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `rightRotate` function takes an array (`arr`) and its length (`n`) as parameters. It performs a right rotation by moving each element to its adjacent right position, starting from the last element. The last element is temporarily stored in a variable (`temp`) before being placed at the beginning of the array. This effectively rotates the array to the right.\n\nThe `main` function demonstrates the usage of the `rightRotate` function by creating an array (`arr`) with initial values and specifying its length (`length`). The `rightRotate` function is then called with these arguments to rotate the array. Finally, a loop is used to print the rotated array elements using `std::cout`.\n\nWhen executing this program, the output will be `6 2 3 4 5`, which represents the rotated version of the original array `[2, 3, 4, 5, 6]`."}
