{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_973875", "question": "If x ^ 2 + ( 1 / x ^ 2 ) = 7, what is the value of x ^ 4 + ( 1 / x ^ 4 )?", "answer": "Let's solve this step by step.\n\nGiven:\nx^2 + (1/x^2) = 7\n\nWe want to find the value of:\nx^4 + (1/x^4)\n\nFirst, let's square both sides of the given equation to find x^4 + (1/x^4) + 2, because when we square x^2 + (1/x^2), we will get x^4 + 2*(x^2)*(1/x^2) + (1/x^4), and since (x^2)*(1/x^2) = 1, it simplifies to x^4 + 2 + (1/x^4).\n\n(x^2 + 1/x^2)^2 = 7^2\nx^4 + 2*(x^2)*(1/x^2) + 1/x^4 = 49\nx^4 + 2 + 1/x^4 = 49\n\nNow, we subtract 2 from both sides to isolate x^4 + (1/x^4):\n\nx^4 + 1/x^4 = 49 - 2\nx^4 + 1/x^4 = 47\n\nTherefore, the value of x^4 + (1/x^4) is 47."}
