{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_390656", "question": "Solve the following math problem step-by-step.\nSimplify your answer as much as possible. Present your final answer as \\boxed{Your Answer}.\nEric, Ben, and Jack have some money. Eric has $10 less than Ben, and Ben has $9 less than Jack. If Jack has $26, how much money, in dollars, do all 3 of them have in total?", "answer": "Step 1: Let's assume the amount of money Jack has is J dollars.\nStep 2: According to the information given, Ben has $9 less than Jack. So Ben has (J-9) dollars.\nStep 3: Eric has $10 less than Ben. So Eric has (J-9-10) dollars, which simplifies to (J-19) dollars.\nStep 4: We are given that Jack has $26. So J = 26.\nStep 5: Now we can calculate the total amount of money all three of them have. Total = 26 + (26-9) + (26-19) = 26 + 17 + 7 = 50.\n\nAnswer:\n\\boxed{50}"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_964434", "question": "Andrew installed hardwood flooring in his house. His bedroom took eight wooden planks, his living room took twenty planks, his kitchen took eleven planks, and his dining room took thirteen planks. The guest bedroom took two fewer planks than Andrew’s bedroom, and each of his two hallways took four planks. The study took the same number of planks as the guest bedroom, plus three. He also installed wooden planks in his home office and the playroom; both rooms together required a total of P planks.\n\nHe accidentally ruined three planks in each bedroom, two planks in the living room, and one plank in the study by dragging furniture over them and had to replace them. The total number of ruined planks was 20% of the total number of planks he initially purchased. He ended up with seven leftover planks at the end. How many wooden planks did Andrew buy to start with, and how many planks were used in the home office and the playroom?", "answer": "Let's calculate the number of planks Andrew used for each room, including the extra planks he had to replace due to damage.\n\nBedrooms:\n- Andrew's bedroom: 8 planks + 3 ruined = 11 planks\n- Guest bedroom: 8 - 2 = 6 planks + 3 ruined = 9 planks\n- Study: 6 + 3 = 9 planks + 1 ruined = 10 planks\n\nOther rooms:\n- Living room: 20 planks + 2 ruined = 22 planks\n- Kitchen: 11 planks\n- Dining room: 13 planks\n- Hallways: 2 * 4 = 8 planks\n\nTotal planks used (excluding home office and playroom):\n11 (Andrew's bedroom) + 9 (Guest bedroom) + 10 (Study) + 22 (Living room) + 11 (Kitchen) + 13 (Dining room) + 8 (Hallways) = 84 planks\n\nNow, let's denote the total number of planks Andrew bought as T and the number of planks used in the home office and the playroom as P. We know that the total number of ruined planks was 20% of T, and that number is 20 planks. So:\n\n0.20 * T = 20\nT = 20 / 0.20\nT = 100 planks\n\nNow we can find out how many planks were used in the home office and the playroom (P). We know that Andrew ended up with 7 leftover planks, so:\n\nT = 84 (used in known rooms) + P (home office and playroom) + 7 (leftover)\n100 = 84 + P + 7\n100 = 91 + P\nP = 100 - 91\nP = 9 planks\n\nSo, Andrew bought 100 planks to start with, and 9 planks were used in the home office and the playroom."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_52917", "question": "Write a Bash script to accept two command line arguments (username and password) and echo them out. Additionally, the script should check if the password meets the following criteria:\n- The password must be at least 12 characters long.\n- The password must contain at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one digit, and one special character (!@#$%^&*).\n\nIf the password does not meet these criteria, the script should display an error message instead of echoing the password.\n\nFurthermore, the script should handle the following scenarios:\n- If no command line arguments are provided, the script should display an error message and exit.\n- If only one command line argument is provided, the script should display an error message and exit.\n- If more than two command line arguments are provided, the script should ignore any extra arguments and proceed with the first two arguments.\n\nExample usage and expected output:\n```\n$ bash script.sh johnDoe Password123!\nUsername: johnDoe\nPassword: Password123!\n\n$ bash script.sh janeSmith 123\nUsername: janeSmith\nError: Password must be at least 12 characters long and contain at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one digit, and one special character.\n\n$ bash script.sh\nError: Please provide both username and password.\n\n$ bash script.sh johnDoe Password123! extraArgument\nUsername: johnDoe\nPassword: Password123!\n```", "answer": "Here's a Bash script that meets the requirements:\n\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\n\n# Check if username and password are provided as command line arguments\nif [ $# -lt 2 ]; then\n    echo \"Error: Please provide both username and password.\"\n    exit 1\nfi\n\n# Get the first two command line arguments\nusername=$1\npassword=$2\n\n# Check if password meets the criteria\nif [[ ${#password} -lt 12 || !($password =~ [[:upper:]]) || !($password =~ [[:lower:]]) || !($password =~ [[:digit:]]) || !($password =~ [!@#$%^&*]) ]]; then\n    echo \"Username: $username\"\n    echo \"Error: Password must be at least 12 characters long and contain at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one digit, and one special character.\"\nelse\n    echo \"Username: $username\"\n    echo \"Password: $password\"\nfi\n```\n\nYou can save this script to a file, for example `script.sh`, and run it from the command line with the provided username and password as arguments."}
