past six months Essex Police's investigations have led to 33 people being jailed for more than 180 years in total for sexual offences against children.\nNick Alston, Police and Crime Commissioner for Essex, said: \"Despite the very disappointing news today, I know that day by day, Essex police officers continue to handle many cases well, and for that they have my full support.\"\nWhat was that article about?", "answer": "Police are failing to protect children at risk of harm in Essex, investigators have found."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_517904", "question": "I'm trying to define a function that will take a reference as a parameter, and call a **generic** method on the referenced object, passing in a concrete value. I need a way of requiring that the generic type of the parameter passed to my function is a trait of the concrete type that the function will use it with. I can't seem to work out how to do this.\n\nA minimal example of the sort of thing I'm trying to achieve:\n\n```rust\ntrait Vehicle {}\ntrait Floating {}\n\nstruct Boat;\nimpl Vehicle for Boat {}\nimpl Floating for Boat {}\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut a: Vec<Box<dyn Vehicle>> = vec![];\n    populate(&mut a); // Does not compile\n\n    let mut b: Vec<Box<dyn Floating>> = vec![];\n    populate(&mut b); // Also does not compile\n}\n\nfn populate(receiver: &mut Vec<Box<Boat>>) { // What should I put here?\n    receiver.push(Box::new(Boat{}));\n}\n```\n\nTrying to compile this gives the following errors:\n\n```\nerror[E0308]: mismatched types\n  --> src/main.rs:10:14\n   |\n10 |     populate(&mut a); // Does not compile\n   |              ^^^^^^ expected struct `Boat`, found trait object `dyn Vehicle`\n   |\n   = note: expected mutable reference `&mut std::vec::Vec<std::boxed::Box<Boat>>`\n              found mutable reference `&mut std::vec::Vec<std::boxed::Box<dyn Vehicle>>`\n\nerror[E0308]: mismatched types\n  --> src/main.rs:13:14\n   |\n13 |     populate(&mut b); // Also does not compile\n   |              ^^^^^^ expected struct `Boat`, found trait object `dyn Floating`\n   |\n   = note: expected mutable reference `&mut std::vec::Vec<std::boxed::Box<Boat>>`\n              found mutable reference `&mut std::vec::Vec<std::boxed::Box<dyn Floating>>`\n```\n\nI didn't expect this to compile, but I don't know how to change the signature of `populate` so that it will. I come from Java land, where I would achieve this using this using a bounded wildcard (e.g. `void populate(List<? super Boat> receiver)`), but I can't find anything to suggest that Rust offers equivalent semantics.\n\nHow might I go about fixing my definition of `populate` here?\n\nI'm new to Rust, so bear with me if I'm completely barking up the wrong tree. I've searched around, and can't seem to find an example of how this pattern should be implemented.", "answer": "In Rust, you can create and implement a trait for every unique trait object you are interested in. Here's how you can fix your `populate` function:\n\n```rust\ntrait Shipyard {\n    fn construct(boat: Boat) -> Box<Self>;\n}\n\nimpl Shipyard for Boat {\n    fn construct(boat: Boat) -> Box<Self> {\n        Box::new(boat)\n    }\n}\n\nimpl Shipyard for dyn Vehicle {\n    fn construct(boat: Boat) -> Box<dyn Vehicle> {\n        Box::new(boat) as Box<dyn Vehicle>\n    }\n}\n\nimpl Shipyard for dyn Floating {\n    fn construct(boat: Boat) -> Box<dyn Floating> {\n        Box::new(boat) as Box<dyn Floating>\n    }\n}\n\nfn populate<T: ?Sized>(receiver: &mut Vec<Box<T>>)\nwhere\n    T: Shipyard,\n{\n    receiver.push(T::construct(Boat));\n}\n```\n\nHere, we define a `Shipyard` trait that has a generic method `construct` which takes a `Boat` and returns a boxed object of the implementing type. We then implement this trait for `Boat` itself, as well as for the `dyn Vehicle` and `dyn Floating` trait objects.\n\nIn the `populate` function, we use the `Shipyard` trait as a trait bound for the generic type `T`, and we require that the `receiver` vector contains boxes of type `T`. This allows us to call the `construct` method on `T` and push the resulting boxed object into the `receiver` vector.\n\nNote that in stable Rust, you need to create and implement a separate trait for each unique trait object you want to use with the `populate` function. However, in nightly Rust, you can use the unstable `CoerceUnsized` trait to simplify the code. Here's an example using nightly Rust:\n\n```rust\n#![feature(coerce_unsized)]\n\nuse std::ops::CoerceUnsized;\n\nfn populate<T: ?Sized>(receiver: &mut Vec<Box<T>>)\nwhere\n    Box<Boat>: CoerceUnsized<Box<T>>,\n{\n    receiver.push(Box::new(Boat) as Box<T>);\n}\n```\n\nIn this version, we use the `CoerceUnsized` trait to specify that `Box<Boat>` can be coerced to `Box<T>`, allowing us to push a boxed `Boat` into the `receiver` vector. However, note that this code relies on unstable features and may not work in all Rust versions.\n\nI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions."}
