{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_373147", "question": "Develop a Golang command-line tool that accepts a URL as input, downloads the HTML content of the page, and counts the frequency of each word on the page. The tool should output the top 10 most frequent words along with their count.\nPLAINFORMAT", "answer": "package main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"io/ioutil\"\n\t\"net/http\"\n\t\"os\"\n\t\"regexp\"\n\t\"sort\"\n\t\"strings\"\n)\n\ntype WordCount struct {\n\tWord  string\n\tCount int\n}\n\nfunc main() {\n\tif len(os.Args) != 2 {\n\t\tfmt.Println(\"Usage: go run main.go <URL>\")\n\t\tos.Exit(1)\n\t}\n\n\turl := os.Args[1]\n\tcontent, err := fetchContent(url)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tfmt.Printf(\"Error fetching content from %s: %v\\n\", url, err)\n\t\tos.Exit(1)\n\t}\n\n\twordCounts := countWords(content)\n\ttop10 := getTopN(wordCounts, 10)\n\n\tfor _, wc := range top10 {\n\t\tfmt.Printf(\"%s: %d\\n\", wc.Word, wc.Count)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc fetchContent(url string) (string, error) {\n\tresp, err := http.Get(url)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn \"\", err\n\t}\n\tdefer resp.Body.Close()\n\n\tbodyBytes, err := ioutil.ReadAll(resp.Body)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn \"\", err\n\t}\n\n\treturn string(bodyBytes), nil\n}\n\nfunc countWords(content string) map[string]int {\n\tre := regexp.MustCompile(`\\b[\\w']+\\b`)\n\twords := re.FindAllString(strings.ToLower(content), -1)\n\n\twordCounts := make(map[string]int)\n\tfor _, word := range words {\n\t\twordCounts[word]++\n\t}\n\n\treturn wordCounts\n}\n\nfunc getTopN(wordCounts map[string]int, n int) []WordCount {\n\tcounts := make([]WordCount, 0, len(wordCounts))\n\tfor word, count := range wordCounts {\n\t\tcounts = append(counts, WordCount{word, count})\n\t}\n\n\tsort.Slice(counts, func(i, j int) bool {\n\t\treturn counts[i].Count > counts[j].Count\n\t})\n\n\tif len(counts) > n {\n\t\tcounts = counts[:n]\n\t}\n\n\treturn counts\n}"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_903336", "question": "Using the given code snippet, generate a linked list containing numbers from 1 to n in a circular manner, with n being the last node pointing back to the first node.\nn = 5", "answer": "Below is a Python solution using a basic structure for a singly linked list node.\n\n```python\nclass Node:\n    def __init__(self, data=None):\n        self.data = data\n        self.next = None\n\nclass CircularLinkedList:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.head = None\n\n    def append(self, data):\n        if not self.head:\n            self.head = Node(data)\n            self.head.next = self.head\n        else:\n            new_node = Node(data)\n            cur = self.head\n            while cur.next != self.head:\n                cur = cur.next\n            cur.next = new_node\n            new_node.next = self.head\n\n    def display(self):\n        elements = []\n        cur_node = self.head\n        while True:\n            elements.append(cur_node.data)\n            cur_node = cur_node.next\n            if cur_node == self.head:\n                break\n        return elements\n\nn = 5\nCLL = CircularLinkedList()\nfor i in range(1, n+1):\n    CLL.append(i)\n\nprint(CLL.display())\n```\n\nThe above code first creates the classes for the Node and the Circular Linked List. In the Circular Linked List class, there are methods to append data into the list and a method to display the data present in the list. The append method checks if the head is none and if this is the case, it creates the head node, otherwise, it traverses the linked list until it finds the node that has next as the head. This is effectively the last node in the circular linked list (due to its circular nature).\n\nThen, we add nodes in the range from 1 to 5 in the circular linked list and the display function is run to print the nodes' data of the linked list. The display function starts at the list's head and continues until it finds the element which points next to the head, indicating that we are at the ending of the circular linked list, hence we stop. We use a list `elements` to track all nodes in order that can be printed out as the result."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1388490", "question": "Write Java code to create a class called Card with two string fields, rank and suit. The rank should only be one of the following values: \"Ace\", \"2\", \"3\", \"4\", \"5\", \"6\", \"7\", \"8\", \"9\", \"10\", \"Jack\", \"Queen\", \"King\". The suit should only be one of the following values: \"Hearts\", \"Diamonds\", \"Clubs\", \"Spades\". The Card class should also include a method called \"getValue\" that returns the numeric value of the card based on its rank. The numeric value should be as follows: \"Ace\" = 1, \"2\"-\"10\" = respective numeric value, \"Jack\"-\"King\" = 10.", "answer": "Here is the Java code for the Card class:\n\n```java\npublic class Card {\n    private String rank;\n    private String suit;\n    \n    public Card(String rank, String suit) {\n        this.rank = rank;\n        this.suit = suit;\n    }\n    \n    public String getRank() {\n        return rank;\n    }\n    \n    public String getSuit() {\n        return suit;\n    }\n    \n    public int getValue() {\n        if (rank.equals(\"Ace\")) {\n            return 1;\n        } else if (rank.equals(\"Jack\") || rank.equals(\"Queen\") || rank.equals(\"King\")) {\n            return 10;\n        } else {\n            return Integer.parseInt(rank);\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow, you can create instances of the Card class and use the getValue() method to get the numeric value of the card:\n\n```java\nCard card1 = new Card(\"Ace\", \"Spades\");\nSystem.out.println(card1.getValue()); // Output: 1\n\nCard card2 = new Card(\"10\", \"Diamonds\");\nSystem.out.println(card2.getValue()); // Output: 10\n\nCard card3 = new Card(\"King\", \"Hearts\");\nSystem.out.println(card3.getValue()); // Output: 10\n```"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_675979", "question": "Create a list of unique elements from a list of numbers. However, instead of using built-in functions or libraries to solve the problem, you should implement your own algorithm to achieve this. Additionally, your algorithm should have a time complexity of O(n^2) and a space complexity of O(1), meaning it should solve the problem in a single pass through the list but should not use any additional data structures such as sets or dictionaries.\n\nYou can assume that the input list will always be non-empty and will only contain integer elements.\n\nExample:\nnums = [1, 1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 6]\n\nOutput:\n[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]", "answer": "Here is one possible solution to the problem:\n\n```python\ndef get_unique_elements(nums):\n    unique_elements = []\n    for i in range(len(nums)):\n        is_unique = True\n        for j in range(i + 1, len(nums)):\n            if nums[i] == nums[j]:\n                is_unique = False\n                break\n        if is_unique:\n            unique_elements.append(nums[i])\n    return unique_elements\n```\n\nIn this solution, we iterate over each element in the input list `nums`. For each element, we iterate over the rest of the list to check if it is unique. If we find another occurrence of the element, we set a flag `is_unique` to `False` and break out of the inner loop. If the flag remains `True` after the inner loop, it means the element is unique and we add it to the `unique_elements` list.\n\nThis algorithm has a time complexity of O(n^2) because for each element, we iterate over the remaining elements in the list. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single additional list to store the unique elements."}
