{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1104361", "question": "A batsman in some innings makes a score of 85, and thereby increases his average by 3. His average after that innings is 43. He had never been 'not out'. In which innings did he make the score of 85?", "answer": "Let's denote the number of innings before the innings in which he scored 85 as \\( n \\). His average before scoring 85 was \\( 43 - 3 = 40 \\).\n\nThe total runs scored in \\( n \\) innings would be \\( 40n \\).\n\nAfter scoring 85 in the \\( (n+1)^{th} \\) innings, his average became 43. Therefore, the total runs scored after \\( (n+1) \\) innings would be \\( 43(n+1) \\).\n\nThe difference between the total runs scored after \\( (n+1) \\) innings and the total runs before that innings is the score of the \\( (n+1)^{th} \\) innings, which is 85.\n\nSo we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ 43(n+1) = 40n + 85 \\]\n\nNow we solve for \\( n \\):\n\n\\[ 43n + 43 = 40n + 85 \\]\n\\[ 43n - 40n = 85 - 43 \\]\n\\[ 3n = 42 \\]\n\\[ n = \\frac{42}{3} \\]\n\\[ n = 14 \\]\n\nSo, the batsman made the score of 85 in his \\( 15^{th} \\) innings (since we were looking for the innings after the \\( 14 \\) innings already played)."}
