{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_632761", "question": "Phillip is taking a math test and an English test on Monday. The math test has some questions and he gets 75% of them right. The English test has 50 questions and he gets 98% of them right. He gets a total of 79 questions right. How many questions were on the math test?", "answer": "Let's denote the total number of questions on the math test as M.\n\nFrom the information given, Phillip gets 75% of the math questions right, which means he answers 0.75M questions correctly on the math test.\n\nOn the English test, he gets 98% of 50 questions right, which is 0.98 * 50 = 49 questions.\n\nWe know that the total number of questions he gets right from both tests is 79. So, the sum of the correct answers from both tests should equal 79:\n\n0.75M (correct math answers) + 49 (correct English answers) = 79\n\nNow, we can solve for M:\n\n0.75M = 79 - 49\n0.75M = 30\n\nTo find M, we divide both sides by 0.75:\n\nM = 30 / 0.75\nM = 40\n\nSo, there were 40 questions on the math test."}
