{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_785771", "question": "In a class of 20 students, 2 students did not borrow any books from the library, 8 students each borrowed 1 book, 3 students each borrowed 2 books, and the rest borrowed at least 3 books. If the average number of books per student was 2, what is the maximum number of books any single student could have borrowed?", "answer": "Let's calculate the total number of books borrowed by the students.\n\nWe have:\n- 2 students who borrowed 0 books, contributing 0 * 2 = 0 books to the total.\n- 8 students who borrowed 1 book each, contributing 1 * 8 = 8 books to the total.\n- 3 students who borrowed 2 books each, contributing 2 * 3 = 6 books to the total.\n\nThe total number of students accounted for so far is 2 + 8 + 3 = 13 students.\n\nThis leaves 20 - 13 = 7 students who borrowed at least 3 books.\n\nThe average number of books per student is 2, so the total number of books borrowed by the 20 students is 20 * 2 = 40 books.\n\nWe have already accounted for 0 + 8 + 6 = 14 books.\n\nThis means the 7 students who borrowed at least 3 books must have borrowed a total of 40 - 14 = 26 books.\n\nIf we want to maximize the number of books borrowed by a single student, we should minimize the number of books borrowed by the other 6 students in this group. Since each of these 6 students borrowed at least 3 books, the minimum they could have borrowed is 3 * 6 = 18 books.\n\nSubtracting this from the 26 books borrowed by the group of 7 students, we find that the maximum number of books a single student could have borrowed is 26 - 18 = 8 books."}
