{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_829732", "question": "If $a \\bowtie b = a+\\sqrt{b+\\sqrt{b+\\sqrt{b+...}}}$, and $4\\bowtie y = 10$, what is the value of $y$?", "answer": "We have $4 \\bowtie y = 4 + \\sqrt{y + \\sqrt{y + \\sqrt{y + ... }}}.$\nSince $4 \\bowtie y = 10,$ we can write\n\\[10 = 4 + \\sqrt{y + \\sqrt{y + \\sqrt{y + ... }}}.\\]\nLet $x = \\sqrt{y + \\sqrt{y + \\sqrt{y + ... }}}.$  Then we have $x = \\sqrt{y + x},$ so $x^2 = y + x.$\nSubstituting into the equation $10 = 4 + x,$ we get $x = 6.$  Then $x^2 = y + x$ becomes $36 = y + 6,$ so $y = \\boxed{30}.$\nThe answer is: 30"}
