{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_878009", "question": "Line a is parallel to the line y = 2x + 4 and intersects the point (2, 5). What is the y-intercept of line a?", "answer": "Since line a is parallel to the line $y = 2x + 4$, it has the same slope of 2.\nUsing the point-slope form of a linear equation, we have $y - 5 = 2(x - 2)$.\nSimplifying, we get $y - 5 = 2x - 4$.\nAdding 5 to both sides, we get $y = 2x + 1$.\nThe y-intercept of line a is the value of y when x is 0, so the y-intercept is $\\boxed{1}$.\nThe answer is: 1"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_925462", "question": "I have this problem : Determine if Two Strings Are Close\nDescription are as below: Two strings are considered close if you can attain one from the other using the following operations:\nOperation 1: Swap any two existing characters.\n\nFor example, `abcde -> aecdb`\nOperation 2: Transform every occurrence of one existing character into another existing character, and do the same with the other character.\n\nFor example, `aacabb -> bbcbaa` (all `a`s turn into `b`s, and all `b`s turn into `a`s)\nYou can use the operations on either string as many times as necessary.\n\nGiven two strings, `word1` and `word2`, return `true` if `word1` and `word2` are close, and `false` otherwise. Additionally, return the minimum number of operations required to transform `word1` into `word2` if they are close.\n\nExample 1:\nInput: word1 = \"abc\", word2 = \"bca\"\nOutput: true, 2\nExplanation: You can attain word2 from word1 in 2 operations.\n\nApply Operation 1: \"abc\" -> \"acb\"\nApply Operation 1: \"acb\" -> \"bca\"\n\nExample 2:\nInput: word1 = \"a\", word2 = \"aa\"\nOutput: false, -1\nExplanation: It is impossible to attain word2 from word1, or vice versa, in any number of operations.\n\nExample 3:\nInput: word1 = \"cabbba\", word2 = \"abbccc\"\nOutput: true, 3\nExplanation: You can attain word2 from word1 in 3 operations.\n\nApply Operation 1: \"cabbba\" -> \"caabbb\"\nApply Operation 2: \"caabbb\" -> \"baaccc\"\nApply Operation 2: \"baaccc\" -> \"abbccc\"\n\nExample 4:\nInput: word1 = \"cabbba\", word2 = \"aabbss\"\nOutput: false, -1\nExplanation: It is impossible to attain word2 from word1, or vice versa, in any amount of operations.\n\nConstraints:\n`1 <= word1.length, word2.length <= 105`\n`word1` and `word2` contain only lowercase English letters.", "answer": "This problem is of string type and can be solved using Python. It can be solved with the help of sets and collections modules in Python . Since we have to determine if word1 can be transformed to word2 which involves swapping of letters and replacing all occurrences of a letter with other, to satisfy these conditions, the type of distinct letters and the frequency for each type of letter in the two strings can be established as below conditions:\n\n1. Both strings must have the same set of distinct letters.\n2. Sorted frequency list of letters in both strings should be same.\n\nA Pythonic solution will be as follows:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import Counter\n\ndef closeStrings(word1: str, word2: str) -> bool:\n    counter1, counter2 = Counter(word1), Counter(word2)\n    return set(word1) == set(word2) and sorted(counter1.values()) == sorted(counter2.values())\n\ndef opCount(word1: str, word2: str) -> int:\n    if not closeStrings(word1, word2): return -1\n  \n    count_op = 0\n    counter1, counter2 = Counter(word1), Counter(word2)\n  \n    for k in counter1.keys():\n        if counter1[k] != counter2[k]:\n            count_op += abs(counter1[k] - counter2[k])\n  \n    return count_op // 2  # Because we are considering 2 letters at the same time.\n```\n\nHere `Counter` is a function in `collections` module in Python. It's a container that stores elements as dictionary keys and their counts as dictionary values. It counts the frequency of each character in the strings.\n\nThis Python function first checks if the `word1` and `word2` are closeStrings or not, if not then returns `False, -1`. If they are close, then it finds the minimum number of operations needed and returns `True` with the operation count.\n\nNote: Operation count can always be calculated as being half of the absolute sum of the frequency difference of matching letters across both strings, because every operation involves 2 letters."}
