{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_630613", "question": "French national Pierre Legris, 61, is accused of killing Rui Li, 44, by hitting her over the head with a blunt implement at their Bournemouth home.\nThe Chinese national, who moved to the UK in 2003 and worked as a nurse, was found in the boot of a Fiat Punto car a week after going missing on 23 May.\nMr Legris denies murder.\nNigel Lickley QC, prosecuting, told Winchester Crown Court Mr Legris, also known as Alain Baron, conspired to murder Ms Li with Irene Smith, 66, and their son Jonathan Legris, 27, for her life insurance policy.\nHe said Pierre Legris went to a police station four days after her murder.\n\"He said he had been away and when he returned on Sunday she wasn't there. He was vague and not in a hurry.\"\nIn a later interview \"officers formed the impression he wasn't overly concerned about her being missing\", he added.\n\"He showed no emotion... his son Jonathan was eating his lunch, similarly showing little concern.\"\nHe added Ms Smith told police her husband was at her home on the night Ms Li died, where they ate a meal and watched Eastenders.\nBut the jury was shown CCTV footage of Pierre Legris arriving there at about 04:45 BST.\nThe couple were also seen at a dancing competition in Watford the next day walking \"arm-in-arm, hand-in-hand\".\nMr Lickley said this showed \"the closeness of their relationship\".\nAnother CCTV video showed Pierre Legris and his son drive a Transit van from Ms Lui's home in Burnham Drive to Cromer Motors in St Clement's Road, a business that father and son ran together.\nMr Lickley said Ms Li's body was inside the van.\n\"It was all planned and agreed the van would be moved back to the garage, they would carry on as normal and deal with Rui Li at some future time.\"\nPrior to the start of the trial, Mr Legris pleaded guilty to an offence of bigamy by marrying Ms Li in 2007 while having been married to Ms Smith since 1987.\nJonathan Legris and Irene Smith deny a charge of conspiracy to murder.\nMs Smith, of St Clement's Road, also denies a charge of perverting the course of justice by providing a false alibi.\nShe also denies an offence of assisting an offender by hiring a storage facility and placing her husband's clothes and French passport in it.\nJonathan Legris, of Spring Road, Bournemouth, also denies a charge of assisting an offender by driving the Fiat Punto with Ms Li's body inside.\nThe trial continues.\n\nThis article was about:", "answer": "A bigamist accused of conspiring with his first wife and son to kill his second wife showed \"no emotion\" as he reported her missing, a court heard."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1273925", "question": "Devise a meticulously constructed pattern, using regular expression syntax, that can accurately detect and isolate the precise sequence of characters that form the phrase \"hello people\".", "answer": "Here is a Python code snippet that uses regular expression (package `re`) to detect and isolate the phrase \"hello people\".\n\n```python\nimport re\n\ndef find_phrase(text):\n    pattern = re.compile(r'\\bhello people\\b')  # compile regex pattern\n    match = pattern.search(text)  # search for the pattern in the text\n    if match:\n        return match.group()  # if found, return the match\n    else:\n        return None  # if not found, return None\n\ntext = 'Say hello people of the world!'\nprint(find_phrase(text))  # will print \"hello people\"\n```\n\nThis regular expression pattern `r'\\bhello people\\b'` checks for the exact phrase \"hello people\". The `\\b` in the pattern represents a word boundary, so it ensures that the phrase is not part of a larger word (like \"ahello peopleb\"). This helps to isolate the exact phrase \"hello people\"."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_284020", "question": "Let A = {1, 2} and B = {3, 4}. Find the Cartesian products of (A × B) × B and A × (B × B) and show that they are equal.", "answer": "First, let's find the Cartesian product A × B:\n\nA × B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}\n\nNow let's find the Cartesian product (A × B) × B:\n\n(A × B) × B = {((1, 3), 3), ((1, 3), 4), ((1, 4), 3), ((1, 4), 4), ((2, 3), 3), ((2, 3), 4), ((2, 4), 3), ((2, 4), 4)}\n\nNext, let's find the Cartesian product B × B:\n\nB × B = {(3, 3), (3, 4), (4, 3), (4, 4)}\n\nNow let's find the Cartesian product A × (B × B):\n\nA × (B × B) = {(1, (3, 3)), (1, (3, 4)), (1, (4, 3)), (1, (4, 4)), (2, (3, 3)), (2, (3, 4)), (2, (4, 3)), (2, (4, 4))}\n\nNow, let's rewrite the elements of A × (B × B) to match the format of (A × B) × B:\n\nA × (B × B) = {((1, 3), 3), ((1, 3), 4), ((1, 4), 3), ((1, 4), 4), ((2, 3), 3), ((2, 3), 4), ((2, 4), 3), ((2, 4), 4)}\n\nComparing the two sets, we can see that:\n\n(A × B) × B = A × (B × B)\n\nThus, the Cartesian products of (A × B) × B and A × (B × B) are equal."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_508711", "question": "Can you provide a code example for a function that calculates the number of elements in a binary tree?", "answer": "Sure! Here's an example of how you can define a function to count the number of elements in a binary tree:\n\n```python\ndef count_elements_in_binary_tree(root):\n    if root is None:\n        return 0\n\n    return 1 + count_elements_in_binary_tree(root.left) + count_elements_in_binary_tree(root.right)\n```\n\nIn this code, the `count_elements_in_binary_tree` function takes the root of the binary tree as an input. \n\nFirst, it checks if the root is `None`, which means the tree is empty. In this case, it returns 0, indicating that there are no elements in the tree.\n\nIf the root is not `None`, the function recursively calls itself on the left and right child nodes of the current root. It then adds 1 (representing the current element) to the count of elements in the left subtree and the count of elements in the right subtree.\n\nBy using recursion, the function traverses the entire binary tree, counting each element along the way. Finally, it returns the total count of elements in the binary tree."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_925117", "question": "In a right-angled triangle, the sum of the squares of the three side lengths is 1800.  What is the length of the hypotenuse of this triangle?", "answer": "Let the side lengths of the right-angled triangle be $a$, $b$, and $c$,\nwhere $c$ is the length of the hypotenuse.\nAccording to the Pythagorean Theorem, we have $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$.\nWe are given that $a^2 + b^2 + c^2 = 1800$.\nSubstituting the first equation into the second equation, we get $c^2 + c^2 = 1800$,\nor $2c^2 = 1800$.\nDividing both sides by 2, we have $c^2 = 900$.\nTaking the square root of both sides, we find that $c = \\boxed{30}$.\nThe answer is: 30"}
