{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_238808", "question": "Determine the range of the function $G(x) = |x+1| - |x-1|$, and express your answer using interval notation.", "answer": "First, let's consider the different cases for the value of $x$.\nIf $x \\leq -1$, then $x+1 \\leq 0$ and $x-1 \\leq -2$, so $|x+1| = -(x+1)$ and $|x-1| = -(x-1)$.\nTherefore, $G(x) = -(x+1) - -(x-1) = -x-1 + x-1 = -2$.\nIf $-1 \\leq x \\leq 1$, then $x+1 \\geq 0$ and $x-1 \\leq 0$, so $|x+1| = x+1$ and $|x-1| = -(x-1)$.\nTherefore, $G(x) = x+1 - -(x-1) = x+1 + x-1 = 2x$.\nIf $x \\geq 1$, then $x+1 \\geq 2$ and $x-1 \\geq 0$, so $|x+1| = x+1$ and $|x-1| = x-1$.\nTherefore, $G(x) = x+1 - (x-1) = x+1 - x + 1 = 2$.\nPutting it all together, the range of $G(x)$ is $[-2, 2]$ in interval notation.\nThe answer is: [-2,2]"}
