{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1122844", "question": "def compare_temperatures(temperatures):\n    \"\"\"\n    This exercise is aimed at a Civil Engineer to compare temperatures using a basic for loop.\n\n    Given a list of temperatures, you need to find the number of temperatures above a certain threshold.\n    For each temperature in the list, compare it with the threshold and increment a counter if the temperature is higher.\n\n    Args:\n    temperatures (list): A list of floating-point numbers representing temperatures.\n\n    Returns:\n    int: The count of temperatures above the threshold.\n    \"\"\"", "answer": "# Define the threshold temperature\n    threshold = 30.0\n\n    # Initialize a counter variable to keep track of temperatures above the threshold\n    count = 0\n\n    # Loop through each temperature in the list\n    for temperature in temperatures:\n\n        # Compare the temperature with the threshold\n        if temperature > threshold:\n\n            # Increment the counter variable if the temperature is higher than the threshold\n            count += 1\n\n    return count"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_22136", "question": "When $1000^{100}$ is expanded, how many zeros follow the 1 in the result?", "answer": "To find the number of zeros that follow the 1 in the expansion of $1000^{100}$,\nwe need to find the power of 10 in the prime factorization of $1000^{100}$.\nSince $1000 = 10^3$, we have $1000^{100} = (10^3)^{100} = 10^{300}$.\nTherefore, there are $\\boxed{300}$ zeros that follow the 1 in the expansion of $1000^{100}$.\nThe answer is: 300"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_132794", "question": "Fox jeans regularly sell for $10 a pair and Pony jeans regularly sell for $18 a pair. During a sale, these regular unit prices are discounted at different rates so that a total of $9 is saved by purchasing 5 pairs of jeans: 3 pairs of Fox jeans and 2 pairs of Pony jeans. If the sum of the two discount rates is 22 percent, what is the discount rate on Pony jeans?", "answer": "Let's denote the discount rate on Fox jeans as \\( F \\) and the discount rate on Pony jeans as \\( P \\). We are given that \\( F + P = 22\\% \\).\n\nThe total regular price for 3 pairs of Fox jeans is \\( 3 \\times $10 = $30 \\), and for 2 pairs of Pony jeans is \\( 2 \\times $18 = $36 \\).\n\nThe total savings from the discounts on 3 pairs of Fox jeans and 2 pairs of Pony jeans is $9.\n\nLet's calculate the savings on each type of jeans separately.\n\nFor Fox jeans:\n\\( \\text{Savings on Fox jeans} = 3 \\times $10 \\times \\frac{F}{100} \\)\n\nFor Pony jeans:\n\\( \\text{Savings on Pony jeans} = 2 \\times $18 \\times \\frac{P}{100} \\)\n\nThe total savings is the sum of the savings on Fox jeans and Pony jeans:\n\\( 3 \\times $10 \\times \\frac{F}{100} + 2 \\times $18 \\times \\frac{P}{100} = $9 \\)\n\nNow we can substitute \\( F = 22 - P \\) into the equation:\n\\( 3 \\times $10 \\times \\frac{22 - P}{100} + 2 \\times $18 \\times \\frac{P}{100} = $9 \\)\n\nSimplify and solve for \\( P \\):\n\\( 3 \\times 10 \\times \\frac{22 - P}{100} + 2 \\times 18 \\times \\frac{P}{100} = 9 \\)\n\\( 30 \\times \\frac{22 - P}{100} + 36 \\times \\frac{P}{100} = 9 \\)\n\\( 30 \\times (22 - P) + 36 \\times P = 900 \\)\n\\( 660 - 30P + 36P = 900 \\)\n\\( 6P = 900 - 660 \\)\n\\( 6P = 240 \\)\n\\( P = 240 / 6 \\)\n\\( P = 40 \\)\n\nSo the discount rate on Pony jeans is 40%."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1112438", "question": "One pump drains one-half of a pond in 2.5 hours, and then a second pump starts draining the pond. The two pumps working together finish emptying the pond in one-half hour. How long would it take the second pump to drain the pond if it had to do the job alone?", "answer": "Let's denote the rate at which the first pump drains the pond as \\( R_1 \\) and the rate at which the second pump drains the pond as \\( R_2 \\). The rate is typically in units of the pond per hour.\n\nGiven that the first pump drains one-half of the pond in 2.5 hours, we can write:\n\\[ R_1 = \\frac{1/2 \\text{ pond}}{2.5 \\text{ hours}} \\]\n\\[ R_1 = \\frac{1}{5} \\text{ pond per hour} \\]\n\nNow, when the second pump starts working together with the first pump, they finish the remaining half of the pond in 0.5 hours. The combined rate of the two pumps working together, \\( R_1 + R_2 \\), can be written as:\n\\[ R_1 + R_2 = \\frac{1/2 \\text{ pond}}{0.5 \\text{ hours}} \\]\n\\[ R_1 + R_2 = 1 \\text{ pond per hour} \\]\n\nWe already know that \\( R_1 = 1/5 \\) pond per hour, so we can substitute that into the equation to find \\( R_2 \\):\n\\[ 1/5 + R_2 = 1 \\]\n\\[ R_2 = 1 - 1/5 \\]\n\\[ R_2 = 5/5 - 1/5 \\]\n\\[ R_2 = 4/5 \\text{ pond per hour} \\]\n\nNow, to find out how long it would take the second pump to drain the pond alone, we need to calculate the time it would take for the second pump to drain one whole pond at the rate of \\( 4/5 \\) pond per hour. We can use the formula:\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{\\text{Total Work}}{\\text{Rate}} \\]\n\nSo for the second pump:\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{1 \\text{ pond}}{4/5 \\text{ pond per hour}} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{1}{4/5} \\text{ hours} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{1}{4/5} \\times \\frac{5}{4} \\text{ hours} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{5}{4} \\text{ hours} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Time} = 1.25 \\text{ hours} \\]\n\nTherefore, it would take the second pump 1.25 hours (or 1 hour and 15 minutes) to drain the pond if it had to do the job alone."}
