{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1317103", "question": "A man completes a journey in 40 hours. He travels the first half of the journey at the rate of 20 km/hr and the second half at a different speed. The total journey is 960 km. What is the speed in km/hr for the second half of the journey?", "answer": "Let's denote the speed during the second half of the journey as \\( v \\) km/hr.\n\nThe total distance of the journey is 960 km, so each half of the journey is \\( \\frac{960}{2} = 480 \\) km.\n\nFor the first half of the journey, at 20 km/hr, the time taken is \\( \\frac{480}{20} = 24 \\) hours.\n\nSince the total journey takes 40 hours, the time taken for the second half of the journey is \\( 40 - 24 = 16 \\) hours.\n\nNow, we can find the speed during the second half of the journey using the formula:\n\\[ \\text{Speed} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Time}} \\]\n\nSo, the speed during the second half is:\n\\[ v = \\frac{480}{16} = 30 \\text{ km/hr} \\]\n\nTherefore, the speed for the second half of the journey is 30 km/hr."}
