{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_395852", "question": "Laura took out a charge account at the general store and agreed to pay 9% simple annual interest. She charges a certain amount on her account in January. A year later, she owes $38.15, assuming she does not make any additional charges or payments. How much did she charge on her account in January?", "answer": "To find out how much Laura charged on her account in January, we need to calculate the principal amount (the original amount charged) that, with 9% simple annual interest, would result in a total debt of $38.15 after one year.\n\nLet's denote the original amount charged as \\( P \\). The interest \\( I \\) that Laura would owe after one year at a 9% annual interest rate would be:\n\n\\[ I = P \\times \\text{interest rate} \\times \\text{time} \\]\n\\[ I = P \\times 0.09 \\times 1 \\]\n\\[ I = 0.09P \\]\n\nThe total amount owed after one year, which includes the original amount charged \\( P \\) plus the interest \\( I \\), is $38.15. So we can write:\n\n\\[ P + I = P + 0.09P = 38.15 \\]\n\\[ 1P + 0.09P = 38.15 \\]\n\\[ 1.09P = 38.15 \\]\n\nNow, we solve for \\( P \\) by dividing both sides of the equation by 1.09:\n\n\\[ P = \\frac{38.15}{1.09} \\]\n\nNow, calculate the value of \\( P \\):\n\n\\[ P = \\frac{38.15}{1.09} \\]\n\\[ P \\approx 35 \\]\n\nSo, Laura charged approximately $35 on her account in January."}
