{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1387180", "question": "There were 80 people at a football game on Saturday. On Monday, 20 fewer people were at the football game. On Wednesday, 50 more people were at the game than on Monday. On Friday, there were the same number of people as on Saturday and Monday combined. If their expected total audience at the football game for a week is 350, how many more people attended the games than they had expected?", "answer": "On Monday, 80 - 20 = 60 people attended the game.\nOn Wednesday, 60 + 50 = 110 people attended the game.\nOn Friday, 80 + 60 = 140 people attended the game.\nA total of 80 + 60 + 110 + 140 = 390 people attended the games in a week.\nTherefore, 390 - 350 = 40 people more attended the games than they had expected.\nThe answer is 40"}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_772280", "question": "How would you output the average value of a given list of numbers, considering only even numbers? Further, the solution should ignore any negative numbers in the list.\nlist_int = [2, 7, 15, 25, -2, 4]", "answer": "You can solve this problem using a simple Python program, which calculates the sum of all even and non-negative numbers in the list and then divides it by the count of these numbers:\n\n```python\nlist_int = [2, 7, 15, 25, -2, 4]\n\ndef average_even_positive_numbers(lst):\n    # Filtering out non-even and negative numbers\n    even_and_positive = [n for n in lst if n%2 == 0 and n >= 0]\n    # Handle edge case of no even non-negative numbers\n    if len(even_and_positive) == 0:\n        return None\n    # Compute average\n    return sum(even_and_positive) / len(even_and_positive)\n\naverage = average_even_positive_numbers(list_int)\n\nif average is not None:\n    print('Average of even and non-negative numbers is:', average)\nelse:\n    print('No even non-negative numbers in the list')\n``` \n\nThis program first creates a new list that includes only even and non-negative numbers (i.e., the number is included if its remainder when divided by 2 is 0 and it is greater than or equal to zero). It then returns the sum of these numbers divided by the count of these numbers, which is the definition of average. If there are no even non-negative numbers in the list, the program will return None and print the corresponding message."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_1457946", "question": "The grade point average of one third of the classroom is a certain value; the grade point average of the rest is 66. The grade point average of the whole class is 64. What is the grade point average of one third of the classroom?", "answer": "Let's denote the grade point average (GPA) of one third of the classroom as X. The GPA of the rest of the class (two thirds) is given as 66. The overall GPA of the whole class is 64.\n\nWe can set up the equation based on the weighted average of the two groups (one third and two thirds of the class):\n\n(1/3) * X + (2/3) * 66 = 64\n\nTo solve for X, we first distribute the fractions:\n\n(1/3)X + (2/3)(66) = 64\n\nNow, we multiply both sides of the equation by 3 to eliminate the fractions:\n\n3 * [(1/3)X + (2/3)(66)] = 3 * 64\n\nThis simplifies to:\n\nX + 2(66) = 192\n\nNow, we solve for X:\n\nX + 132 = 192\n\nSubtract 132 from both sides:\n\nX = 192 - 132\n\nX = 60\n\nTherefore, the grade point average of one third of the classroom is 60."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_18449", "question": "Reese had a sum of money in her savings account. She spent a certain percentage of her savings for her expenses in February, 40% of it in March, and $1500 in April. She had $11000 in her savings account and still has $2900 after spending those amounts. What percentage of her savings did she spend in February?", "answer": "Let's denote the initial amount of money Reese had in her savings account as \\( S \\).\n\nIn February, she spent a certain percentage of her savings, which we'll call \\( P \\) (where \\( P \\) is a fraction representing the percentage).\n\nIn March, she spent 40% of her savings, which is \\( 0.40S \\).\n\nIn April, she spent a fixed amount of $1500.\n\nAfter all these expenses, she has $2900 left in her savings account.\n\nSo, the equation representing the situation after all the expenses is:\n\n\\[ S - (PS + 0.40S + 1500) = 2900 \\]\n\nWe also know that she initially had $11000 in her savings account, so \\( S = 11000 \\).\n\nSubstituting \\( S \\) into the equation, we get:\n\n\\[ 11000 - (P \\cdot 11000 + 0.40 \\cdot 11000 + 1500) = 2900 \\]\n\nSimplifying the equation:\n\n\\[ 11000 - (P \\cdot 11000 + 4400 + 1500) = 2900 \\]\n\n\\[ 11000 - P \\cdot 11000 - 4400 - 1500 = 2900 \\]\n\n\\[ 11000 - P \\cdot 11000 = 2900 + 4400 + 1500 \\]\n\n\\[ 11000 - P \\cdot 11000 = 8800 \\]\n\nNow, we isolate \\( P \\cdot 11000 \\):\n\n\\[ P \\cdot 11000 = 11000 - 8800 \\]\n\n\\[ P \\cdot 11000 = 2200 \\]\n\nNow, we solve for \\( P \\):\n\n\\[ P = \\frac{2200}{11000} \\]\n\n\\[ P = \\frac{1}{5} \\]\n\nTo find the percentage, we multiply \\( P \\) by 100:\n\n\\[ P \\times 100 = \\frac{1}{5} \\times 100 \\]\n\n\\[ P = 20\\% \\]\n\nTherefore, Reese spent 20% of her savings in February."}
{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_890825", "question": "A man buys Rs. 52 shares paying 9% dividend. The man wants to have an interest of 12% on his money. What is the market value of each share?", "answer": "To calculate the market value of each share, we need to determine how much the man expects to earn from each share and then compare it to the dividend being paid.\n\nThe man wants to have an interest of 12% on his money. Let's assume he invests Rs. X to buy one share.\n\nHis expected earning from one share = 12% of X = 0.12X\n\nThe actual dividend paid on one Rs. 52 share is 9%. Therefore, the actual earning from one share = 9% of 52 = 0.09 * 52 = Rs. 4.68\n\nNow, we equate the expected earning to the actual earning to find the market value (X) of each share:\n\n0.12X = Rs. 4.68\nX = Rs. 4.68 / 0.12\nX = Rs. 39\n\nTherefore, the market value of each share should be Rs. 39 for the man to get a 12% return on his investment."}
