{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_90901", "question": "It takes John 13 seconds to run 100 meters. He only goes 4 meters in the first second. He then maintains the same speed for the rest of the race. James is 2 m/s faster at the top speed and he can run the first 10 meters in 2 seconds. How long does it take James to run 100 meters?", "answer": "Let's first calculate John's speed after the first second. Since John covers 4 meters in the first second, he has 96 meters left to run (100 meters - 4 meters). He runs this distance in 12 seconds (13 seconds - 1 second). Therefore, John's speed for the rest of the race is:\n\nSpeed = Distance / Time\nSpeed = 96 meters / 12 seconds\nSpeed = 8 meters/second\n\nNow, let's calculate James's speed. We know that James is 2 m/s faster than John at top speed. Therefore, James's top speed is:\n\nJames's speed = John's speed + 2 m/s\nJames's speed = 8 m/s + 2 m/s\nJames's speed = 10 m/s\n\nJames covers the first 10 meters in 2 seconds, so he has 90 meters left to run (100 meters - 10 meters). Since his speed is 10 m/s, we can calculate the time it takes him to run the remaining 90 meters:\n\nTime = Distance / Speed\nTime = 90 meters / 10 m/s\nTime = 9 seconds\n\nNow, we add the time it took James to run the first 10 meters:\n\nTotal time for James = Time for first 10 meters + Time for remaining 90 meters\nTotal time for James = 2 seconds + 9 seconds\nTotal time for James = 11 seconds\n\nTherefore, it takes James 11 seconds to run 100 meters."}
