{"id": "general_infinity_instruct_2300_241661", "question": "a train traveling at 72 kmph crosses a platform in 30 seconds and a man standing on the platform in 20 seconds . what is the length of the platform in meters ?", "answer": "First, let's convert the speed of the train from kilometers per hour (kmph) to meters per second (m/s) because the time is given in seconds. \n\n1 km = 1000 meters\n1 hour = 3600 seconds\n\nSo, 72 kmph is equivalent to:\n72 kmph * (1000 meters / 1 km) * (1 hour / 3600 seconds) = 20 m/s\n\nNow, let's calculate the distance the train covers when passing the man, which is equal to the length of the train itself. Since it takes 20 seconds to pass the man, we can use the formula:\n\nDistance = Speed * Time\n\nDistance (length of the train) = 20 m/s * 20 seconds = 400 meters\n\nNext, we need to find out the distance the train covers when passing the platform, which is the length of the train plus the length of the platform. Since it takes 30 seconds to pass the platform, we can use the same formula:\n\nDistance (length of the train + length of the platform) = 20 m/s * 30 seconds = 600 meters\n\nNow, we can find the length of the platform by subtracting the length of the train from the total distance covered when passing the platform:\n\nLength of the platform = Distance (train + platform) - Length of the train\nLength of the platform = 600 meters - 400 meters = 200 meters\n\nTherefore, the length of the platform is 200 meters."}
